<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Baseball 4thLd-Writethru a0795 06-28 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Baseball, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0795,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Enjoys Baseball Game With Grandson</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 4: ``Bush and,'' to give final score, Baltimore wins
2-1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, an avid baseball fan, took his
13-year-old grandson and the budget director to an American League
Baseball game Wednesday at Baltimore's Memorial Stadium.
   The president and grandson George P. Bush stayed through six
innings of an evening game between the first-place Baltimore Orioles
and third-place Toronto Blue Jays. With them were Budget Director
Richard Darman and his son, Willie, also 13.
   The presidential party left with the score tied 1-1 in the top of
the seventh. The Orioles won it, 2-1.
   Bush and his party sat in a sky box over home plate with Orioles'
owner Eli Jacobs. Bush took off his suitcoat and tie and waved to
the crowd at the beginning of the game.
   The president, who keeps his first-baseman's glove in his Oval
Office desk, was captain of Yale's baseball team in 1948, his senior
year.
   Bush threw out the first ball when he and Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak attended the April 3 season opener between the Orioles
and the Boston Red Sox. This trip, the White House said, Bush was
expected to merely watch the game from a sky box.
   Young George, the son of Jeb and Columba Bush, has been staying
at the White House for several weeks.
 
</TEXT>
