<FIRST>r a AM-LogExports     06-28 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Log Exports,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregonians Approve Export Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregonians voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to
keep Oregon logs at home to preserve mill jobs rather than allow
them to be shipped overseas for premium prices.
   With 8 percent of precincts reporting in unofficial returns,
Measure 2 was passing 43,263, or 92 percent, to 3,701, or 8 percent.
   The measure will amend the state constitution to keep logs cut
from state-owned forests at home for processing, but Congress would
have to adopt enabling legislation before the export ban could go
into effect.
   ``This is the greatest present Oregon could give me trying to get
this bill through,'' said Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore.
   The measure also calls on Congress to permanently ban the export
of logs grown on national forests and other federal timberlands. The
Bush administration has proposed lifting the annual ban on exporting
federal logs to boost revenue by an estimated $200 million.
   Financing for the $800,000 campaign came largely from
non-exporting timber companies afraid that failure of the measure
could have led to a lifting of the ban on federal log exports.
   Federal logs are already in short supply because of court
injunctions barring timber sales in old growth forests that are
critical to the survival of the rare Northern spotted owl.
   The measure drew no organized opposition, but the Pacific Rim
Trade Association complained that supporters have misled the public
about the threat of state log exports to domestic mill jobs.
   Working through the association, large log exporters such as
Weyerhaeuser Co. have concentrated their efforts on Congress, where
they were successful last year in scuttling a bill to allow states
to ban exports of logs grown on state lands.
   The U.S. Forest Service has estimated that federal exports could
send an additional 1 billion board feet of raw timber from Oregon
and Washington forests to Japan, China and Korea.
   About 1.3 billion board feet of Oregon logs, primarily cut on
private lands, were shipped last year out of a statewide harvest of
9 billion board feet.
   Of the state forest harvest of 220 million board feet, about half
was exported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
