<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     06-28 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summer Series Draw Yawns from Nielsen Families</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the midst of summer reruns, the few new
episodes and new series the networks are offering aren't faring
particularly well in the Nielsens.
   NBC did, however, get a top-10 performance last week from the
A.C. Nielsen Co. out of ``The Gifted One,'' a pilot not on the fall
schedule. ``I wouldn't be surprised if it did well enough to be
considered'' as a possible mid-season replacement, said Preston
Beckman, the NBC director of audience research.
   Pete Kowanko starred as a man with mystical powers who is pursued
by a scientist (John Rhys-Davies) seeking to capture him and study
him.
   Of the summer series, CBS' ``Doctor, Doctor'' did the best,
ranking 38th.
   But a new episode of ABC's ``Hooperman'' was 55th. NBC's
``Highway to Heaven'' was 58th, and ABC's ``The Robert Guillaume
Show'' 59th.
   ``Microcops,'' part of CBS' ``Summer Playhouse,'' a series of
pilots that weren't picked up, ranked 69th. And CBS' ``Hard Time on
Planet Earth'' was 63rd.
   NBC won the week ending June 25, its 53rd in a row, with an
average prime-time rating of 12.3 to CBS' 9.3 and ABC's 9.0.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' maintained its place at No. 1. The rest of the
top 10 included ``Cheers'' NBC, ``Dear John'' NBC, which got its
highest ranking to date, ``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``Golden Girls''
NBC, ``A Different World'' NBC, ``The Gifted One'' NBC, ``L.A. Law''
NBC, ``Empty Nest'' NBC and ``Murder, She Wrote'' CBS.
   ABC added ``Coach'' to the top 20. It was tied for 17th, thanks
to a summer time slot on Tuesday behind ``Roseanne.''
   The lowest-rated network shows of the week were: ``Hard Time on
Planet Earth,'' ``Mission Impossible,'' ``Mickey's 60th Birthday,''
``Paradise,'' ``Beauty &amp; the Beast,'' ``Incredible Sunday,'' ``Tour
of Duty,'' ``Microcops,'' ``Have Faith'' and ``The Right of the
People.''
   The news race continued to be neck and neck, with the ``CBS
Evening News'' barely winning the week on a 9.2 rating and 20 share.
``ABC World News Tonight'' had a 9.0 and 20 share, and ``NBC Nightly
News'' had an 8.5 and 19.
   The rating is a percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes in
the United States that have televisions. The share is a percentage
of sets in use.
</TEXT>
