<FIRST>r a PM-OwlCompromise     06-28 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Owl Compromise,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalist Rejection Spurs New Efforts at Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists rejected a deal allowing
timber to flow to Northwest mills while protecting the habitat of
the rare spotted owl, but worked toward a deadline for compromise
with the logging industry.
   Lawmakers hoped to attach a rider to a House spending bill to
establish timber harvest levels for fiscal 1990. The bill is to be
considered Thursday.
   ``I don't think the environmental community really wants to
torpedo this agreement,'' said Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., who met with
conservationists Tuesday. ``I think cool heads can come together.''
   A compromise for saving old growth forest while opening some land
to loggers was offered Saturday at the so-called spotted owl summit
of timber industry representatives, environmentalists, the seven
members of Oregon's congressional delegation and Gov. Neil
Goldschmidt.
   The industry currently is blocked from logging many forest tracts
by federal injunctions brought to protect the old growth forests,
the owl's sole habitat.
   ``We are talking about the extinction of a species and shouldn't
act precipitously,'' said Andy Kerr, conservation director for the
Oregon Natural Resources Council.
   ``Conservationists, like misers, may be hell to live with, but we
make great ancestors.''
   Environmentalists said they supported many aspects of the
compromise but had trouble getting information they needed from the
U.S. Forest Service.
   ``Yesterday we got three different answers to how much has been
cut already and how much is available,'' said Larry Tuttle, Oregon
director of The Wilderness Society. ``I think we need that kind of
baseline information before anybody can proceed much further.''
   The timber industry warned that it could drop its initial
approval of the deal if the cut level was reduced. Industry
representatives claim that up to 18,000 jobs could be lost unless
timber tied up in court battles is freed.
   The proposal called for allowing 8 billion board feet of timber
to be harvested from national forests in Oregon and Washington and 1
billion board feet from Bureau of Land Management forests in Oregon
through Sept. 30, 1990. Some of the logged lands would be old growth
forests, but loggers would accept The Wilderness Society guidelines
for protecting large blocs of the forest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
