<FIRST>r w PM-US-Zaire     06-28 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Zaire,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobutu Visit To Highlight His Role In Angolan Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Mobutu arrival and talks scheduled to begin late morning EDT;
Will be led</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials want to talk with Zaire
President Mobutu Sese Seko about his peacemaking role in Angola but
may downplay his poor human rights record in the first visit by an
African leader during the Bush administration.
   Mobutu was arriving today for three days of talks with the Bush
administration. He had meetings scheduled shortly after his arrival
with Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney.
   On Thursday, Mobutu is to have two hours of talks with President
Bush, including a working lunch.
   Mobutu's visit reflects the importance he holds for the conduct
of American policy in Africa.
   Briefing reporters about the visit, a senior administration
official said Mobutu's role in organizing last week's peace
conference in Zaire between the Angolan government and the
U.S.-backed UNITA rebels would be high on the agenda. Angola and
UNITA signed a cease-fire that will end a 14-year civil war and lead
to talks on power-sharing.
   The U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
American aid for UNITA, much of which has been funneled through
Zaire, will continue until a peace accord is signed.
   The State Department is hoping Mobutu's role in facilitating the
agreement will deflect some of the congressional opposition to
Mobutu over his country's human rights abuses.
   ``We think Zaire's human rights record, while being far from
perfect ... has improved considerably in recent years,'' said the
official. The number of political prisoners has declined, prison
conditions have improved and a human rights ministry has been
established, he said.
   But sentiment in Congress is strongly weighed against Mobutu, and
Rep. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., head of the Black Caucus, has proposed
halting U.S. aid, which is $60 million this year.
   The House has already slashed the administration's request of $9
million for military aid to Zaire next year down to $3 million. The
money is intended for maintenance of U.S.-supplied planes and
equipment, the official said.
   U.S. officials also want to ask Mobutu for his assessment of
recent contacts between the left-leaning government of Mozambique
and the violent RENAMO rebels, he said.
   Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen will travel to
Mozambique's capital of Maputo in July to discuss possible U.S.
involvement in the peacemaking process there, the official said.
   ``I don't think he'll (Mobutu) play a role in Mozambique,'' said
the official. ``He has his hands full with Angola and ... we'd like
him to devote full time to that.''
   Also on the agenda are recent contacts between Zaire and the
apartheid government of South Africa, and the recent agreement Zaire
signed to undertake economic reforms in return for a loan from the
International Monetary Fund.
</TEXT>
