<FIRST>r p PM-CampaignShakeup     06-28 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campaign Shakeup,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Courter Aides Resign Campaign In Midst Of HUD Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. James Courter's top two political
advisers resigned from his gubernatorial campaign over their ties to
the growing scandal of influence peddling within a federal housing
agency.
   Roger Stone and Greg Stevens, two nationally known political
consultants, handed in their resignations Tuesday despite Courter's
repeated denial of links between his campaign and the widening
congressional probe into contracts obtained through the Department
of Housing and Urban Development by prominent Republicans.
   Stone and his firm _ Black, Manafort, Stone and Kelly _ are
resigning as Courter's political strategists. Stevens will step down
as Courter's media adviser.
   Stone said he withdrew from the campaign because of ``unwarranted
recent news coverage'' about his firms ties to the HUD scandal.
Stone said the scandal would distract voters from the Courter
campaign's attempts to spotlight his Democratic opponent, Rep. James
Florio, as the political boss of Camden County. ``We are intent on
preventing Jim Florio and the Democrats from using my association
with the campaign as a club against Jim Courter,'' Stevens said.
   Stone, Stevens and the Courter camp have consistently and curtly
rejected any suggestion of ties to improper activities within HUD,
but the controversy has been dogging the campaign.
   Stone's firm received more than $300,000 in fees under a no-bid
contract for a moderate-income housing project in Cumberland County,
in southern New Jersey. Paul Manafort, who handled the project,
described his own involvement as ``influence peddling.''
   Stevens, who is Gov. Thomas H. Kean's former chief of staff, has
said he made a telephone call on Manafort's behalf to link him up
with New Jersey housing officials.
   Stone has handled both of Gov. Thomas H. Kean's campaigns and
both of President Reagan's New Jersey campaigns. He also ran the
unsuccessful U.S. Senate race by Pete Dawkins last year.
</TEXT>
