<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-GunLegislation     06-28 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gun Legislation,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislation Would Make Handgun Makers Liable for Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia Council on Tuesday
gave preliminary approval to a bill to make handgun manufacturers
and distributors financially liable forinjuries or deaths caused in
shootings.
   The 8-4 vote was on legislation to allow shooting victims and the
families of homicide victims to recover monetary damages from the
manufacturer of a gun used in a shooting, regardless of who was at
fault. If given final approval, it could be the first such law in
the United States.
   Manufacturers around the country generally have not been held
responsible by the courts for gun damage under existing laws. The
new legislation could expose them to hundreds of new lawsuits.
   Council members said they hope the measure will reduce the
availability of firearms in the district, as well as around the
country.
   ``This is not PR,'' said council member William P. Lightfoot,
D-At Large, a proponent of the legislation. ``If you make a
dangerous weapon, we're going to hold you responsible any time it is
used.''
   Richard R. Atkinson Jr., a member of the board of directors of
the National Rifle Association and president of the District of
Columbia Firearms Association, said the council's action could have
a negative impact on home rule by giving its federal opponents
additional ammunition with which to attack the district's local
government.
   ``I think if the city council continues with this kind of
meddling in other states' affairs, it will go down in history as the
city council that lost home rule,'' he said.
   During the council debate over the legislation Tuesday, opponents
of the handgun bill raised similar concerns.
   Council member Betty Ann Kane, who voted against the bill, called
it a ``knee-jerk'' response to the violence on the street. She said
she doesn't understand ``why we are taking away individual
responsibility'' for the commission of shooting crimes.
</TEXT>
