<DOCNO> AP890628-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ThirdWorldDebt     06-28 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third World Debt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed, Congress Add Pressure Banks to Join Debt Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators and members of Congress are
threatening to trim the profits of the nation's biggest banks if
they continue resisting ``voluntary'' reductions in debt owed them
by Third World countries.
   The Federal Reserve is the latest to put the pressure on, telling
a House subcommittee it will order the banks to set aside more
reserves to cover possible losses from the loans unless there is
progress soon on Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady's debt reduction
plan.
   ``Without further cooperation between borrowers and lenders,
credit quality will continue to deteriorate as more countries become
unable or unwilling to service their bank debts,'' William Taylor,
the Fed's director of banking supervision and regulation, said
Tuesday.
   ``In such an event, further significant increases in reserves
will clearly be required,'' Taylor told the House Banking
subcommittee on international development, finance, trade and
monetary policy.
   The panel's chairman, Del. Walter Fauntroy, D-D.C., and Rep. John
LaFalce, D-N.Y., have introduced separate bills that would require
banks to double their reserves for Third World loan losses. Such a
move could cut the earnings of those banks by $20 billion.
   ``If there is one lesson we have learned from the savings and
loan crisis, it's that we must require adequate reserves on
high-risk loans,'' said LaFalce.
   In addition, Fauntroy would prohibit banks that do not
participate in the Brady plan from taking any tax losses on the
loans if and when they are declared in default.
   U.S. commercial banks now hold $70.7 billion of some $340 billion
in troubled Third World loans but have set aside reserves of only
$23 billion to cover them, most of it in the past two years.
   The General Accounting Office said Tuesday that based on the
discounted value of the loans, regulators should be requiring
reserves of nearly $50 billion instead of the $4.9 billion now
mandated.
   Allan Mendelowitz, director of trade and finance issues for the
GAO, said the Federal Reserve and the comptroller of the currency
now require reserves on only about 16 percent of the loans owed by
countries with problems servicing their debt.
   And no reserves are required for covering possible losses on a
total of $59.5 billion of the debt carrying a high level of risk or
in arrears, he said. The GAO estimated the value of those loans if
sold on the secondary market at only $23.6 billion.
   Brady's plan calls for reducing Third World debt by 20 percent.
It asks private banks to effectively forgive a portion of the loans
in exchange for promises that government-backed international
lending agencies such as the World Bank will guarantee interest
payments on the remaining balances.
   But in its first major test with Mexico, the plan has run into
stiff resistance among commercial banks.
   After adopting wide-scale austerity programs in the wake of
falling oil prices demanded by lenders, Mexico is now seeking a 55
percent reduction in the nearly $70 billion it owes private
creditors.
   The commercial banks countered that plea with an offer of a 15
percent reduction. Talks between the two parties are continuing.
   But without a general agreement by July 14, when the Paris
economic summit of major industrialized nations opens,
administration officials fear Brady's debt reduction plan _ like
that of his predecessor, James A. Baker III _ may come unraveled.
   Debt-ridden poor countries claim a 20 percent reduction is not
enough to allow them to lift up their economies.
   And other lender nations are skeptical at the plan's ultimate
reliance upon taxpayer assistance through the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund to guarantee private banks against
further losses.
   ``Time is running short and uncertainties appear to be
increasing,'' said Taylor.
</TEXT>
