<FIRST>r w PM-GunLiability     06-28 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gun Liability,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislation Would Make Handgun Makers Liable for Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Handgun manufacturers and distributors would be
financially liable for injuries or deaths caused in shootings, under
a measure awaiting final action by the District of Columbia Council.
   On an 8 to 4 vote Tuesday, the council voted to allow shooting
victims and the families of homicide victims to recover monetary
damages from the manufacturer of a gun used in a shooting,
regardless of who was at fault.
   If given final approval, the measure would be the first such law
in the United States.
   Council members said they hope the measure will reduce the
availability of firearms in the district, as well as around the
country.
   ``This is not P.R.,'' said William P. Lightfoot, an at-large
council member who backs the legislation. ``If you make a dangerous
weapon, we're going to hold you responsible any time it is used.''
   Richard R. Atkinson Jr., a member of the board of directors of
the National Rifle Association and president of the District of
Columbia Firearms Association, warned the council that its action
could harm home rule for the district. Such a law could give federal
opponents new ammunition to attack the district's local government,
he said.
   ``I think if the city council continues with this kind of
meddling in other states' affairs, it will go down in history as the
city council that lost home rule,'' Atkinson said.
   Council member Betty Ann Kane, who voted against the bill, called
it a ``knee-jerk'' response to street violence. She said she does
not understand ``why we are taking away individual responsibility''
for gun-related crimes.
</TEXT>
