<FIRST>r a PM-HUD-Georgia     06-28 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Georgia,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Case Included in Allegations of HUD Scandals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers are being sued for $7.5 million by
HUD for allegedly failing to turn over $1.6 million from
agency-acquired single-family homes to the government.
   The lawsuit alleges that David and Robert Martin of Atlanta,
escrow agents for the sales, failed to turn over the money between
October 1984 and May 1987.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr said an audit leading to the lawsuit
was begun in May 1987 and revealed that government losses reached
$2.5 million.
   Barr and Raymond Buday Jr., the U.S. Department of Housing and
Urban Development's regional counsel, said the investigation
revealed that false documents were filed to mask the non-payment.
   The Martins' lawyers contend the money was paid but cannot be
traced in Washington because of sloppy government bookkeeping.
   The Martins are not charged with a crime.
   ``The nature of the case lent itself to a civil suit,'' Barr said
Tuesday.
   He said there are related criminal investigations pending, but
declined to say if they involved the Martins.
   The homes in question were repossessed by HUD after owners
defaulted on Federal Housing Administration loans.
   There are several investigations into missing funds including
major ones in Indianapolis, Denver, Philadelphia and the Washington,
D.C., area. Investigators say the cases appear unrelated.
   Critics contend the problems stem from incompetence and
influence-peddling at high levels of HUD during the Reagan
administration.
</TEXT>
