<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council Meets on Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Economic Policy Council is trying to
determine whether to extend steel import curbs for five more years.
   The curbs expire Sept. 30 and President Bush is expected to issue
a decision that tries to mollify both sides.
   In 1984, the Reagan administration negotiated five-year,
product-by-product ``voluntary restraint agreements'' with 29
nations, including Japan, South Korea, Brazil and the European
Community, to limit the flow of steel into the United States.
   Three days before last November's election, Bush pledged to renew
the restraints in some form.
   Opponents of the curbs are led by a coalition of U.S.
manufacturers concerned about high steel prices. Supporters say the
restrictions help U.S. industry.
