<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Report Challenges Shoreham Closure; Seabrook Sirens OK'ed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operating the controversial Shoreham nuclear
power plant on Long Island would be cheaper that shutting it down,
contrary to an analysis by state regulators, according to a Senate
staff study.
   The analysis was released Tuesday as the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission's Atomic Safety and Licensing Board decided it was
acceptable to use pole-mounted sirens on trucks to notify nearby
residents of an emergency at the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power
plant, the other completed but not operating reactor in the
Northeast.
   The state of Massachusetts and its towns in the evacuation zones
have refused to cooperate in emergency planning, and Massachusetts
Deputy Attorney General Stephen Jonas said the state would appeal
the decision.
   The Senate report, prepared for the Energy and Natural Resources
Committee, concluded that Shoreham's operation would save $750
million in real economic costs over the first 15 years of its life.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>FCC Gives AT&amp;T the OK for New Pricing Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
turned down a request to delay a new pricing scheme scheduled to go
into effect July 1 for the nation's largest long-distance company,
AT&amp;T.
   The requests for a stay had been filed in June by the Puerto Rico
Telephone Co. and La Telefonica Larga Distancia, which had said the
new plan to limit the prices American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. can
charge would put the two companies at a competitive disadvantage.
   But the FCC, in a decision made public Tuesday, concluded that
the companies failed to provide adequate reasons for a stay and the
public would benefit from the new pricing.
   AT&amp;T last month told the commission it would lower its prices by
$140 million on July 1. The price cap lets AT&amp;T, which in 1988
controlled 68 percent of the U.S. long-distance market, raise rates
3 percent less than the rate of inflation in three categories of
service: residential and small business; 800 calls; and other
business services, mainly for large customers.
