<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Hills     06-28 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Hills,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ms. Hills Sought HUD Funds for Client</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills, a former
secretary of Housing and Urban Development, lobbied her old
department on behalf of a real estate firm trying to win federal
subsidies, her spokeswoman confirmed.
   ``They hired her because of her expertise. I don't see a story in
it,'' Clair Buchan said Tuesday night.
   Ms. Hills represented the company, Swezy Realty, in 1987 and 1988
when she was in private practice as a lawyer in Washington.
   The two projects were in Florida's Dade and Broward counties.
   Ms. Buchan said she believed one project won funds and one was
not approved, and she did not know their names or which was
successful. She also said she did not know how much money was
sought, or what Ms. Hills' fee was.
   The New York Times reported in its editions today that Ms. Hills
reported a fee of at least $5,000 from Swezy in her January
financial disclosure form.
   Ms. Hills is the first prominent Republican in the Bush
administration known to have acted as a lobbyist for developers
seeking HUD ``moderate rehabilitation'' funds under the Reagan
administration. The program is being investigated by Congress
following revelations that well-connected developers won tens of
millions of dollars in aid.
   Many Republican campaign advisers and former officials out of
office such as former Interior Secretary James Watt and former
Massachusetts Sen. Edward Brooke won six-figure fees for telephone
calls to HUD officials on behalf of their clients.
   Many of these consultants had no particular expertise in housing.
</TEXT>
