<FIRST>r a PM-SewerSurvivor     06-28 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sewer Survivor,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girl Rescued After More Than 12 Hours in Storm Drain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after a 7-year-old girl was swept into a
storm sewer, rescuers gave up plans to search for her in the
fast-flowing water and her mother abandoned hope.
   But Latricia Reese managed to cling to cracks in the lining of
the sewer for 12 hours while the flood waters from Tropical Storm
Allison swirled around her.
   ``It was a horrible night and a terrible storm, but we found a
rainbow at the end,'' said Karen Resse after two construction
workers found her daughter.
   ``I gave up most hope and everybody kept telling me not to give
it up, but I did,'' Mrs. Reese said Tuesday, while Latricia rested
in a hospital bed and watched cartoons.
   ``I just held on to the crack in the cement,'' Latricia said,
complaining that mosquitos and ants bothered her throughout her
ordeal.
   Latricia, her hands white and wrinkled and her body covered with
scrapes and bruises, was suffering mild shock Tuesday but was
reported in good condition at Humana Hospital-Southmore, said
spokeswoman Ramona Branch.
   The 4-foot-tall Latricia was playing in a flooded ditch near her
home around 7:30 p.m. Monday when her cousin saw her lose her
footing and vanish into an 18-inch concrete culvert.
   ``She spent the entire night in the city's major sewer system
with all that flood water coming in on her, and hardly had a
scratch,'' said Fire Department spokesman Mike Warnke. ``It's just a
miracle that she could still be alive.''
   When the police diving team was called out, the water was still
flowing at a rate they believed too hazardous to risk entering the
unfamiliar storm sewage system. Police thought the girl would have
been swept to where the sewer system empties into a bayou, Warnke
said.
   ``The diving team told me they can't do any more, it's too
dangerous for them. They told my friend they thought they should get
me a pastor because I would need it and it didn't look too good,''
Mrs. Reese said.
   She and a sister walked around a nearby bayou in search of the
girl at daylight Tuesday. Other relatives enlisted the help of two
construction workers checking sewer lines who removed manhole covers
near the spot where the girl disappeared and found her in the sewer
about 8 a.m.
   ``We used a flashlight and saw a little figure about 30 feet
under the street,'' said Timothy Gabrysch, who went into the drain
Tuesday morning. ``It was pitch dark and she couldn't see anything.
When she saw us, she ran to us.
   ``It's an experience I guess you can't explain. I have no idea
how she stayed there. It's pretty nasty down there. There's all
kinds of debris down there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
