<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Strike     06-28 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Strike,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Railroads Again Immobilized by One-Day Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike immobilized all of Britain's railroads
today and virtually all of London's subway network, forcing millions
of commuters to drive, cycle, walk or ride buses to work.
   It was the second 24-hour strike in eight days by 75,000 national
railroad workers and the eighth unofficial walkout in 12 weeks by
the capital's 10,500 subway workers.
   Traffic jams in London started two hours early and traffic ``is
definitely heavier than usual,'' said Scotland Yard spokeswoman
Alison Bland.
   Birmingham, Liverpool, Manchester, Edinburgh and Glasgow also
reported earlier rush hours with more traffic congestion than
normal, the Automobile Association said.
   Last Wednesday, there was little of the traffic chaos that might
have been expected from a triple-barreled strike that hit the
national railroad and London's buses and subways. Many commuters
carefully planned their journeys, and others simply stayed at home.
   This week, major companies again hired fleets of coaches to bring
in staff, and London hotels were full of employees spending the
night in the city to beat the strike.
   The 248-station subway system carries 2.7 million passengers a
day, while rail services are used by some 2 million people.
   A sharply reduced subway service was operating on two of London's
10 subway lines, said London Underground spokesman David Morris.
   London's buses, which carry 3.2 million people daily, appeared to
be working normally today, and special shuttle services were added
between Victoria Station in central London and the southern suburb
of Wimbledon, where the two-week lawn tennis championships opened
Monday.
   ``I think it's absolutely disgraceful that people in the
transport unions don't think about their fellow citizens,'' Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher told Sky News, the cable television
network.
   ``It's the public sector unions that are the problem ... Those
people are there to serve the public but they don't,'' she said.
   The National Union of Railwaymen is striking against state-owned
British Rail's offer of a 7 percent wage hike, and union leader
Jimmy Knapp is demanding a pay rise of at least 10 percent.
   The subway workers want a $99 weekly increase to operate without
a guard. Management is offering $46 a week plus 14 days extra annual
vacation, but is tying the raise to increase productivity.
   The union plans another one-day strike on July 5 unless British
Rail raises its pay offer.
</TEXT>
