<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0404EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Thornburgh-CivilRights Bjt   06-28 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thornburgh-Civil Rights, Bjt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Leaders Urge Greater White House Commitment to Civil Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush seems more interested in defending
the flag than defending the ideas the flag represents, say civil
rights leaders who heard a speech by Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh.
   In his address Tuesday to Operation PUSH, Thornburgh said the
Bush administration wouldn't immediately pursue legislation to
overturn controversial U.S. Supreme Court rulings on job
discrimination.
   Thornburgh said the administration wanted to first assess the
impact of the high court rulings on anti-discrimination laws.
   Jesse Jackson, founder of the Chicago-based Operation PUSH,
expressed disappointment with Thornburgh's ``wait-and-see'' message.
He and others contrasted it with Bush's immediate call for a
constitutional amendment to set aside last week's Supreme Court
ruling nullifying flag desecration laws in 48 states.
   ``We cannot help but notice the haste with which Bush has rushed
to defend the flag, and his lack of haste in defending the substance
that flag stands for, which is equality under the law and
fairness,'' Jackson said after Thornburgh's speech.
   In his speech, Thornburgh said the administration ``is fully
committed to eliminating every form of discrimination in our
society.''
   But while acknowledging that some people view the recent high
court decisions as a retreat in the battle for civil rights, he
urged caution.
   ``I recognize, as does the president, that the full effect of
these rulings will not be felt until they are applied in new
cases,'' the attorney general said.
   ``In fact, the president has asked that I monitor the
implementation of these opinions in the lower courts to assess their
impact on equal employment opportunities and, if needed, to suggest
any legislative or executive action that might be required to
resolve inequities,'' he said.
   Bush made similar comments in Washington earlier in the day.
   ``I am strongly committed to equal opportunity for all
Americans,'' Bush said, adding that he had been advised in a Justice
Department report that the Supreme Court decisions didn't undermine
those principles.
   Thornburgh received a generally polite but cool reception from
the audience of about 200.
   Several delegates to the convention said they believed Thornburgh
was speaking for Bush, and not for himself.
   ``Clearly, the Dick Thornburgh that I heard this morning was not
the Dick Thornburgh I have known in the past,'' said Richard
Hatcher, former mayor of Gary, Ind. ``The only conclusion I can
reach is that it was a speech that was crafted at the White House.
I, personally, felt he was a little uncomfortable with it.''
   Hatcher added: ``For the president to call for a constitutional
amendment _ that's a pretty serious step. I can't help but feel that
he is showing greater compassion regarding an inanimate object _
precious though the flag is to all of us _ than he is to some 22
million citizens of this country.''
   Jackson, who declined to criticize Thornburgh, called for an
effort to persuade Congress to enact legislation that would set
aside the recent high court decisions.
   The Supreme Court has invalidated minority set-aside quotas for
local public works contracts, made it harder for plaintiffs to prove
employment discrimination and given white males the right to
challenge affirmative action plans previously approved by courts.
   During a discussion after Thornburgh's speech, Rutgers University
law professor Arthur Kinoy loudly compared the administration's
``wait-and-see response'' to the reaction after 19th century Supreme
Court decisions that dismantled Reconstruction legislation.
   The high court decisions included the 1896 ruling that upheld
``separate but equal'' facilities for blacks and whites.
   Thornburgh responded angrily.
   ``You are free to question the integrity and commitment of the
president and the attorney general,'' Thornburgh said. ``But I don't
think it adds to the kind of dialogue that we are seeking to engage
in to reduce this to the level of shouting matches.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
