<FIRST>r a PM-DroppedBomb     06-28 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dropped Bomb,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Rack Out of Adjustment Caused F-16 to Drop Bomb Accidentally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRANTLEY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force officials blame a bomb rack that
was out of adjustment and contained a worn-out part for an accident
last month in which a jet fighter dropped a live, 500-pound bomb
accidentally.
   The bomb exploded May 4 near the small west Georgia town of
Brantley and flattened some trees, but caused no injuries or major
damage.
   The Air Force subsequently has tested the bomb rack on the F-16
jet and regularly replaced the suspect part. But the planes will
continue to fly practice bombing runs into Fort Benning, passing
over the Marion County area east of the post.
   ``We're looking at alternate ways of getting there. ... We've
discussed that. But no decision has been made,'' Col. Joe Prater,
commander of the 347th Tactical Fighter Wing, based at Moody Air
Force Base near Valdosta, said Tuesday.
   The bomb exploded 40 feet above the ground when it hit a tree,
scarring and knocking down trees for 100 yards in every direction.
   A summary of the findings of an investigation of the accident
undertaken by Moody Air Force Base officials was released Tuesday in
Washington, D.C.
   Prater, who oversaw the probe, said the cause likely was the
alignment of the bomb rack and the likely deterioration of a
rubberized ``O-ring'' that may have caused the bomb to get hung up
and then fall unexpectedly.
</TEXT>
