<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0458EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cuba Bjt   06-28 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba, Bjt,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban War Hero Admits Treason, May Face Firing Squad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a military tribunal have called for the
court-martial and execution of a highly decorated senior general who
admitted to trafficking in cocaine, ivory, diamonds and other
contraband.
   Gen. Arnaldo Ochoa, 57, told the panel of his peers that he had
betrayed the revolution he held so dear but that none of his actions
were meant to discredit it or the government of Fidel Castro.
   State-run television has broadcast segments of the hearing before
the 47 generals and admirals that began Sunday, including a
30-minute statement by Ochoa, who was charged with masterminding
smuggling operations run by officers.
   Cuban media said viewers unaccustomed to such public show trials
were transfixed by the proceedings against one of Cuba's most
decorated war heroes.
   Ochoa received one of his country's highest honors for his work
as commander of Cuban troops in Angola in 1987-88, where Cuba
supported the Marxist government against Western-backed rebels.
   ``If this (death) sentence were to come, which could even even
include a firing squad, my last throught will be for Fidel and our
great revolution,'' the general told the tribunal in the statement
broadcast Tuesday night.
   Throughout the hearing, Ochoa looked dejected, sometimes toying
with a piece of string as members of the panel talked.
   On Tuesday, the tribunal ruled that Ochoa had committed treason
and recommended he be court-martialed.
   Witnesses who testified during the hearing said that, beginning
as early as 1985, Ochoa was in league with Colombian drug bosses and
had helped turn Cuba into a way station for U.S.-bound cocaine.
   The government news agency Prensa Latina said Tuesday that
officers who testified before the tribunal all said Ochoa had
persuaded them to raise dollars ``at all costs'' to help this
Communist nation's troubled economy.
   In addition to drug trafficking, Ochoa is accused of overseeing a
thriving black market trade in supplies provided to the troops he
commanded in Angola.
   Prensa Latina said he traded fuel, dried fish and beef, weapons,
electronics and other supplies for diamonds and dollars.
   The witnesses said some of the money he made ended up a
Panamanian bank account. Some was used to buy refrigerators and
stereos for Ochoa and other officers, they said.
   Some of the generals on the tribunal were angered by the
testimony, while others choked backed tears.
   Some younger officers said they rose through the ranks regarding
Ochoa as a hero. Older officers mentioned their 30-year friendships
with Ochoa and their common combat experience dating to the
guerrilla war in the Sierra Maestra that ended with the 1959 victory
of the Castro-led revolution.
   Nearly to a man, however, they recommended that Ochoa be stripped
of his rank and honors and be dishonorably discharged. Most asked
that he be given the maximum penalty _ death by firing squad.
   ``One pays for treason with one's life,'' said Ochoa, whose voice
grew husky at times.
   He told the panel he was ashamed of his actions and recognized
his mistakes, but denied he wanted to embarrass the government: ``It
was to be expected that the enemy would try to use this. But nothing
is further from the truth than this having been for political
motives.''
   The general also denied the Castros or any other top-level Cuban
government officials were involved in drug-running.
   ``Neither the commander-in-chief (Fidel Castro) nor the (defense)
minister, nor the party, nor the armed forces, ever had anything to
do with this ... I wanted to make this clear before you,'' Ochoa
told his colleagues.
   Authorities had said the court-martial proceedings might begin
Tuesday, but by early today there was no word that they had begun.
   Defense Minister Raul Castro, brother of the president, testified
that Ochoa's punishment should ``set an example.''
   The tribunal recommended that the ``full weight of the law'' be
applied because of the ``extreme seriousness of his crimes.''
   Capt. Jorge Martinez Valdez, Ochoa's assistant, had testified
that Ochoa began laundering money with Panamanians and Colombians in
1985.
   He said Ochoa had direct contacts with leaders of the Medellin
cartel, the world's largest cocaine-smuggling operation. He said the
Colombian drug lords ``thought that we were official representatives
of Cuba.''
</TEXT>
