<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-LogExports     06-28 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Log Exports,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Log Export Ban Moves to Congress After Voter Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate over the export of logs grown on
state and federal forests in Oregon shifts to Congress after voters
gave overwhelming support to a measure intended to save jobs at
local mills.
   The measure, which would ban the export of logs cut from
state-owned forests, will become effective only if Congress adopts
enabling legislation. The ban would not effect logs already
processed into lumber.
   The measure also calls on Congress to permanently ban the export
of logs grown on the national forests and other federal timberlands.
The Bush administration has proposed lifting the annual ban on
exporting federal logs to boost federal revenue by an estimated $200
million.
   In Tuesday's election, a count of 99 percent of the votes showed
the measure passing with 421,991, or 90 percent, to 44,604, or 10
percent.
   ``This is the greatest present Oregon could give me trying to get
this bill through,'' said Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., adding he has
lined up 20 co-sponsors for the bill on federal log exports and 16
for the bill on state exports.
   Financing for the $800,000 Citzens to Save Oregon Jobs campaign
came largely from non-exporting timber companies afraid that failure
of the measure could have led to a lifting of the ban on federal log
exports.
   Weyerhaeuser Co. spokesman Kelly Conover said the proposal to
keep logs grown on Oregon state forests exclusively for use in
Oregon mills faced constitutional problems because it created a
barrier to interstate commerce.
   Conover said counties and school districts receiving revenues
from the sale of logs grown on state forests were likely to go to
court to protest the loss of the premium prices paid by buyers from
Japan, China and Korea.
   ``The campaign spent $1.5 million and failed to tell Oregonians
what their real problem is for the industry, which is federal timber
supply,'' Conover said.
   Federal logs are already in short supply because of court
injunctions barring timber sales in old growth forests that
environmentalists say are critical to the survival of the rare
Northern spotted owl.
   The U.S. Forest Service has estimated that lifting the ban on
federal log exports could send an additional 1 billion board feet of
raw timber from Oregon and Washington forests to Japan, China and
Korea.
   About 1.3 billion board feet of logs from Oregon, primarily cut
on private lands, were exported last year out of a statewide harvest
of 9 billion board feet. Of the state forest harvest of 220 million
board feet, about half was exported.
   The measure drew no organized opposition, but the Pacific Rim
Trade Association complained that supporters misled the public about
the threat of state log exports to domestic mill jobs.
</TEXT>
