<DOCNO> AP890628-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-ArmenianQuake     06-28 0823</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Armenian Quake,0848</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Months After Quake, Armenian Tragedy Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One by one they emerged from the airport
terminal, most leaning heavily on crutches with just one leg. They
are victims of a tragedy that began almost seven months ago as the
earth shook under Armenia.
   Bound for surgery in Israel, these survivors of the Dec. 7
earthquake that killed 25,000 people and injured thousands more are
still haunted by visions of collapsing buildings.
   They bear the scars of emergency surgery and are left with stumps
that promise a life as social misfits.
   ``I want my left leg to heal, so that I would have at least one
leg, and I want to be able to walk normally like young women do. I
want to be able to do everything at home, to be a good housewife,''
said Alyona Berchuliak.
   Berchuliak, an attractive 19-year-old with dark hair, had bigger
plans. She was a graduate student working on a construction site and
planned a career as a construction site manager.
   But that was before she was trapped in the ruins of a nine-story
dormitory in Leninakan, Armenia's second-largest city.
   ``We finished our post-graduate practice and were gathering our
belongings to return home when the earthquake started,'' said
Berchuliak.
   ``We tried to run out, but the door was stuck, the lock was
broken.''
   Now confined to a wheelchair, Berchuliak lost her right leg.
Doctors diagnosed multiple fractures in her left leg, and she has
suffered from kidney complications.
   Unemployed, Berchuliak was recognized as an ``invalid of the
first group'' by the state, which entitled her to a monthly 75-ruble
pension, about $10 on the Soviet black market.
   ``I am sorry, but it's impossible to live on that,'' she said.
   Even so, Berchuliak is more fortunate than some. She was among 61
earthquake survivors, 49 of whom are amputees, who were flown to
Israel for medical treatment Tuesday on ``Mission Healing,'' which
is funded by the American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee.
   Aryeh Cooperstock, an American who coordinated the project, said
many of the amputees are suffering the effects of inadequate,
hastily performed emergency surgery.
   ``They did the best they could under the circumstances,'' he
said. ``But in order to fit prosthetic limbs, other preparatory
surgery has to be done.''
   Israeli officials saw the mercy mission, in which a jetliner of
the national El Al airlines flew to Soviet Union for the first time,
as a further thaw in relations.
   ``This definitely shows we are experiencing a new relationship
with the Soviet Union,'' said Health Minister Yaakov Tzur, who met
the mercy flight at the airport Tuesday night.
   Moscow cut diplomatic relations with Israel after the 1967 Middle
East war in a show of solidarity with Arab nations. The Soviets are
also the major arms supplier for Israel's Arab enemies.
   Arieh Levin, head of the Israeli consular delegation in Moscow,
suggested there was a struggle in the Kremlin between pro-Arab
officials and those favoring closer ties with Israel.
   ``Our friends in the (Soviet) leadership are looking for signs of
good will from Israel in order to build on them toward an
amelioration of the Soviet policy towards Israel,'' Levin said.
   Narine Balayan, social welfare minister for the Republic of
Armenia, told reporters at a reception in Yerevan ``I hope the time
will come when planes like yours will land in Yerevan without any
disaster having prompted their visit.''
   About 40 other amputees from Armenia have been flown to Western
countries for treatment. Armenian officials said the Soviet Union
cannot produce prosthetic limbs of the same quality.
   The Soviet Union has plans to build factories to make articial
arms and legs with the help of West Germany and donations from
Lebanese Armenians. But the estimated 500 quake survivors with
missing limbs may wait for long to get prostheses without treatment
abroad.
   ``Some of the amputees have already received prostheses in the
United States. This group is now leaving for Israel, and another
group is to go abroad in autumn,'' said the republic's deputy social
welfare minister, Zaven Manuchian.
   ``We don't want the foreign aid to be a one-time action. We want
to be able to produce prostheses ourselves according to the world
standards,'' he said, speaking outside the red-brick airport
terminal as crippled survivors slowly struggled to the waiting the
Boeing 757.
   The survivors may eventually receive artificial limbs and find
their way back into society, but some of their wounds will never
heal.
   Like those of Egor Khatchaturian, 17, who lost 18 classmates when
his school collapsed in the city of Spitak. Khatchaturian, who lost
his left leg, burst into tears as he recalled the terrible moment of
their death.
   Sylvia Gevorkian, 51, kept adding the word ``killed'' to the list
of relatives when asked if she had lost family in the quake.
   ``Daughter killed,'' she said in a lifeless voice.
``Granddaughter killed...''
</TEXT>
