<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SunkenTreasure     06-28 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sunken Treasure,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pile of Rubble Could Be Sunken 17th-Century Galleon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasure hunters and archaeologists are
hoping a ship found off the Florida Keys in 1,500 feet of water will
turn out to be the remains of a treasure-laden, 17th-century Spanish
galleon.
   Seahawk Deep Ocean Technology of Tampa today planned to disclose
videotapes made by remote-controlled cameras of the shipwreck. The
ship could be the Nuestra Senora de la Merced, a Spanish galleon
believed to have vanished during a hurricane in 1622.
   ``It's worth a fortune in history,'' said Greg Stemm, a Tampa
businessman who hopes to recover the riches.
   Another galleon that sank in the same hurricane, the Nuestra
Senora de Atocha, was found laden with gold and silver by treasure
hunter Mel Fisher in 1985, about 50 miles north of Stemm's discovery.
   Jim Miller, Florida's state archaeologist who already viewed the
videos of the ship wreck, said the find's historical value is
significant because, although the ship's structure has collapsed,
its cargo, wood and organic materials have been well-preserved.
   ``This particular wreck is more like a time capsule. It sank and
it hasn't been touched since that time,'' Miller said.
   Last weekend, salvors aboard Stemm's 85-foot research vessel
Seahawk retrieved the ship's bell that will be used to strengthen
his company's federal admiralty claim to the wreck. Admiralty law
governs shipwrecks found in international waters _ in this case,
more than 12 miles from the U.S. coast.
   By summer's end, the salvors will begin a full-scale operation to
retrieve the fragile artifacts and confirm the ship's identity.
   So far, they have discovered a number of jars that could be
filled with wine, food and other commodities. The artifacts looked
to be piled in a mound about 100-by-30 feet, Miller said.
   If Stemm's research proves correct, the wreck he discovered could
hold a treasure worth millions.
   ``We're going to profit tremendously,'' said Stemm, 32, co-owner
of a deep-sea research company that discovered the sunken vessel in
April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
