<FIRST>r i PM-BoyPilot     06-28 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boy Pilot,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Too Busy to Meet with American Boy Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is too busy
to meet an 11-year-old Californian who is flying around the world on
a ``friendship flight,'' a Soviet sponsor of the trip said today.
   But Tony Aliengena will still have the chance to pass along a
scroll with signatures of 250,000 American schoolchildren to a
Soviet official, said Valery Nikolayev, director of the Foundation
for Social Inventions.
   Nikolayev said in a telephone interview that Tony and his family
would meet with Valery Tzibukh, chairman of the Soviet parliament's
committee on youth, who would pass along the scroll to Gorbachev.
   Kremlin officials said ``this is just a bad time,'' Nikolayev
said, with Gorbachev involved in the formation of the new Soviet
government.
   Tony arrived in Moscow on Monday and has already visited Red
Square, where West German teen-ager Matthias Rust gained worldwide
fame _ and more than a year in Soviet prison _ by landing a
single-engined Cessna there in May 1987 after penetrated Soviet air
defenses.
   When his 47-day round-the-world trip is completed, Tony will
present a friendship scroll signed by Soviet youngsters to President
Bush, who has already agreed to meet him at journey's end.
   Tony, accompanied by his father, began the global flight in his
blue-and-white Cessna Centurion June 5 from California.
   His flight plan will take him 19,000 miles around the world in
short hops averaging three hours each.
   From Moscow, Tony is scheduled to fly on to the Volga River city
of Kuibyshev about 400 miles away, and eventually across the Bering
Strait to Alaska before heading home to San Juan Capistrano.
</TEXT>
