<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   06-28 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0500,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Legislature Confirms Cabinet Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with confirmation of Cabinet nominees.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Soviet legislature today confirmed its
first Cabinet members after rejecting, for the first time in Soviet
history, a slate of nominees for the government positions.
   One of the three confirmed today was approved only after
promising more radical changes than he had earlier espoused.
   Under questioning from the 542-member Supreme Soviet, Yuri
Maslyukov, chairman of the government planning agency Gosplan, said
his agency would drastically reduce central planning of the economy.
He was then confirmed as both the new Gosplan chairman and first
deputy premier.
   Lev Voronin, 61, a bureaucrat in the state supply committee, was
confirmed as a first deputy premier in charge of general matters.
   Economist Leonid Abalkin was confirmed as a deputy premier and
head of the new economic reform commission.
   On Tuesday, Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov withdrew seven of his Cabinet
nominees after the newly elected legislature refused to support them
_ a first in Soviet history.
   Six of the nominees were rejected in first-ever confirmation
hearings last week by committees of the Supreme Soviet, which this
year replaced the old rubber-stamp legislature. The previous
legislature did not have the power to confirm or reject top
government officials.
   Ryzhkov also withdrew his nominee, who was not identified, to
head the Ministry of Instrument-Making, Automation Equipment and
Control Systems, and said he had no nominee to lead the government
environmental agency.
   Deputy Igor Griazin of Estonia said he had expected more
controversy over the 52-year-old Maslyukov, but the Gosplan chief
promised his agency would confine itself to setting major economic
factors such as the federal budget, raw materials and military
production, leaving details to the republics.
   ``Two months ago, he was opposed to all this,'' Griazin said.
``This is a new guy. I like him very much.''
   There were only six votes against Maslyukov. The hands raised to
vote `yes' were not counted as they were a clear majority.
   Abalkin took the podium after his confirmation and said Soviet
efficiency must be improved.
   ``We have a budget deficit of 100 billion rubles ($156 billion)
this year,'' he said. ``There are two ways to eliminate it. Cut
expenditures or increase revenues.''
   Abalkin explained the poor Soviet standard of living with the
comment: ``We live no worse than we work.''
   Deputies laughed and then applauded.
   The Supreme Soviet is the country's first full-time
representative legislature, a branch of the larger Congress of
People's Deputies chosen this spring in the first nationwide
contested elections in seven decades.
   The six nominees rejected Tuesday after committee hearings were
Culture Minister Vasily G. Zakharov; Gennady P. Bogomyakov, nominee
for minister of the oil and gas industry; Polad A. Polad-Zade for
minister of land reclamation and water management, a controversial
department in charge of dams and canals; Marat V. Gramov for head of
the sports committee; Lira I. Rozenova for the price committee, and
Vladimir G. Gribov for head of the central bank.
   Ryzhkov said candidates for a first deputy premiership and head
of a new Commission on Food and Purchases were withdrawn during
other committee work.
   The legislative agenda for this 40-day summer session includes
new laws on consumer protection, inventions, the court system, the
press, taxes, citizen associations, the criminal code and economic
reform, and first readings of new laws on trade unions, youth,
freedom of conscience and religious organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
