<FIRST>r i AM-Malaysia-Baby     06-28 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-Baby,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infant Saves Fellow Storm-Tossed Indonesians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infant girl probably saved the
lives of 18 fellow Indonesians after their boat capsized in a storm,
the Bernama news agency reported Wednesday.
   One of the Indonesians clinging to the boat held up the
1-year-old to attract the attention of the crew of the merchant
vessel Trans Sun in the Straits of Malacca, about 210 miles
northwest of Kuala Lumpur, Bernama said.
   The ship's captain, E.M.R. Fonseca, said his crew at first
believed the boat was a log, but looking back through binoculars, he
saw the baby and ordered the ship to turn back. The Indonesians were
rescued after being adrift nearly 10 hours.
   Their skipper, Abdul Rahman Baki, said the group of 19
Indonesians, including the girl, had left Sunday from Pulau Rapat
for Sungai Pak Ning, in another part of Indonesian Sumatra.
   Their 30-foot boat capsized and sprang a leak, but all managed to
cling to it, he added.
   After much frantic shouting and waving as the Trans Sun passed,
Abdul Rahman said he held up the girl, Erna Yusup, to attract the
crew's attention.
   Heirianto Wongso, immigration officer at the Indonesian Consulate
in Penang, said the 19 would be sent back to Sumatra in two days.
</TEXT>
