<FIRST>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   06-28 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the thumbs.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 25
   The Post-Crescent, Appleton-Neenah-Menasha, Wis., on children and
gun laws:
   A new Florida law imposes criminal penalties on parents whose
loaded weapons are not kept out of the reach of their children. ...
   In the wake of several recent shootings by Wisconsin children who
had such easy access, some legislators want a similar law here.
   We don't.
   The key to preventing horrible accidents of this nature is not to
lock up the weapons; the key is to get children to act responsibly
around the weapons in the first place. That can best be accomplished
not by punishing parents after their kids have shot someone, but by
educating the kids about gun safety, by acting before tragedy
strikes.
   Teaching children to handle guns properly is a far better
solution than thinking that hiding guns will make the problem go
away. It won't.

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 23
   The Columbian of Vancouver, Wash., on the HUD scandal:
   Teapot Dome, the notorious tale about public servants tapping the
federal till for private gain, blots the historical view of
President Warren Harding. The unfolding scandal in the recent
administration's Department of Housing and Urban Development may
stand as an even darker mark against Ronald Reagan.
   Harding died ... before the extent of Teapot Dome was clear. He
did not have to watch Secretary of Interior Albert B. Fall locked up
for taking more than $100,000 in bribes. Similarly, Reagan's
well-documented Teflon coating may keep the HUD mud from sticking to
him in the short run.
   The HUD scandal, however, shapes up as larger and more pernicious
than Teapot Dome. Whatever else historians write about the past
decade, they must reckon with massive expropriation of federal funds
by friends and former associates of Reagan. While thousands of
families and individuals daily fought for wretched shelter, while
construction of new subsidized housing dwindled, while the decay of
existing housing stock accelerated, well-connected Republicans used
HUD as a private slush fund.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 22
   The State, Columbia, S.C., on President Bush's clean-air proposal:
   President Bush's clean-air package is an important first step in
reducing dangerous airborne pollutants and a welcome change from the
Reagan administration's do-nothing attitude.
   Predictably, some environmentalists say the Bush plan doesn't go
far enough, while coal, oil and auto industry officials say it
amounts to overkill. But Democrats and Republicans in Congress are
generally supportive of the President's three-pronged approach to
curb acid rain, urban smog and airborne toxic chemicals. ...
   Now Congress, which ... in areas that exceed one or more of the federal
   air pollution standards, that is good news, indeed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 26
   St. Albans (Vt.) Messenger on China:
   ... The spontaneous rebellion in Beijing does demonstrate that
the yearning to be free and to share governmental power is part of
being human. But, no, it did not demonstrate that such yearnings
cannot be stymied by force.
   There is, in fact, nothing in the past month's events that holds
out the faintest hope that China's government will allow itself to
evolve into a participatory democracy. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 27
   Los Angeles Herald Examiner on the Supreme Court's death penalty
rulings:
   Even the most ardent advocates of capital punishment would be
hard pressed to defend a pair of Supreme Court decisions authorizing
executions for crimes committed by 16- and 17-year-old teen-agers
and the mentally retarded.
   While we still believe the death penalty is appropriate in
certain circumstances, such a sentence must never be taken lightly.
Proponents should start by admitting that protecting society from
specific violent killers is probably the death penalty's least
important function; in most circumstances, life without parole would
do as well, and given the high cost of legal appeals, at lower cost.
   But given the three traditional justifications for capital
punishment _ to deter those who would commit heinous crimes, to
punish those for whom rehabilitation is not possible, and as an act
of social ablution, or ritual cleansing _ killing teen-age criminals
serves little purpose. ...
   Killing them is neither measured justice, nor fitting
retribution; it's a spasm of vindictiveness, the least defensible of
all motivations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End of Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
