<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Czech-Rights     06-28 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Czech-Rights,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activist Convicted, Gets 2{ Years in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading underground publisher in
Czechoslovakia was convicted Wednesday on charges of incitement to
riot and sentenced to 2{ years in jail, emigre sources said.
   Frantisek Starek and his companion, Iva Vojtkova, were convicted
in the town of Usti nad Orlice, 90 miles east of Prague.
   Ms. Vojtkova received a 12-month sentence that was reduced to two
years' probation, the sources said.
   After serving his jail time, Starek will remain under police
observation for two years and report to police every day, said the
sources, who requested anonimity.
   Starek, 36, chief editor of the underground magazine Vokno,
already has served two prison sentences for his independent
activities since 1975.
   He was arrested in February after police confiscated his
magazine's archives. ``An important source of information on
independent culture in Czechoslovakia in the last 20 years was
lost,'' according to the Vienna-based International Helsinki
Federation, a human rights group.
</TEXT>
