<FIRST>r a PM-ByrneKilling     06-28 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Byrne Killing,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Triggerman Gets Life in Byrne Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gunman who killed a rookie policeman guarding
the home of a drug witness was sentenced today to 25 years to life
in prison, becoming the fourth and final defendant in the 1988
slaying to get the maximum term.
   Supreme Court Justice Thomas Demakos imposed the sentence on
David McClary, 23, who was found guilty June 6 of firing five shots
at close range at 22-year-old Officer Edward Byrne as he sat in his
patrol car.
   McClary and co-defendants Scott Cobb, Todd Scott and Philip
Copeland were convicted of murdering Byrne on orders from reputed
drug kingpin Howard ``Pappy'' Mason, who allegedly wanted to avenge
his jailing on a weapons charge.
   Prosecutors charged Copeland masterminded the killing, while
Scott was the lookout and Cobb the getaway driver.
   The murder received national attention during the 1988
presidential campaign when the slain officer's father, Matthew
Byrne, presented his son's shield to President Bush during a rally
in favor of the death penalty.
   Demakos, in sentencing McClary's co-defendants, promised that his
last act as a judge would be to ask the parole board never to
release them.
