<FIRST>u a PM-SovietSpy-Reax 3rdLd-Writethru a0556 06-28 0932</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Spy-Reax, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0556,0956</SECOND>
<HEAD>Associate Says KGB Used Spy `Like a Spider Playing With a Moth'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with comments today by KGB chief,
other details in PM-Soviet-Spy, a0574. Picks up in 7th graf, `Kryuchkov
said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To those who knew Glenn Michael Souther
before he defected to the Soviet Union, he was a rambunctious
college student who liked to play pranks.
   But his obituary in a Soviet military newspaper called him a KGB
spy who ``made a great contribution to maintaining the Soviet
Union's security.''
   Today, the head of the KGB said Souther, a former U.S. Navy
intelligence analyst, broke under the pressure of his work and
committed suicide.
   Souther, 32, defected to the Soviet Union and rose to become a
major in the Soviet KGB. Yet ``his nervous system could not stand
the pressure ...,'' Gen. Vladimir Kryuchkov told reporters in Moscow
outside the meeting hall of the Soviet legislature.
   Souther, Kryuchkov said, took his life last week and left a note
thanking the Soviet government for what it did for him personally.
   The spy chief would not say how Souther committed suicide.
   The obituary on Tuesday identified Souther by the Russian name of
Mikhail Orlov, a name he took when he arrived in the Soviet Union,
Kryuchkov said.
   The name had led to speculation that Souther ws a Russian mole
rather than an American defector.
   Kryuchkov said Souther left behind a Russian wife and daughter
and was buried Monday in the same cemetery as Kim Philby, the
British traitor who spied for Moscow. He said Souther's parents and
brother traveled to Moscow from the United States for the funeral.
   Some of the people who knew Souther as a Russian major at Old
Dominion University speculated he committed suicide because of his
disillusionment with the Soviet Union.
   ``They used him like a spider playing with a moth and when they
were going to finish with him, they finished with him,'' said
Barbara Fahey, a professor's wife who knew him in school.
   Others said he could have turned Soviet spy but they doubt he was
a mole who masqueraded as an American during four years at Old
Dominion and an eight-year Navy enlisted career that included
intelligence work.
   ``He was not a Soviet. I can assure you of that,'' said Ms.
Fahey's husband, John, a retired Navy commander who taught Russian
to Souther at Old Dominion.
   Fahey said the Soviets may have described Souther as one of their
own to prevent the United States from investigating his death.
``Despite glasnost, disinformation is not dead in the Soviet
Union,'' he said.
   The Faheys remembered Souther as a prankster who loved to be the
center of attention.
   ``He wanted to be the life of the party,'' Mrs. Fahey said. ``I
felt he was screaming out to be seen and heard.''
   Souther's outgoing personality may have been ill-suited to the
Soviet Union, the Faheys said.
   ``I'm sure he was depressed after they got through with him and
debriefed him. He would not get the recognition or attention
there,'' Fahey said. ``The dismal life there I'm sure was a shock to
him.''
   Ronald Kessler, a writer preparing a book on Souther, said his
research shows Souther was an American who became a Soviet spy.
   ``He was in fact a very successful spy,'' Kessler said in a
telephone interview from his Potomac, Md., home. ``It's possible
that he took this Russian name after he defected.''
   Kessler said Souther referred to ``my life's vicissitudes'' in a
letter he sent the writer this month. ``He was perhaps having second
thoughts or having trouble adjusting over there,'' Kessler said.
   Souther enlisted in the Navy in 1975 and was honorably discharged
in 1982 with the rank of petty officer first class. He served in the
Naval Reserve until May 1986.
   That's when he disappeared. He turned up on Soviet television
last July, saying he had defected because he was being harassed by
the FBI. Souther indicated in the broadcast that he was dissatisfied
with his new life although he had a comfortable Moscow apartment.
   ``I haven't found my niche exactly. I don't feel that I'm being
the most productive for what I have to offer,'' he said.
   Souther had been married to an Italian woman and had a son with
her before they divorced, said Fran Hassencahl, his speech professor
at Old Dominion. Ms. Hassencahl said he was engaged to an American
woman when he defected.
   Kessler said he had been told Souther was in excellent health and
rode his bicycle regularly in the Soviet Union.
   ``There's no reason to believe that he would die so early,'' he
said. ``Any kind of violent death should be considered.''
   Dennis Leighton, who knew Souther in the mid-1970s when they
attended high school in Cumberland, Maine, said he was surprised
when he found out about the defection.
   ``To me, he was just a regular guy who ran track and
cross-country. There was nothing unusual,'' said Leighton, a
physical therapist in Portland, Maine. ``If he was a Russian, he had
me fooled. He wasn't political or anything.''
   One of Souther's campus pranks may have led to his decision to
defect, Fahey said. Because he was suspended from Old Dominion in
1984 for biting a female student on the neck, Souther was turned
down for Navy's officer candidate school.
   ``He was very bitter about what happened to him as far as the
problem on campus,'' Fahey said. ``He really wanted to become a
naval officer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
