<FIRST>r w AM-Women-Politics     06-28 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Women-Politics,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Fund-Raisers Recruiting Women Candidates for Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic fund-raisers said Wednesday they are
recruiting women to run for dozens of open and swing House seats
expected to result from the 1992 overhaul of the nation's
congressional districts.
   ``This is the critical moment,'' said Rosa DeLauro, executive
director of EMILY's List, which has raised nearly $1 million for
Democratic women candidates in the last four years.
   Women, who make up about 6 percent of the House, have increased
their numbers only three times in 20 years: in 1972 and 1982 after
redistricting, and in 1988. EMILY's List, an acronym for Early Money
Is Like Yeast, attributes the 1988 increase largely to its own
fund-raising activities on behalf of several women who are now House
freshmen.
   The group estimates there will be 80 open seats as a result of
redistricting, retirement and electoral changes in 1992. Recruiters
are already trying to identify potential women candidates for 1992
and 1994 as part of a long-term Majority Project.
   Asked how the list intends to make sure Democratic women pre-empt
the Democratic men who no doubt will be interested in running for
the same open seats, DeLauro replied, ``We're going to find them
fast.''
   ``And give them money,'' added Celinda Lake, a consultant
studying women's House campaigns.
   DeLauro said the Majority Project also is looking at which women
incumbents may be vulnerable due to the 1992 redistricting process
and will help them work closely with Democrats in the state
legislatures charged with drawing the new lines.
   Democratic incumbents with districts likely to change are Reps.
Louise Slaughter and Nita Lowey of New York, according to Mark Gersh
of the National Committee for an Effective Congress, a political
action committee working with EMILY's List.
   Gersh said the two districts, in the suburbs of Rochester and New
York City, don't have enough people and whatever changes are made
could either solidify or weaken the two women's positions.
   Gersh also said Rep. Jill Long, D-Ind., was elected in a
Republican district and any subtle boundary changes could affect her
future. He said the greater Cleveland area stands to lose a seat,
affecting any one of six or seven incumbents. One of them, Rep. Mary
Rose Oakar, is a Democratic woman.
   Open seat opportunities are expected to abound in California,
Texas and Florida because of population shifts. California
anticipates a gain of five to seven seats during reapportionment,
while the other two should win at least three seats each.
   Many of the new seats will be in suburban areas, a factor the
strategists said bodes well for women. According to Lake, women
become increasingly attractive candidates as income level rises and
the proportion of women under 45 working outside the home increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
