<FIRST>r i AM-PhotoFestival     06-28 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Photo Festival,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>American South Focus of Photography Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From a deserted strip of highway to the muscle-bound
athletes of a high school football team, the many faces of the
American South are on display at the International Photography
Festival in the city of Arles.
   ``The Deep South,'' at the Palais de l'Archeveche from July 2
through Sept. 3, features 200 pictures by 18 American and European
photographers. Some of the photos date back to 1930.
   ``The South has long been photography's poor relative because
it's so difficult to photograph,'' said Gilles Mora, the show's
curator. ``There is racial tension, and then, there are the
protectionist attitudes of the people who resent outside cultural
influences.''
   American photographer Robert Frank's pictures of Birmingham,
Ala., focus on the city's down-and-out residents.
   Frank gave up photography 20 years ago to pursue a career in the
movies, but he picked up his camera again last year to photograph
Birmingham's centennial celebrations at the request of the
Birmingham News.
   Also on show are works by Bruce Davidson, best known for his
pictures of the New York subway and East 100th Street in Harlem. For
``The Deep South,'' he shot firefighters, doctors and police.
   Mora, a photographer who spent four years teaching French in
Louisiana, says the French are particularly fond of the South.
   ``It's the only place in the United States where there's a life
for the senses. There are smells, people live outdoors and take
walks. They handle problems with a kind of inefficient and relaxed
detachment reminiscent of southern France, Italy and other Latin
countries,'' Mora said.
   ``The South is a unique juxtaposition of kitsch and class, luxury
and poverty.''
   In the 1930s, dozens of American photographers immortalized the
Works Project Administration, the government sponsored building and
improvement project that created jobs for the unemployed between
1935-43.
   ``The photos show that the South hasn't gone down hill. Things
are remarkably unchanged,'' Mora said. ``There are the same
landscapes and cityscapes, and the people show the same pride and
the same mistrust of outsiders.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
