<FIRST>u w AM-Wolves-Yellowstone     06-28 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wolves-Yellowstone,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Return of Wolves to Yellowstone Urged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morning Star rested quietly on the Capitol lawn
Wednesday, fixing her yellow eyes on the crowd as politicians and
conservationists advocated the return of her species, the timber
wolf, to Yellowstone National Park.
   ``Wolves don't eat little children,'' stressed Rep. Wayne Owens,
D-Utah, sponsor of a bill requiring the National Park Service to do
an environmental impact study on returning wolves to Yellowstone.
   Wolves have gotten an undeserved bad reputation because they
``howl at night and scare people ... and compete with us for food,''
said Owens.
   Even as Owens was discussing his measure, Sen. Alan K. Simpson,
R-Wyo., was attacking it in a statement issued in Cheyenne.
   Simpson, an opponent of returning wolves to Yellowstone,
condemned Owens' bill as ``a misguided and zealous effort to
accelerate wolf reintroduction without considering in any way how
wolves will affect other animals in Yellowstone Park and the very
real human beings that also live in Wyoming.''
   ``He's half right, I am zealous,'' Owens responded in Washington.
   Owens' bill does not require the reintroduction of wolves to the
park. Rather, it directs the Park Service to begin a study of what
the impact would be if wolves were returned, and sets a date of Dec.
31, 1991, for completion of that report.
   ``It has been 60 years since a wolf's howl has been heard in
Yellowstone,'' M. Rupert Cutler, president of the conservation group
Defenders of Wildlife, said in Washington. ``It never should have
been silenced.''
   Morning Star, a 13-month-old female gray wolf, shifted her long
legs and panted slightly in the capital's summer heat and humidity,
but otherwise seemed uninterested in the speeches and cameras.
   She yawned languidly as Owens expounded on her docility,
tolerating petting from him and her handlers, from Wolf Haven, a
refuge near Olympia, Wash., that cares for abandoned wolves.
   Wolves were exterminated from Yellowstone by hunters and
government trappers, Cutler said, with the result that today
``thousands of elk and bison are overgrazing the Yellowstone range
and many starve to death every winter.
   ``Wolves are needed in the Northern Rockies to restore the
natural balance among animals,'' said Cutler.
   Although backed by Defenders of Wildlife, the National Wildlife
Federation, the National Parks and Conservation Association and
other national and local conservation groups, Owens' measure may
face rough going due to opposition from ranchers who fear wolves
will eat their sheep and cattle.
   Owens said he has invited Simpson to travel to Canada with him to
see a park where wolves live peacefully, not bothering nearby
livestock.
   And Cutler pointed out that Defenders of Wildlife has raised a
special fund to compensate any rancher in the Yellowstone area
losing stock to wolves.
   Rep. William D. Ford, D-Mich., said he was co-sponsoring the
measure as a way of ``trying to make amends to nature for what our
predecessors did.''
   Asked how he would respond to residents who contend he is
interfering in local affairs of the park region, Owens said that
``they don't own the park ... the park belongs to all Americans.''
   While wolves once roamed over much of the area currently occupied
by the United States, they were relentlessly hunted and poisoned in
the last century. Today, only Alaska has large numbers of wolves,
with about 1,200 in northern Minnesota and a few reported in
Michigan and Montana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
