<DOCNO> AP890628-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HeartAttackDrug     06-28 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heart Attack Drug,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heart Attack Drug Altered, May Work Longer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clot-busting drug that interrupts heart attacks
has been redesigned to work longer, which might reduce the risk of a
second heart attack after treatment.
   In test tube experiments, an altered version of a drug called
tissue plasminogen activator remained largely potent when exposed to
substances in blood that de-activate the current form of the drug.
   The work is described in Thursday's issue of the British journal
Nature by researchers at the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center in Dallas and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute
there.
   It will take animal studies to assess the persistence of altered
forms of the drug, said study co-author Joseph Sambrook, of the
medical center, on Wednesday.
   Most heart attacks occur when a clot plugs an artery that feeds
blood to part of the heart muscle. Tissue plasminogen activator,
called TPA, can stop a heart attack by dissolving the clot.
   But some patients who get TPA therapy develop another clot after
the treatment stops, putting them at risk for another heart attack.
If TPA can be made to remain active longer, it may reduce the
tendency toward forming clots after therapy stops, said Thomas J.
Ryan, chief of cardiology at Boston University.
   TPA's effectiveness is limited not only by inactivation, but also
because the drug is removed from the bloodstream by the liver. That
is why animal studies are needed to assess persistence of altered
versions, said Edgar Haber, president of the Squibb Institute for
Medical Research in Princeton, N.J.
   Some researchers have altered TPA to hamper removal by the liver,
and perhaps that approach can be combined with that of the new study
to create a longer-lasting drug, Haber said.
   Sambrook said a longer-lasting TPA might make treatment cheaper
because smaller doses could be used. Currently, because a given dose
works only briefly, TPA must be given as a continuous infusion over
a few hours, he said.
   The treatment costs about $2,000, some 10 times that of using
another clot-busting drug, streptokinase, which is administered as a
single injection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     06-28 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Lawmaker Arrested for Illegal Trip to North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's intelligence agency
arrested an opposition lawmaker Wednesday for illegally visiting
communist North Korea to discuss unification of the countries.
   Also on Wednesday, about 2,000 radical students battled riot
police at two universities to protest a government ban on
participation in an international youth festival in North Korea.
   The Agency for National Security Planning said Suh Kyung-won of
the Party for Peace and Democracy was arrested for secretly visiting
North Korea in August and meeting with the nation's leader, Kim Il
Sung.
   Suh's party, South Korea's largest opposition group, apologized
and called his trip ``a reckless act.''
   Suh, 52, was charged with violating the National Security Law,
which carries a maximum sentence of death, security officials said.
   President Roh Tae-woo said Suh's trip to Pyongyang was ``a really
shocking incident'' and called for firm measures against the leftist
movement.
   He also dismissed calls by radical students for the withdrawal of
the 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual
defense treaty. Roh said the troops contribute to peace and
stability.
   About 1,500 radical students from Seoul and other cities gathered
at Hanyang University in the capital and clashed with about 3,500
riot police.
   ``Punish Roh Tae-woo!'' groups of masked students shouted as they
marched and attacked police with firebombs, rocks and clubs.
   Police responded with barrages of tear gas and threw back rocks
hurled by students. Authorities said dozens of officers suffered
minor injuries.
   Police arrested more than 100 students trying to enter the
school, they said.
   Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, reported similar clashes at
Hannam University in the city of Taejon, where police blocked about
600 students from leaving for Seoul.
   Student protesters have called for marches to Panmunjom, the
border truce village in the demilitarized zone, to press their
demand to be allowed to participate in the weeklong North Korean
festival, which begins Saturday in Pyongyang.
   Students say they want to attend the festival to help advance
unification. Seoul accuses North Korea of using the festival to
dramatize its demand for the withdrawal of U.S. forces.
   South Koreans have been barred from visiting North Korea without
government permission since the nations fought the Korean war from
1950-53. Korea was divided in 1945 at the end of World War II.
   Security officials charged Wednesday there are about 10,000
leftists in South Korea seeking revolution and unification with
North Korea. They said leftists and communists in South Korea
dominate 26 dissident, religious, labor, student and other groups.
</TEXT>
