<FIRST>r a AM-Flyaways     06-28 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flyaways,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Boys Talk Their Way Onto Plane for Free Flight to Detroit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two runaway boys who may have been trying to get
to Walt Disney World at Orlando, Fla., talked their way onto a
United Airlines flight and ended up with a free trip to Detroit,
officials say.
   ``Our understanding is that it was late at night, they said they
had lost their tickets, and they were crying,'' said United
spokesman Joe Hopkins. ``They were not stowaways. We boarded them.''
   ``Their version of the story was that they went up to a ticket
agent, said they had deplaned in Chicago, and lost their boarding
passes and that their parents were on the plane,'' said Nancy
Mouradian, a spokeswoman for the Wayne County sheriff's department
in Detroit.
   When the boys, aged 12 and 14, arrived in Detroit early Tuesday
they told an airline employee that someone was supposed to meet
them, Hopkins said.
   They were taken to a United office, but wandered away and were
later stopped by a sheriff's deputy.
   Ms. Mouradian said authorities in Chicago said one of the boys
had been reported missing. One was returned home by plane, the other
by bus.
   ``When they asked why they came to Detroit, they didn't know,''
Ms. Mouradian said. ``One of the boys said he'd like to get to
Orlando. I guess Orlando sounds pretty good this time of year.''
