<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-CounterfeitBolts     06-28 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Counterfeit Bolts,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Companies Accused of Supplying Shoddy Nuts and Bolts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associted Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. company and a Japanese
manufacturer sold hundreds of thousands of substandard nuts and
bolts to the Pentagon and the Comanche Peak nuclear plant, the
Justice Department charged today.
   The indictment unsealed today names Yamaguchi-Seisakusho Co. of
Shizuoka, Japan, and Aircom Fasteners Inc. of Arlington.
   The nuts and bolts were used in a variety of items, including
tractor-trailers and other military vehicles and nuclear plants. But
authorities today said they don't know for sure where all the
fasteners ended up.
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported today that the bolts, which
were of an inferior composition but labeled as if they were made of
higher-quality material, have been blamed for at least two
accidents, in which no one was hurt.
   ``It's like if someone orders a Cadillac and you slap a Cadillac
emblem on a Chevrolet and sell it as a Cadillac,'' said Jim Slick,
agent in charge of the defense criminal investigative service in the
Fort Worth office of the Inspector General's office.
   U.S. Attorney Marvin Collins said he expects six Aircom employees
to surrender today. Marcy Forman, Customs supervisor in Houston,
said the government will seek extradition of five employees of the
Japanese manufacturer.
   A woman who answered the telephone at Aircom said no one was in
the office and ``we've got nothing to say'' before hanging up.
   The Defense Department and TU Electric, owner of Comanche Peak,
ordered bolts with high tensile strength, meaning they would break
only under extreme conditions.
   But federal officials contend Yamaguchi Seisakusho used low-grade
boron in its bolts instead of stronger steel alloys, the
Star-Telegram reported. The bolts tend to fail prematurely when put
under stress.
   Slick said, ``We had several products that did not work because
of the substandard fasteners and that constituted a safety problem.''
   Slick and Brooks Griffin, an investigator with the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission, said they don't know where all the bolts
ended up and to what extent they were used.
   Griffin said some of the bolts were taken out of a system that
removes heat from the reactor core at the nearly operational
Comanche Peak in Glen Rose. He would not speculate on what would
have happened had the bolts never been discovered.
   Peterbilt Motors Co. had to recall many of its trucks, including
several used by the government to haul nuclear Minuteman missiles,
after learning in 1988 that Aircom bolts used in the steering
mechanism were failing, causing drivers to lose control, the
Star-Telegram said.
   At least two mishaps occurred before the recall, but no injuries
were reported, the newspaper said, citing unidentified sources.
   The investigation began 2{ years ago when the Pentagon was tipped
by industry sources, authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
