<FIRST>r a AM-CatAttack     06-28 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cat Attack,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owner Strangles Cat After Daughter is Mauled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KITTERY, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pet cat attacked an 8-year-old girl
several times and drove her family from their home, ``making all
kinds of weird sounds,'' until it finally was wrestled to the ground
by two men and killed.
   The body of 3-year-old Gypsy was sent to a state laboratory for
rabies testing.
   ``I've watched all kinds of movies and I've never seen anything
like this,'' Mike Johnson said of the cat's last attack on his
daughter, Amy. ``The cat was ripping her apart all over.''
   Gypsy attacked Amy several times Monday and finally drove the
family from the house for several hours.
   When the family returned home, Johnson persuaded Amy to take a
shower, thinking that perhaps she had picked up the scent of other
cats.
   But when the girl entered her bedroom, Gypsy reappeared, glared
at Johnson and then pounced on Amy, clawing a one-inch gash above
her right eye that required four stitches.
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' Amy said. ``It felt like 150
needles going through me.''
   Johnson rescued his daughter by striking the cat with a mop
handle, then called police while Amy's mother, Dorothy, took her to
a hospital.
   After Patrolman Gary Berg arrived, he and Johnson found the cat
under Amy's bed.
   ``She came flying out, making all kinds of weird sounds,''
Johnson said.
   The cat bit and scratched, but the men managed to wrestle her to
the floor. Johnson said he finally was forced to strangle the animal.
   ``I was tired and the cat was freaking out and both of us were
getting sliced and diced,'' Johnson said. ``If was afraid if I let
her go she would kill me.
   ``She had an evil look on her face.''
   Mrs. Johnson said Gypsy had been with the family since she was a
kitten and was never mistreated or deprived of food. Johnson said
the cat never had a rabies shot, but was an indoor cat and therefore
unlikely to catch the disease.
   Dr. Philip Haines of the state Department of Human Services
laboratory in Augusta acknowledged that the likelihood of an indoor
cat contracting rabies was slim, but said there could be many
reasons why a cat would go berserk.
</TEXT>
