<FIRST>u a PM-OilSpillsRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0573 06-28 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spills Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0573,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Captain Says Anchor Got Away, Caused Tanker to Run Aground</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with captain testifying that prematurely
dropped anchor caused accident; PICKS UP 11th graf pvs, `Coast Guard ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLAYMONT, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot and captain of a tanker that
spilled more 310,000 gallons of oil in the Delaware River said today
an anchor was dropped too soon, causing the vessel to swing around
and run aground on the shoals.
   In Rhode Island, a grand jury was convened today to investigate a
420,000-gallon oil spill, and the cleanup of 250,000 gallons of
crude in Texas was nearly over.
   The spills occcured within hours of each other over the weekend.
   Capt Raul Dibarrart, testifying at a Coast Guard inquiry in
Philadelphia, said the crew of the Uruguayan tanker was lowering the
anchor to the water's surface in preparation for dropping anchor
farther up the Delaware River shipping channel.
   ``I heard the anchor fall, and I heard over the walkie-talkie my
lieutenant say `It's running away,''' the captain said, speaking
through an intepreter.
   The captain and the tanker pilot, Robert Anderson, said the
vessel swung around and ran aground in the shallows, then ran
aground again as two tugboats tried to bring it back into deep water
and set it back on course.
   It was then that a tugboat captain noticed oil coming from the
tanker, the pilot said.
   Paul L. Ives Jr., president of the Pilots Association for the Bay
and River Delaware, said before the hearing got under way that
dropping the anchor from 749-foot vessel is ``like stepping on the
leash of a running dog.''
   Meanwhile, a Coast Guard spokesman said more people and boats
were being pressed into service today to clean up the heavy
industrial heating oil, which was mostly congealed in huge blobs
that could be picked up by hand.
   Temperatures in the mid-90s Tuesday made the oil run in spots,
complicating the cleanup and raising the threat to the shore and to
wildlife, but Coast Guard spokesman Jim Weakley said today's weather
was cooler and the spill is ``winding down.''
   ``It's winding down because we're getting the stuff out of the
water,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, New Jersey officials said a wind shift was sending oil
toward their side of the river. crews were cleaning up the debris as
it came ashore, said Tom Gallagher, spokesman for the state's
emergency response agency.
   Coast Guard spokeswoman Annette Sebastian said 600 people and 33
boats worked on the cleanup Tuesday and more were expected today.
Officials dramatically reduced their estimate of the amount of oil
spilled, from 800,000 gallons to about 310,000. An estimated 106,240
gallons had been recovered by Tuesday night.
   In Rhode Island, the effort to fix blame for Friday's tanker
accident shifted to a state grand jury. Some of the crew and the
captain, Iakovas Georgudis, have been summoned.
   The state is investigating whether a harbor pilot was required to
be on board the World Prodigy when it ran aground, spilling 420,000
gallons of heating oil at the mouth of Narragansett Bay.
   In interviews with Coast Guard officials and the governor after
the spill, Georgudis admitted he made a mistake in not taking on a
pilot to take the vessel into the harbor.
   The Coast Guard wants prosecutors to grant a helmsman immunity
from prosecution to secure his testimony. Helmsman Konstadinos A.
Paraskevopulos, accompanied by an attorney and speaking through an
interpreter, invoked his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination and refused to testify Tuesday at the Coast Guard
inquiry.
   Virtually all the spilled No. 2 heating oil had dispersed, and
officials said a rainstorm forecast for this afternoon would help
flush the oil out of the sand and break up a sheen in the water.
   In Houston, the pilot of a tanker that collided with a barge in
the Houston Ship Channel radioed he couldn't stop his vessel minutes
before the accident, according to the captain of a tugboat pushing
the barge.
   Mason T. Ware testified at a Coast Guard inquiry that he realized
he wouldn't be able to stop his tugboat and three barges it was
pushing.
   Friday night's collision damaged one of the barges, which leaked
about 250,000 gallons of crude into the water and fouled a mile-long
stretch of the Galveston Bay shoreline.
   Crews this morning continued the cleanup near La Porte, where
most of the slick was contained within a ship channel, and all but
about 20,000 gallons have been removed, Coast Guard spokesman Bob
Morehead said.
   The tanker pilot, Michael Gale, testified Tuesday that his vessel
failed to perform as expected on a right turn into the channel,
leading to the collision.
   In Delaware, the state filed suit in federal court against the
government of Uruguay and the captain of the Presidente Rivera,
seeking unspecified damages caused when the government-owned tanker
ran aground Saturday.
   The spill covered 21 miles Tuesday, extending from above Marcus
Hook, Pa., to below Pea Patch Island. The island is the site of a
wildlife refuge, which was being protected by booms.
</TEXT>
