<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     06-28 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government, Tamil Tigers Declare Cease-fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and the biggest group of
Tamil rebels agreed to an immediate cease-fire in a six-year war
that has claimed 9,000 lives, the two sides said Wednesday.
   On Sri Lanka's second war front Wednesday, police said Sinhalese
extremists detonated a car bomb in the southern provincial capital,
killing four people and wounding 25 others.
   Industries Minister Ranil Wickremasinghe announced the government
and Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam reached agreement Tuesday.
   The two sides will resolve Tamil demands for an independent
nation and other differences through negotiations, Wickremasinghe
said at a news conference.
   It was not attended by any Tamil leader. But a rebel source said
the cease-fire does not mean they have abandoned their campaign for
a separate homeland in the northeast.
   ``The LTTE has clearly told the government that it is premature
to talk about the withdrawal of the (homeland) demand,'' the source
said on condition of anonymity.
   The truce follows a unilateral cease-fire announced by the Tigers
on May 4 when they began their first peace talks with the government.
   Rebels want a separate nation for the ethnic minority Tamils
because they say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese who
comprise 75 percent of the population. Tamils are mainly Hindu while
most Sinhalese are Buddhist.
   Most war victims have been government soldiers and Sinhalese
civilians killed by rebels in the north and east, where Tamils
predominate.
   Confrontations between the rebels and government troops reduced
considerably after India brokered a July 29, 1987, peace accord.
   It confined the Sri Lankan military in the north and east to
barracks and replaced them with Indian peacekeeping troops.
   The accord says rebels should surrender their arms in exchange
for local political powers for the Tamils who make up 18 percent of
Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   The Tigers initially accepted the accord, as did other smaller
Tamil rebel groups. But then the Tigers turned their guns on Indian
soldiers. At least 800 Indian troops and 1,500 Tamils have been
killed.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has asked India to withdraw its
45,000 troops by the second anniversary of the accord, but New Delhi
says a hasty withdrawal could cause even greater violence.
   India got involved because its own 60 million Tamils sympathize
with the Sri Lankan rebels' cause.
   Wednesday's cease-fire offers peace for the north and east. But
the government still is fighting a southern insurgency against
ultranationalist Sinhalese angered by the Indian troop presence and
government concessions to Tamils.
   Extremists of the left-wing Sinhalese People's Liberation Front
have killed more than 3,500 government officials, supporters and
governing party members in the last two years, by official count.
   Front guerrillas Wednesday detonated a car bomb outside a local
government building in Galle were 50 councilors were meeting, a
senior police official said in a telephone interview.
   It killed four people, the officer said without identifying the
victims.
   Galle, 70 miles south of Colombo, is headquarters of the southern
province.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
