<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Jazz     06-28 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jazz,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>JVC Jazz: Bebop Revisited</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the early 1940s, jazz clubs in New York such
as Minton's were the scenes of some extraordinary jam sessions.
These musical gymnastics shaped the American art form to a classic
style that became known as bebop.
   Trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie was one of the masterminds of bop. And
so it was fitting that he should lead a ``Bebop Revisited'' concert
Tuesday night at the JVC Jazz Festival.
   Bebop prospered under Gillespie and Kenny Clarke, who led the
house band at Minton's. Soon, pianist-composer Thelonious Monk and
alto saxophonist Charlie Parker, who also composed, refined the
musical style to pretty much what it is today.
   Some of Parker's old bandmates played at the Tuesday night
concert at Avery Fisher Hall, including pianist Duke Jordan, with
Parker in 1947-48; and trumpet player Red Rodney, one of the first
white musicians to understand bebop, who played with the Charlie
Parker Quintet from 1949-51.
   Jordan and Rodney joined Phil Woods on sax and Mel Lewis on drums
in the evening's first set, which featured outstanding solo work on
some bebop standards. Jordan's fingering was light and lovely on
``Don't Blame Me.'' Woods sweetly soared with ``Lover Man.'' And
Rodney was in good form with ``I Can't Get Started.''
   Gillespie joined in for a final blast with the group.
   The next set brought the dueling pianos of Barry Harris and
Walter Davis Jr. Joining them were Ron Carter on bass and Roy
Haynes, who played with the Parker Quintet in 1949-50, on drums. It
was an energetic set that ended with an explosive version of ``How
High the Moon.''
   The second half of the evening opened with vibes king Milt
Jackson, who has worked with Gillespie, Monk, Parker and the
legendary Modern Jazz Quartet. Jackson was joined by Bob Cranshaw on
bass, Cedar Walton on piano, Mickey Roker on drums and Jimmy Heath
on tenor sax. Gillespie joined in for a jam or two.
   The group excelled with Monk's lilting ``Round Midnight.''
   Unfortunately, bad miking made Art Blakey and the Jazz Messengers
a poor closing act. Avery Fisher has excellent acoustics, but some
groups tend to over-mike. Blakey's drums were so loud no other
instrument in his eight-piece group could be heard _ and that
included a trombone, three saxophones and a trumpet!
   By the time the group finished the set with ``A Night in
Tunisia,'' the amplification had been adjusted and listeners
realized the collection of talent Blakey had assembled.
   Blakey's Jazz Messengers has been a proving ground for some of
the brightest talent in jazz. The personnel who've played in the
group reads like a who's who: Horace Silver, Wynton Marsalis,
Branford Marsalis, Wayne Shorter, Lee Morgan, Freddie Hubbard, Woody
Shaw, Chick Corea, Jackie McLean and Cedar Walton.
   Ed Bradley of CBS' ``60 Minutes'' served as host for the night.
Before becoming a TV journalist, Bradley was a jazz deejay in
Philadelphia. The concert was a benefit for the Studio Museum in
Harlem.
   The JVC Jazz Festival is sponsored by the Japanese Victor Corp.,
an electronics firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0115 </DOCNO>
