<FIRST>r a PM-SchoolBudget     06-28 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Budget,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Board Approves $50 Million in Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debt-ridden Detroit School Board voted to cut
$50 million from the budget, lay off 900 teachers and 700 other
employees and eliminate some varsity sports unless the voters
approve a tax increase.
   Over jeers and shouts from more than 350 parents and teachers,
the board voted 7-2 Tuesday to approve a 1989-90 budget of more than
$700 million.
   The cuts were made to avoid intervention by the state, which has
threatened to impose its own reductions. Retiring Superintendent
Arthur Jefferson said the district will be $151 million in the red
by the end of the fiscal year in October.
   The layoffs would affect one out of 10 teachers and 455 janitors,
nearly half the maintenance staff. Some varsity sports and driver
education would be cut, and six administrative offices and five
schools would be closed.
   ``This budget is killing our kids and it is killing our school
district,'' said parent Delores Smith. ``For a long time I was
afraid of a state takeover of our schools, but now I see the enemy's
the board.''
   No specific tax increase or election date for such an increase
has been set.
</TEXT>
