<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0585 06-28 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0585,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Welcome Arab Cease-fire Call; Clashes Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE casualties. Picks up 4th graf,
``The Arab ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Moslem leaders Wednesday
supported an Arab League call for a cease-fire, but Syrian and
Lebanese Christian gunners continued to trade shellfire that killed
two people.
   Police said 11 people were wounded by the rocket and artillery
shells that exploded on both sides of the Green Line slicing Beirut
into Christian and Moslem sectors.
   By police count, 375 people have been killed and 1,471 wounded
since March 8, when the duel began between Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly
Christian Lebanese army and Syrian soldiers allied with Lebanese
Druse militiamen.
   The Arab League's special committee on Lebanon called for both
sides to lift port blockades that started the fighting.
   The committee grouping Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid, King
Hassan II of Morocco, and Saudi Arabia's King Fahd issued its latest
appeal after a Tuesday meeting in Oran, Algeria. Beirut radio
stations aired the call several times as fighting raged Wednesday.
   An Arab summit gave the committee six months to negotiate a
settlement to Lebanon's 14-year civil war, but it has not been able
to enforce even a truce.
   ``We stress that for the initiation of dialogue resulting in
benefits for the Lebanese and Lebanon, violence in all its forms
must stop,'' said the three leaders' statement.
   The daily As-Safir, which supports Syria, said Lakhdar Ibrahimi,
Arab League assistant secretary-general, will come to Lebanon within
48 hours in a new drive to stop the fighting.
   Committee leaders said their foreign ministers will hold talks
with world leaders to promote peace. Syria is the chief power broker
in Lebanon while Aoun is armed by Iraq, Damascus' chief Arab foe.
   Following the contacts and a consolidated cease-fire, the
committee said it will invite Lebanon's single-chamber parliament to
a foreign country of legislators' choice to work out a new
power-sharing formula. Christian sects traditionally have dominated
Lebanese politics, though they are outnumbered 2-1 by Sunni and
Shiite Moslems and the minority Druse.
   ``The cease-fire, lifting of blockades and opening of crossing
links must be achieved before the meeting of the parliamentarians
outside Lebanon, which will set the stage for the meeting of the
Lebanese parliament in Lebanon,'' the committee said.
   Christian legislators welcomed the calls for a cease-fire and
lifting of blockades, but voiced reservations about meeting in a
foreign country.
   Phalangist Party leader George Saadeh, head of a right-wing
Christian coalition, said: ``If crossing gateways were reopened, the
Lebanese would be able to meet in Lebanon.'' Gates linking Beirut's
Christian enclave to Syrian-policed Moslem sectors have been blocked
for more than three months.
   Syria's 40,000 troops and allied forces started besieging the
Christian area northeast of Beirut on March 14, six days after Aoun
blockaded illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias.
   The conservative daily newspaper Ad-Diyar, which is close to
Aoun, said the Maronite Catholic leader opposes a parliament session
outside Lebanon because ``it contradicts the principles of
sovereignty and national dignity.''
   Lebanon's parliament has not met for more than a year, since it
failed to elect a leader to succeed President Amin Gemayel when his
term expired.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, whose Moslem Cabinet competes
with Aoun's Christian one, expressed support for the Arab committee.
   ``We declare our full respect to the decisions of the tripartite
committee. We also declare our full readiness to cooperate with the
committee,'' Hoss said.
   Roman Catholic legislator Shafik Badr said: ``We support the
decisions of the Oran meeting ... but the issue is to apply these
decisions.''
</TEXT>
