<FIRST>r a AM-CowboysCheerleaders     06-28 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cowboys Cheerleaders,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Football Cheerleaders Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 14 Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders who quit over
proposed uniform and policy changes they considered unwholesome have
returned after a meeting with the football team's owner.
   The 14 met with Jerry Jones, owner of the National Football
League club, on Tuesday. Leslie Haynes, the new director of the
squad, said Jones was ``very positive, and I feel they firmly
believe him or they wouldn't have decided to come back.''
   Former cheerleader director Debbie Bond, who resigned June 22
along with the squad's 14 veteran cheerleaders, refused to return.
   ``We all talked about the issues that I had with Mr. Jones and
the assurances he gave me,'' Mrs. Haynes said. ``We got our feelings
and any animosity out. It took a while to break some of the girls
down.''
   Jones, an Arkansas oilman who bought the team in February, said
he and the cheerleaders had ``a real good meeting.''
   ``I don't know that I said anything to change their minds,''
Jones said. ``We talked and I gave them my background and where I
was coming from and my goals, and then I left and they had a
discussion and made their decision. I'm very pleased.''
   Ms. Bond told the 37 women on the squad that Jones suggested
having the cheerleaders serve as hostesses at team parties where
alcohol was served, appear in beer commercials and change their
costumes to halter tops and cycling shorts.
   Jones said Friday that he had suggested the cheerleaders not
automatically be dismissed if they were seen drinking alcohol while
in uniform or fraternizing with team members. He called it a
misunderstanding, but Ms. Bond said Jones ``was lying.''
</TEXT>
