<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-US     06-28 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-US,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Consular Officer Sees Imprisoned American</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An imprisoned American news
photographer was allowed his first visit from a U.S. diplomat
Wednesday since his arrest three weeks ago with Moslem guerrillas
fighting the communist government.
   Tony O'Brien of Santa Fe, N.M., was visited in the office of the
State Interrogation Department by Renny Smith, a consular officer
from the U.S. Embassy in New Delhi.
   ``He is eating OK and not complaining about his food and looked
relaxed,'' she said. ``He is pretty happy. I gave him cheese,
chocolates, six books and paper and pencils.''
   O'Brien, a free-lance photographer working for Time-Life, was
captured by the Afghan secret service June 8 at a guerrilla hideout
in Kabul.
   Ms. Smith came from New Delhi because the U.S. Embassy in Kabul
closed in January, a few weeks before Soviet military forces
withdrew Feb. 15, ending nine years of involvement in the civil war.
   O'Brien, 43, was sharing a 10-foot-by-8-foot cell with two
Afghans, she said. Asked when he might be released, she replied: ``I
have learned not to speculate. It can be the best or the worst. Best
can be tomorrow ... worst can be 10 years of sentence and release by
a presidential pardon.''
   Afghan government officials said O'Brien would have to wait for a
court verdict even if President Najib decided to pardon him.
   ``It is difficult to put a sense of timing,'' one said privately.
``It can be one month, three months or even six months.''
   O'Brien ``felt isolated in the early stages, but now he is aware
what is being done, what his friends are doing,'' she said.
   Many embassies in Kabul closed before the Soviets left, because
of a widespread belief that the Afghan army could not be able to
guarantee the security of the capital.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in December
1979. An estimated 115,000 Red Army soldiers were in Afghanistan
when the withdrawal began last year.
</TEXT>
