<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InsuranceRollback     06-28 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insurance Rollback,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevada Legislature Approves 20 Percent Insurance Rate Rollback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto insurers have promised a court
challenge of legislation that would force them to roll back rates to
15 percent below July 1988 levels for new policies starting next
October.
   The measure was passed Tuesday by the state Assembly and Senate
and sent to Gov. Bob Miller, and aides said the governor will sign
it.
   Nevada has the fifth-highest car insurance rates in the nation,
with an average premium of $600 per driver, according to the state
insurance commissioner.
   The measure would let insurers raise rates only if they could
prove to the insurance commissioner that they would go bankrupt
without the increase.
   ``That is the toughest, in my opinion, rate rollback bill in
America,'' said Assemblyman Gene Porter, who negotiated the rollback
with the Senate.
   The Assembly approved the measure 37-5 and the state Senate then
voted 16-4 for it.
   Auto insurers termed unconstitutional a provision taking into
account profits from fire, health and life insurance when deciding
whether an insurer could raise rates on auto liability coverage.
   ``The language in this bill is more patently unconstitutional
than the language in Prop. 103,'' American Insurance Assocation
spokesman Jim Wadhams said, referring to a California rate rollback.
Parts of Proposition 103 were struck down by that state's Supreme
Court on grounds they denied insurers a fair return on their
investments.
   Wadhams also complained that lawmakers hadn't let insurers
participate in compromise negotiations.
   The insurance commissioner's office estimates auto insurance
prices have risen 5 percent in the last year, making the bill's
average rollback more than 20 percent.
   State Sen. Bob Coffin criticized the bill as inadequate, saying
legislators were winning safe political gains by voting for a bill
they knew a court would strike down later as unconstitutional.
   ``It's probably the Assembly version of `crack' cocaine: they're
going to feel good for a few minutes and then it will go away,''
Coffin said.
   State Sen. Nick Horn said lawmakers nearing the end of the
legislative session finally had to respond to voters' calls to
control insurance costs.
   ``We've been hearing tales of price-gouging all along,'' Horn
said. ``This finally serves the people by providing some rollbacks.''
   Porter, who headed a study commission on auto insurance costs,
had submitted 14 different insurance reform proposals this session,
including a rate rollback of as much as 37 percent.
   After the Senate Commerce and Labor Committee delayed action on
that rollback, lawmakers agreed to insert Porter's insurance rules
into a 10 percent rollback proposed by state Sen. Jack Vergiels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
