<DOCNO> AP890628-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Poland     06-28 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urged to Provide New Aid to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish-American leaders urged President Bush on
Wednesday to provide millions of dollars in new aid for Poland to
forestall economic turmoil that could doom moves toward democracy in
the communist bloc nation.
   They said Bush assured them he has already begun talking with
Western allies about debt relief for Poland, which Bush will visit
July 9-11.
   The Polish American Congress leaders, including president Edward
J. Moskal of Chicago, did not put a price tag on how big a relief
package they had in mind, other than saying it should be a
``multimillion dollar'' one.
   Bush went to the Polish-American community of Hamtramck, Mich.,
April 17 to propose new aid for Poland tied to government reforms,
including recognition of Solidarity, debt-relief and moves to
encourage private enterprise.
   Bush reiterated Tuesday that he would have an aid package for
Poland, but said he will insist ``that Poland itself will have taken
the steps necessary to have the money well-spent. I don't want to
just push money down the drain.''
   Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, said the aid package
is still being developed in the National Security Council.
   Poland owes $39 billion, only $2.5 billion of it to the United
States.
   Asked if they were satisfied with the approach Bush outlined in
Hamtramck, Moskal said, ``We'd like to see a little more, but we
didn't come asking for pie in the sky.''
   Moskal, who is also president of the Polish National Alliance,
said, ``We need some substantial assistance, primarily with private
enterprise, restructuring of the loan, aid for the ecological
situation there, the agriculture situation _ a general uplifting.
   ``We're also looking for some sign that the people will be able
to grasp and say, well, there's a future for them yet,'' he said.
   ``There's so much need over there. ... The economy's a shambles.
You've got 45 years of communism over there, which is nothing less
than bankruptcy,'' said Moskal.
   He said Bush told them he was advocating restructuring of Polish
debt in the Paris Club of creditor nations, in the International
Montetary Fund and in the World Bank.
   ``There are steps being taken and from what we gathered, there
are steps already being taken with the other Western allies,''
including Great Britain, West Germany and France, he said.
   In Poland, Moskal said, both the communist government and the
Solidarity movement ``realize what the stakes are. ... Nobody's
looking for a China solution over there.''
   Jan Nowak, national director of the Polish American Congress,
``What is needed is something that would allay the danger of some
upheaval in the next six months.''
   ``Any suppression by force of massive strikes or riots would
bring to power Stalinists ... hard-liners who are already feeding on
the election defeat, and that would mean the Chinese scenario,' said
Nowak.
   ``If the Polish experiment would end in failure following so soon
the Chinese experience, it would have a tremendous negative impact
on the process of changes in the entire Soviet orbit,'' said Nowak.
``So the stakes are very high. I have an impression the president
understands this very well.''
</TEXT>
