<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Spy     06-28 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Spy,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>KGB Chief Says American Spy Committed Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. Navy intelligence analyst who spied
for the Soviet Union cracked under the pressure of his work before
he committed suicide, the head of the KGB said Wednesday.
   Defector Glenn Michael Souther killed himself June 22 at age 32,
according to Soviet officials.
   ``His nervous system could not stand the pressure,'' said Gen.
Vladimir Kryuchkov.
   After his obituary in the Soviet military newspaper Red Star
listed his name as Mikhail Y. Orlov, speculation arose that Souther
had been a Soviet mole, but Kryuchkov discounted that, saying he was
a native-born American.
   Souther never admitted spying. He had been under investigation by
the FBI when he disappeared in 1986 from his job as a civilian
intelligence specialist in the Navy's 2nd Fleet headquarters in
Norfolk, Va.
   His obituary Tuesday in Red Star, an illustrated article on him
Wednesday in the government newspaper Izvestia, and Kryuchkov's
comments amounted to unusual publicity for any KGB officer and a
rare Soviet admission of spying.
   But Kryuchkov shrugged off the disclosures, saying, ``You have
spies, we have spies.''
   Soviet reports on Souther's death said he was driven to betray
his country because of a fear of nuclear war and a growing interest
in Russian culture.
   His nerves were a problem even in the ``several years'' he spied
before defecting in 1986, Kryuchkov told reporters outside the
meeting hall of the Soviet legislature.
   ``He long ago started to show a nervous state of mind. He was a
gifted, emotional, caring, sensitive person. He was easily hurt,''
the KGB chief said.
   Kryuchkov would not say how Souther took his life, but that ``the
motive was not political.''
   He said Souther left a note thanking the Soviet government for
what it did for him personally.
   Izvestia said Souther took the name Mikhail Orlov only after he
arrived in the Soviet Union. It said he was born in Hammond, Ind.,
which the FBI confirmed.
   Souther's parents, brother and sister traveled to Moscow for his
military funeral Monday, the KGB chief said. He was buried in the
military section of Kuntsevo Cemetery, the resting place of British
traitor Kim Philby.
   The Izvestia article was accompanied by two photographs, one of a
clean-shaven Souther at a chess board and the other showing him with
a full dark beard.
   Souther enlisted in the U.S. Navy in 1975 and became petty
officer first class before being honorably discharged in 1982,
according to U.S. records.
   Izvestia said he served as a military photographer aboard the
nuclear-powered aircraft carrier Nimitz in the U.S. 6th Fleet, and
on other Navy ships in the Mediterranean Sea.
   ``There he comprehended the real danger of the nuclear threat,
which pushed him into fight against it in the ranks of Soviet
intelligence,'' Izvestia said.
   Souther then went to work for U.S. Nayy intelligence analyzing
satellite photographs and worked with top-secret information at the
Norfolk base, Izvestia said. It was there his worries over nuclear
war led to an ``internal breakup,'' the newspaper said.
   Through his Russian language studies at Old Dominion University
in Virginia, he ``saw in the U.S.S.R. a country that was closer to
his soul and his convictions,'' Izvestia said.
   Some of the people who knew Souther at Old Dominion speculated he
committed suicide because of his disillusionment with the Soviet
Union.
   ``They used him like a spider playing with a moth and when they
were going to finish with him, they finished with him,'' said
Barbara Fahey, a professor's wife who knew him in school.
   Ronald Kessler, a U.S. writer preparing a book on Souther, said
the defector referred to ``my life's vicissitudes'' in a letter he
sent the writer this month. ``He was perhaps having second thoughts
or having trouble adjusting over there,'' Kessler said.
   Souther was survived by a Russian wife and an 18-month-old
daughter, according to Soviet news reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-JapanPhones     06-28 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan Phones,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accord Reached on US Access to Tokyo Cullular Phone Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan, facing the threat of heavy trade
sanctions, has agreed to open its multibillion-dollar Tokyo
marketplace to U.S. cellular telephones and to loosen restraints on
business radios, U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said
Wednesday.
   The agreement, which focused on Motorola Inc.'s attempts to
extend its cellular business into the lucrative Tokyo-Nagoya region,
averts a showdown on July 10, when the United States had said it was
prepared to slap tariffs of as much as 100 percent on more than 50
Japanese electronics imports.
   Mrs. Hills, who announced the agreement after talks here with
officials representing Japan's Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications, said she hoped the settlement ``will be a
precedent for the entire telecommunications market in Japan.''
   The United States had a trade deficit with Japan of about $52
billion last year, and the Motorola problem became a test of how new
Japanese Prime Minister Sosuke Uno would treat the festering
U.S.-Japan trade issue.
   The agreement affects cellular phones and ``third-party'' radios,
such as equipment used for dispatching taxis and delivery trucks,
and pagers.
   It will be particularly advantageous for Motorola's new
pocket-sized cellular phone, which the company is just bringing to
market at about $2,500 a copy.
   Motorola, the principal American maker of cellular phones and
business radios, had contended the Japanese restrictions cost $2
billion in lost sales over five years.
   ``The measures should provide immediate improvements for U.S.
companies in these two high-growth segments of the Japanese
telecommunications market,'' Mrs. Hills said. ``There should be
significant additional benefits when fully implemented.''
   She said the agreement forestalls U.S. retaliation against
Japanese exports.
   Mrs. Hills said the Japanese agreed to changes in licensing
procedures for third-party radio companies, improved access to the
broadcast spectrum needed for third-party radio and cellular phones
sold by foreign companies and ``adoption of other rules which will
treat foreign third-party radio companies on a more equitable
basis.''
   The list of potential targets for higher U.S. tariffs had
included Japanese color television sets, tape recorders and
photocopying machines. That variety of goods, including some of the
most popular Japanese electronic devices sold in this country,
emphasized how seriously the administration was taking this issue.
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., who led a campaign by 16 members of
the House to persuade the Japanese to negotiate, said, ``Once the
Japanese realized we were deadly serious about this problem, they
moved quickly to help settle it. Today's agreement is proof positive
that our trade law can work to help open markets and also that we
should not be shy about confronting our trading partners on problems
such as this.''
   The U.S. trade representative's office on April 28 declared that
Japan had violated a 1986 trade agreement by limiting Motorola's
sales. It said the United States would act against Japanese products
on July 10.
   Informal negotiations have been held for the past several weeks,
and Japan sent an envoy, Ichiro Ozawa, to Washington last week for
stepped-up talks.
   Motorola, which is based in Schaumberg, Ill., has sold its
cellular phones in Japan since 1987 through a Japanese company,
Daini-Denden Inc. But Motorola's phones would not work in Japan's
largest market, the Tokyo area, because the Motorola equipment is
not compatible with the cellular phone network operated by the
Nippon Telegraph &amp; Telephone Corp.
   The Japanese government had said there was not enough space
available on Tokyo's crowded airwaves to accommodate Motorola's
system. But last year the government assigned new frequencies to a
Japanese company, Convenience Radio Telephone, prompting Motorola to
complain to the Bush administration, Motorola spokesman Rusty
Brashear said.
   In the negotiations, the Japanese agreed to shift allocations of
airwave space from a Japanese company, IDO, to allow Motorola's
agent, Daini-Denden, access part of the broadcast spectrum in the
Tokyo area immediately. Further access will be phased in later in
Tokyo and other areas of the country for both DDI and IDO, Brashear
said.
</TEXT>
