<FIRST>r a AM-ByrneKilling     06-28 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Byrne Killing,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Defendant Gets Life In Rookie Cop Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of firing five shots into the
head of a rookie police officer allegedly on behalf of a jailed drug
lord was sentenced Wednesday to a maximum 25-years-to-life term in
prison.
   David McClary, 23, received the sentence from Judge Thomas
Demakos at state court in Queens, where he was convicted on June 6.
   ``You showed no compassion or regard for the life of another
human being,'' Demakos said. ``Society, in turn, should have no
compassion or regard for your life by placing you permanently behind
bars.''
   McClary also received a concurrent 5- to 15-year term on a
weapons charge _ the same sentence his three co-defendants received
from Demakos.
   Demakos told McClary his last act as a judge will be to urge that
the state parole board never release the killer.
   The Byrne murder received national attention during the 1988
presidential campaign when the slain officer's father, Matthew
Byrne, presented his son's shield to President Bush during a
pro-death penalty rally.
   Byrne was guarding the home of a drug case witness on Feb. 26,
1988, when he was shot to death. Prosecutors charged Philip Copeland
masterminded the killing, while Todd Scott was the lookout and Scott
Cobb was the getaway driver.
   All three are serving 25-years-to-life sentences in the slaying.
Prosecutors said the killing was ordered by reputed drug kingpin
Howard ``Pappy'' Mason to avenge his jailing on a weapons charge.
Mason has not been charged in Byrne's death.
</TEXT>
