<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Romania 1stLd-Writethru a0568 06-28 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Romania, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0568,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceausescu Nominated for Re-Election as Romanian Party Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Ceausescu quotes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu strongly
criticized reforms in the Soviet bloc and made clear he does not
intend to adopt them, Romania's official Agerpress news agency said
Wednesday.
   Ceausescu made the comments in a speech to the Communist Party's
Central Committee after being unanimously nominated for re-election
to the party leadership, Agerpres said.
   ``We must take a firm attitude against any attempts to denigrate
socialism,'' Ceausescu was quoted as telling the Bucharest meeting.
   ``One should firmly reject the attempts of the reactionary,
imperialist circles to destabilize and blacken socialism for the
obvious purpose of checking or, at least, delaying ... the nations'
march for progress,'' Ceausescu reportedly said.
   Hungary, Poland and the Soviet Union have adopted reforms that
grant the private economy some role in the overall national economy.
   In Romania, East Germany and Czehcolsovakia, however, the
communist leaderships have either rejected the need for change or
adopted only cautious economic reforms.
   The party leader will be chosen when Romania's Communist Party
convenes its 14th congress on Nov. 20-25.
   At the last two congresses in 1979 and 1984, Ceausescu also was
nominated as the sole candidate for the top party job. His
subsequent election was a foregone conclusion.
   ``We are fully confident that this historic proposal springs from
the love, regard and gratitude of the Central Committee members, of
all (Romanian) communists,'' said Politburo member Manea Manescu in
backing Ceausescu's nomination.
</TEXT>
