<FIRST>r w AM-Navy-IndianOcean     06-28 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy-Indian Ocean,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Eases Deployment of Aircraft Carriers in Indian Ocean</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thanks to the continuing cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war, the Pentagon has decided it can revise its deployment
policy for the Indian Ocean to one that doesn't require the
continuous presence of an aircraft carrier, defense officials said
Wednesday.
   The officials, who insisted on anonymity, said the United States
had no intention of withdrawing its naval forces from the Indian
Ocean or the Persian Gulf.
   But with the truce still holding in the Iran-Iraq war, ``we don't
need a non-stop presence,'' explained one official. ``We don't need
an aircraft carrier parked outside the Persian Gulf.''
   Before 1980 and the Iranian hostage crisis, the United States
routinely sent aircraft carrier battle groups to the Indian Ocean on
a staggered basis, leaving gaps of as much as a month or two. As
hostilities then heated up in the Persian Gulf, that policy was cast
aside in favor of keeping at least one aircraft carrier on station
outside the gulf at all times.
   ``But the cease-fire between Iran and Iraq will have held up for
a year in August, so we're going back to our old approach,''
explained one source.
   Although it attracted little attention, the first gap in the Navy
presence already has occurred. The aircraft carrier Ranger was
allowed to depart its station outside the gulf in the northern
Arabian Sea before a replacement, the America, arrived in the region.
   The America just steamed through the Suez Canal into the Indian
Ocean, one official said Wednesday, but such gaps in coverage will
become commonplace starting this fall.
   The source also said the Navy would occasionally send in battle
groups built around battleships instead of aircraft carriers.
   Another official said the change in policy was driven in part by
the recent budget decision of Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to
maintain 14 carriers in the Navy instead of 15.
   A second source downplayed that factor, however, saying the key
reason for the change was the end to the fighting between Iran and
Iraq.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     06-28 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Get Their Turn at Forming Coalition Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in their 71-year
history, Greece's communists were given a chance Wednesday to form a
government after the socialists and conservatives failed to do so.
   The Coalition of the Left and Progress seemed set on using its
three-day mandate to discuss possibilities of a ``national unity
government.'' But efforts to form an all-party government were
hampered by the two larger parties' insistence on leading it.
   National elections June 18 failed to produce a winner. The
Coalition, an anti-American grouping of the Greek Communist Party
and the Eurocommunist Greek Left, emerged as the power broker with
28 seats in the 300-seat unicameral Parliament.
   The conservative New Democracy Party won 145 seats. The
Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK, came in second with 125
seats, ending eight years of socialist rule.
   Coalition leader Harilaos Florakis has been general secretary of
the Communist Party since 1974, when it was legalized after the fall
of the military dictatorship. It was founded in 1918.
   The Coalition rejected a joint-rule proposal by PASOK leader
Andreas Papandreou, the hospitalized caretaker premier, whose
mandate to form a government ended Tuesday night. Before that, the
conservatives had tried to form a government.
   Florakis said his party proposed a government of ``widespread
acceptance'' that would not be led by Papandreou or New Democracy
leader Constantine Mitsotakis.
   Mitsotakis ruled out formation of a government that would not be
headed by himself.
   ``How is it possible for the 13 percent of the Greek people to
impose their will on the 44 percent?'' Mitsotakis said.
   New Democracy won 44 percent of the vote, PASOK 39 and the
Coalition 13 percent.
   If the Coalition cannot form a government by Friday, President
Christos Sartzetakis will ask the three major parties to try to set
aside their differences and form a coalition. If that fails, the
president will call early elections under a caretaker administration.
   PASOK officials have tried to reach an agreement with the
communists on a long-term coalition but rejected proposals that did
not give Papandreou the premiership.
   The Coalition, a strongly anti-American party, calls for the
removal of U.S. military bases in Greece and withdrawal from NATO.
   Papandreou has pledged to put any new agreement with the
Americans on the four bases to a national referendum. The previous
agreement ended in December.
   ``Cooperation on national issues includes a referendum on the
bases,'' said Akis Tsohatzopoulos, a member of PASOK's executive
bureau.
   Tsohatzopoulos was appointed to negotiate with the communists
because Papandreou was still in Athens' General State Hospital.
   Papandreou was hospitalized Thursday for pneumonia but later
developed heartand kidney complications. A hospital bulletin
Wednesday said he was ``no longer in critical condition and in 2-3
days we will be able to say when he will be dismissed.''
</TEXT>
