<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Iran     06-28 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Iran,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Company Cancels Deal to Ship Chemicals to Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company said Wednesday it has
canceled a contract to supply Iran with chemicals produced in India
that could be used to make poison gas.
   The Rheineisen Chemical Products company of Duesseldorf made the
announcement after West German officials began an investigation into
whether the firm had violated federal export laws. It said the
delivery would not be made.
   Also on Wednesday, federal officials announced West Germany was
trying to block delivery of 257 tons of thionyl chloride before it
left India for Iran.
   The Duesseldorf company acknowledged it arranged the deal, but an
attorney for the company said customs officials had told it the
shipment to Iran would not violate export laws.
   ``A customs employee confirmed on May 22 that there were no
objections to the shipment,'' said attorney Georg Greeven.
   Dieter Vogel, spokesman for the Economics Ministry, said
Rheineisen could face prosecution if it is determined an export
permit was required for the shipment. The company did not apply for
such a permit, he said.
   West German authorities say the investigation into the deal was
begun after U.S. officials last week alerted Bonn about the
Duesseldorf company's involvement.
   West Germany has been trying to crack down on illegal exports
since allegations last year that German companies helped build a
Libyan plant that U.S. officials said was intended to produce
chemical weapons.
   Libya said the plant was making pharmaceuticals.
   West German authorities arrested the head of the Imhausen-Chemie
company in connection with the Libyan deal.
   Greeven said Rheineisen was able ``at the last moment'' to keep
the first delivery of the chemicals from being loaded aboard a ship
in India. He did not give other details.
   ``The company will not be resuming this transaction,'' he said.
   Greeven said the chemicals were made by a company in India called
Transpec. He did not give the location of the firm. He also did not
indicate whether Rheineisen knew the chemical could be used to make
mustard gas.
   Company spokesman Juergen Tigler said ``if officials had
expressed any objections'' to the deal ``the whole thing would have
been called off.''
   Doris Grimm, spokeswoman for the Transport Ministry, said a West
German shipping company owns the vessel slated to transport the
chemicals. She refused to identify the ship or the company.
   She also said the vessel is flying the flag of a foreign country,
which under West German law could make prosecution of its owners
impossible.
</TEXT>
