<HEAD>Bush Will Meet With South African Anti-Apartheid Activist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will meet Friday with
anti-apartheid activist Albertina Sisulu to pay tribute to her
``courageous personal struggle for human rights,'' the White House
said Wednesday.
   Mrs. Sisulu, 71, and her family have become a symbol of the
struggle of South Africa's blacks against apartheid.
   Bush extended an invitation to Mrs. Sisulu to visit the United
States last month after he met with Bishop Desmond Tutu and other
anti-apartheid leaders at the White House.
   ``The president will recognize her for her courageous personal
struggle for human rights and dignity,'' Fitzwater said.
   Mrs. Sisulu, a nurse by profession, is one of three joint
presidents of the United Democratic Front, treasurer of the Women's
League of the outlawed African National Congress and a founder of
the Federation of South African Women.
   Her husband, Walter Sisulu, has been serving a jail sentence
since 1964 for helping found the guerrilla arm of the African
National Congress along with its jailed leader, Nelson Mandela.
   Two of her five children have fled into exile to avoid arrest,
and Mrs. Sisulu has served various jail terms and been under house
arrest and other government restrictions for 18 years.
   The government of South Africa gave her a 31-day passport to make
the visit, the first time she has been allowed out of the country.
   Bush has opposed further economic sanctions against the minority
white-ruled government of South Africa, other than the limited
sanctions his predecessor, Ronald Reagan, was forced to impose by
Congress in 1986 over his veto.
   But Bush has endorsed a more forceful U.S. role in pressing for
an end apartheid and political rights to South Africa's blacks, who
outnumber the whites, 28 million to 5 million.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is scheduled to meet here
with month with F.W. De Klerk, who is expected to assume his
country's president later this year.
   It will be the first official visit by a South African government
leader to this capital in 30 years.
