<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     06-28 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Suggests Palme Killed in International Conspiracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENE MURDOCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers on Wednesday asked a court to
hear an intelligence agent testify that Prime Minister Olof Palme
may have been shot as part of an international conspiracy.
   The request came in the third week of the trial of Christer
Pettersson, who is charged with shooting Palme on Feb. 28, 1986, as
the Swedish leader walked home from a movie with his wife, Lisbeth.
   Pettersson, a confessed drug abuser with a long criminal record,
denies the killing.
   Lawyer Arne Liljeros asked for permission to call Jan-Henrik
Barrling, a Swedish security police officer who investigated a
militant Kurdish separatist group called the PKK, or Kurdish Workers
Party, in connection with the assassination.
   ``We want to establish that the PKK lead is still the most
credible,'' Liljeros said.
   Prosecutor Anders Helin objected that Barrling's value as a
witness is ``not very high, since all the information he can give is
secondhand.''
   The court will decide Thursday whether to call Barrling, said
Judge Carl Anton Spak.
   The Kurdish separatists were the focus of a yearlong
investigation by Stockholm police chief Hans Holmer, who was sacked
when he failed to prove a connection and refused to give up his
theory of a plot.
   Police on Wednesday began investigating Holmer on suspicion of
misappropriating funds, Sweden's national TT news agency reported.
   The Kurdish group was branded a terrorist organization by the
Palme government, which also denied refugee status to one of its
leaders. Telephone taps of some separatist members before the
killing appeared to indicate some sort of plot.
   Barrling has been linked to a group that privately pursued the
Kurdish connection. He was indicted for helping smuggle in illegal
eavesdropping equipment, and awaits trial. Justice Minister
Anna-Greta Leijon was forced to resign for supporting the amateur
detectives.
   The prosecution's case rests on Lisbeth Palme's identification of
Pettersson, 42, in court as the man she saw a few feet away after
her husband fell to the ground, fatally wounded.
   In court Wednesday, three passersby testified that only one
person was close enough to Palme to shoot him, although none could
support Mrs. Palme's identification. Two of the witnesses saw the
man fire a gun.
   Leif Ljungkvist, who was stopped at a traffic light when he heard
the shooting, said he saw a man standing near the fallen premier
stare for several seconds before turning slowly away and fleeing up
a side street. He indicated Mrs. Palme had plenty of time to see the
gunman.
   But he also said Mrs. Palme was unresponsive and ``in a state of
shock'' when he approached her two minutes after the shooting. She
has testified she was clear-headed.
   A social worker who knew Pettersson in jail also testified that
the accused showed ``a deep-rooted hatred of authorities,'' which
prosecutors say could have been his motive.
</TEXT>
