<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Cyprus     06-28 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Cyprus,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Cypriot Leader Urges Direct Talks; Rejects U.N. Mediation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Turkish Cypriot leader on Wednesday
rejected U.N. mediation in the Mediterranean island dispute and
called for direct talks with his Greek Cypriot rival.
   ``We are negotiating. We are not negotiating with the United
Nations. The U.N. is there to help us as good offices people,'' said
Rauf Denktash, president of the breakaway state in northern Cyprus.
   ``We must have direct, sincere, face-to-face talks so that we
know what each side is thinking and producing,'' Denktash said after
meeting with Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   The Turkish Cypriot's insistence is considered a major
complication in negotiations to reunify the island, which entered a
new round in New York.
   Denktash also called for more publicity, instead of current
secret talks.
   There was no immediate reaction from the Greek Cypriot side or
U.N. officials.
   In the past 10 months, the talks have made virtually no progress,
and no breakthrough is expected.
   ``We are not near any solution,'' Denktash said. ``The main
fundamental difficulties exist and no one can belittle them. But ...
the fact that we intend to continue talks is a good sign.''
   Denktash and his Greek Cypriot rival, George Vassiliou, president
of the Republic of Cyprus, met the U.N. chief Wednesday for less
than an hour each to prepare for a joint meeting Thursday.
   Vassiliou, who represents the only internationally recognized
government of Cyprus, said Wednesday he hopes for progress in what
he called a ``crucial stage of negotiations.''
   Denktash's government is recognized only by Turkey, which invaded
Cyprus in 1974 to prevent a possible union with Greece and halt
alleged persecution of the island's Turkish minority.
   Cyprus today is divided into Greek and Turkish sectors, with U.N.
troops patrolling a buffer zone between the two. About 40,000
Turkish troops are in the north of the island.
   The two sides are discussing creation of a federated state. Greek
Cypriots want a strong central government and Turkish Cypriots a
loose federation and equality of the two communities.
   Denktash's region occupies 37 percent of Cyprus and has 120,000
residents, mostly Moslems, who comprise 18 percent of the island's
population.
</TEXT>
