<FIRST>r a AM-WheelchairMarathoner     06-28 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wheelchair Marathoner,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marathoner Completes 5,000-Mile Cross-Country Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 27-year-old wheelchair marathoner rolled across
the Brooklyn Bridge to City Hall on Wednesday, completing a
5,000-mile cross-country trip to raise money for spinal cord
research.
   Joseph W. ``Bill'' Duff, a paraplegic since an auto accident in
1982, was met by Mayor Edward I. Koch, who placed a laurel wreath on
his head, and applauded by about 200 people in City Hall Plaza.
   He said he had made the trip not only to fund research but to
tell disabled people, ``If you put your mind to it, you could do
anything.''
   His muscular biceps showed bruises from rubbing against the
wheels of his chair.
   Koch said Duff told him that his greatest joy was meeting the
people in the 475 towns in 20 states through which the 111-day trip
took him. He started Jan. 17 in Los Angeles.
   ``They were what you expect Americans to be,'' Koch said. ``They
admire courage. They admire intestinal fortitude. They admire people
who overcome. That is why he is very special.''
   Duff wore shorts and a white T-shirt covered with medals from
various communities as he wheeled the final mile over the bridge in
a light drizzle.
   Asked how he had managed to push 50 miles a day, he said, ``when
you become paralyzed, you find how much you take for granted as far
as physically what you can do.''
   ``It's very easy to take the self-pity road and say, `Why me?',
and be very bitter. That's the easy path,'' he said.
   ``The most difficult path, the most challenging path is to say,
`OK! This is what life has dealt me. I can handle it. I'll be happy
at it and I'll make the best I can of it and be all I can be and try
to help my fellow man.''
   Duff, who lives in Houston and received a bachelor's degree in
mechanical engineering at the University of Texas two years ago,
undertook the marathon under the sponsorship of ``Wheels Across
America.''
   A donation of $336,000 raised by several corporations for the
marathon was issued through the sponsor Wednesday to the Miami
Project To Curb Paralysis at the University of Miami Jackson
Memorial Medical Center.
   The spokesman for the project is Marc Buoniconti, son of former
all-pro Miami Dolphin linebacker Nick Buoniconti. The younger
Buoniconti was injured while playing college football in 1985 and is
a quadriplegic.
</TEXT>
