<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Legislature     06-28 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Million Layoffs Under Economic Reforms, Reform Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy is in a state of emergency, and up to
15 million people will lose their jobs during its restructuring, the
official in charge of economic reform said at his confirmation
hearing Wednesday.
   Leonid Abalkin painted the bleak picture before the new Supreme
Soviet legislature, which approved his nomination as head of State
Commission on Economic Reform, a job carrying the rank of deputy
premier.
   Abalkin was among four Cabinet members confirmed Wednesday after
the legislature rejected, for the first time in Soviet history, a
slate of nominees for the government positions.
   ``The situation in the country is that of an emergency,'' Abalkin
said. ``Within the last year and a half, the economic situation has
been worsening with every passing month.''
   The economist said 12 million to 15 million people will become
unemployed as a result of reform by the end of the century,
according to remarks carried by the Tass news agency.
   Abalkin said the layoffs will occur as the country moves from
emphasis on production to services and as the labor force is
redistributed from state businesses to private cooperatives and
family-run businesses.
   Other economists have said unemployment will result from
streamlining the government and industry and shifting resources
within the economy.
   Abalkin, the 59-year-old director of the Institute of Economics,
told the legislators the unemployed will need job retraining,
occupational counseling and other social programs.
   Traditional Communist Party doctrine has said unemployment is
solely a Western problem resulting from exploitation of the working
class. But President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program of perestroika,
or economic restructuring, is causing widespread realignment of the
Soviet labor force.
   Abalkin predicted that efforts to make the economy
market-oriented will be successful in six to seven years, at which
time the Soviet currency, the ruble, can be made convertible.
   At it stands, the ruble cannot be freely converted into other
currency, and that severely hampers foreign companies trying to do
business in the Soviet Union.
   Abalkin took the podium after his confirmation and said Soviet
efficiency must be improved.
   ``We have a budget deficit of 100 billion rubles ($156 billion)
this year,'' he said. ``There are two ways to eliminate it. Cut
expenditures or increase revenues.''
   Abalkin explained the poor Soviet standard of living with the
comment: ``We live no worse than we work.''
   Deputies laughed and then applauded.
   Under questioning from the 542-member Supreme Soviet, another
Cabinet nominee, Yuri Maslyukov, chairman of the government planning
agency Gosplan, said his agency would drastically reduce central
planning of the economy. He was then confirmed as both the new
Gosplan chairman and first deputy premier.
   Deputy Igor Griazin of Estonia said he had expected more
controversy over the 52-year-old Maslyukov, but the Gosplan chief
promised his agency would confine itself to setting major economic
factors such as the federal budget, raw materials and military
production, leaving details to the republics.
   ``Two months ago, he was opposed to all this,'' Griazin said.
``This is a new guy. I like him very much.''
   There were only six votes against Maslyukov. The hands raised to
vote `yes' were not counted as they were a clear majority.
   Lev Voronin, 61, a bureaucrat in the state supply committee, was
confirmed as a first deputy premier in charge of general matters.
   Igor Belousov, nominated as deputy premier and head of the State
Commission for Military-Industrial Affairs, told the lawmakers that
by 1995, 60 percent of the defense industry's production will be
civilian goods. Those goods will include equipment to process crops,
consumer items, medical equipment, electronics, computers and
communications devices, Belousov said.
   Gorbachev has said the defense industry will be called on to
tackle production of items in chronically short supply, namely food
and consumer goods.
   On Tuesday, Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov withdrew seven of his Cabinet
nominees after the newly elected legislature refused to support them.
   Six of the nominees were rejected in first-ever confirmation
hearings last week by committees of the Supreme Soviet, which this
year replaced the old rubber-stamp legislature. The previous
legislature did not have the power to confirm or reject top
government officials.
   The Supreme Soviet is the country's first full-time
representative legislature, a branch of the larger Congress of
People's Deputies chosen this spring in the first nationwide
contested elections in seven decades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
