<DOCNO> AP890628-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba     06-28 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Testimony in Ochoa Case Indicates Cuban Involvement in Venezuela</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony in the case of a Cuban military hero who
confessed to smuggling drugs, ivory and diamonds hinted at
involvement by Fidel Castro's communist government in a secret
operation in Venezuela.
   Several witnesses told a military tribunal Maj. Gen. Arnaldo
Ochoa had been an ``internacionalista'' in Venezuela.
   ``Internacionalista'' is a term Cubans use to describe someone
willing to fight anywhere in the world for the ideals of Castro's
communist revolution.
   Ochoa, 57, is believed to have served with a team of military
advisers to Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government in addition to
commanding Cuban troops in Angola and Ethiopia.
   This was the first mention of his name in connection with
Venezuela. Witnesses at the tribunal _ six of eight other officers
arrested earlier this month along with Ochoa _ gave no details and
did not say when his Venezuelan mission occurred.
   Also arrested were Brig. Gen. Patricio de la Guardia Font and his
twin, Col. Antonio de la Guardia Font; Ochoa's assistant, Capt.
Jorge Martinez; Cols. Teudys Trutie Matilla, Antonio Rodriguez
Estupinan and Rafael Morales Velazquez; Lt. Col. Arnaldo Morejon
Plat, and Capt. Jose Llicas Papadedis.
   The military tribunal took testimony only against Ochoa in
hearings Sunday and Monday. The members recommended he be
court-martialed for high treason and, if found guilty, executed by a
firing squad.
   They said Ochoa, decorated for his service as a field commander
in Angola in 1987-1988, had damaged Cuba's reputation and threatened
its national security.
   Defense Minister Raul Castro, Fidel's brother, said Ochoa's
punishment should ``set an example.''
   Witnesses said the general was in league with Colombian drug
smugglers and had helped turn Cuba into a Caribbean stop for
U.S.-bound cocaine.
   An official announcement said the 45 generals and colonels, one
admiral and one rear admiral on the tribunal were unanimous in
recommending the court-martial and ``almost unanimous'' on the death
penalty.
   Videotapes of the hearings were broadcast on state television for
more than six hours until 1 a.m. Wednesday.
   No scenes were shown of testimony by the de la Guardia twins,
although some newscasters said Patricio testified Sunday. There was
no explanation of the omission.
   Castro ordered the investigation that led to the arrests,
according to the official news agency Prensa Latina. Some of those
arrested worked for the Interior Ministry, which is in charge of
internal security.
   Some witnesses confessed their own involvement with the drug,
diamond and ivory traffic, and described hiding money in
refrigerators and under cement slabs in backyards. Nearly all said
their purpose was to help Cuba with its economic problems.
   In his last statement to the court, Ochoa said: ``If this
sentence should come to pass, I want you to know that my last
thought will be for Fidel and the great revolution he has given our
country.''
   He was asked by Ulises Rosales del Toro, president of the court,
whether he had sought to challenge Castro's power or policies, and
replied: ``Of course there is nothing to that. I have never been
opposed to the revolution.''
</TEXT>
