<FIRST>u w AM-DairySupport     06-28 0119</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dairy Support,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milk Price Support to Drop This Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's milk price support will be cut
sharply on July 1, removing a temporary increase ordered by Congress
last year to help drought-stricken milk producers, Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter announced Wednesday.
   Congress specified in the Disaster Assistance Act of 1988 that
milk price supports be boosted 50 cents per 100 pounds from April 1
through June 30. That put the basic support price at $11.10 per
hundredweight. Effective July 1, the support will revert back to the
$10.60 level.
   The National Milk Producers Federation had estimated the
three-month boost of 50 cents per hundredweight provided an
additional $300 million in revenues for dairy farmers.
</TEXT>
