<DOCNO> AP890628-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Zaire     06-28 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Zaire,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobutu Says 100 Percent of His People Support Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire, a key U.S.
ally, rejected allegations Wednesday that his government abuses
human rights, saying he has the support of 100 percent of his people.
   ``I'm sure that you know that in Zaire I enjoy the support of 100
percent of the population,'' Mobuto told reporters after a lengthy
meeting with Secretary of State James A. Baker III. ``Therefore, I
would not victimize my own supporters.''
   The meeting marked the beginning of the African leader's official
visit, which includes a Thursday meeting with President Bush.
   Baker praised Mobutu for his role in helping arrange a cease-fire
that began last week in Angola's 14-year-old civil war. The
breakthrough occurred at an 18-nation summit at which Mobutu was the
host.
   The United States and Zaire have enjoyed close ties for most of
Mobutu's 24-year rule. Zaire has received substantial U.S.
assistance while serving as a transit point for U.S. military
supplies destined for anti-communist rebels in neighboring Angola.
   But Mobutu has been dogged for years by allegations that his
government is corrupt and repressive.
   ``He continues to run the world's pre-eminent `kleptocracy,'''
said Randall Robinson, head of the liberal lobbying group
TransAfrica.
   Robinson alleged that Mobutu has ``siphoned enough funds from
public accounts to private accounts in Switzerland to liquidate the
entire national debt of Zaire.''
   A State Department document cited in a New York Times story two
years ago estimated Mobutu's wealth at more than $5 billion.
   Freedom House, a New York-based group that promotes democracy
around the world, ranks Zaire among the worst human rights violators
in Africa.
   The annual State Department human rights report, released in
February, cited torture and other physical mistreatment of detainees
as the most significant human rights abuses in Zaire.
   State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said Wednesday
that Mobutu has taken steps to correct such abuses.
   ``Human rights problems and deficiencies are part of our ongoing
dialogue with Zaire,'' Boucher said.
   Concern over human rights in Zaire is expected to lead to a
cutback in U.S. military aid to Zaire from $9 million to $3 million
in fiscal 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
