<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-ElSalvador     06-28 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-El Salvador,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Briefed on Civil Rights in El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top El Salvadoran defense official told Vice
President Dan Quayle on Wednesday that President Alfredo Cristiani
will establish a human rights commission in that strife-torn country.
   Rene Emilio Ponce, chief of staff of El Salvador's armed forces,
disclosed the plans in a meeting with Quayle at the White House.
   Quayle spokesman David Beckwith said Ponce informed the vice
president that the commission will be composed of three independent
citizens with a mandate to ensure that the government, including the
military, respects human rights.
   Ponce is considered a leading candidate to become defense
minister in El Salvador under the new, conservative Cristiani
admnistration after the current caretaker minister completes a
six-month term.
   Quayle visited El Salvador last month on his second Central
American trip and admonished right-wing leaders there, including
Cristiani associate Roberto d'Aubuisson, to avoid human rights
abuses.
   Quayle told reporters at the outset of his meeting with Ponce
that he stands by his message of wanting to see ``no embarrassments
to the Cristiani government.''
   ``Let's not have any kind of overreaction to the brutal killings
that have been going (by) the FMLN in El Salvador,'' he said.
   The FMLN was trying to overthrow the government even before
Cristiani's party came to power. It is blamed for several recent
assassinations, including the killing of El Salvador's attorney
general and Jose Antonio Rodriquez Porth, Cristiani's chief of staff.
   Quayle said he met with both right- and left-wing politicians in
El Salvador because he wanted to reach ``as wide a political
spectrum as possible.''
   Some Democrats in Congress have criticized Quayle for meeting
with d'Aubuisson. But Quayle said his critics have been silent about
the killings by the left.
   ``It's a total one-way street and certainly something I don't
accept,'' said Quayle.
   ``They have very narrow minds when it comes to the enforcement of
human rights _ only on one side. We're taking human rights across
the board,'' he said.
   According to Beckwith, Quayle told Ponce the Salvadoran military
has made great progress on its human rights record, and praised it
for refusing to respond to the violent provocations by the FMLN.
</TEXT>
