<FIRST>u a AM-RoseInvestigation     06-28 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rose Investigation,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Rose's Block On Baseball Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court Wednesday upheld
Cincinnati Reds manager Pete Rose's bid to stave off a hearing
before baseball Commissioner A. Bartlett Giamatti, setting up a
possible court fight between the two.
   The 1st Ohio District Court of Appeals gave Rose his second legal
victory in four days, deciding it had no authority to nullify an
order that temporarily blocks Giamatti from holding a hearing to
decide Rose's fate.
   Giamatti is still barred from holding a hearing on allegations
that Rose bet on his own team and from taking any action against the
manager for two weeks.
   Another hearing is scheduled July 6 before Hamilton County Common
Pleas Judge Norbert A. Nadel for a preliminary injunction, which
would extend Rose's protection while the case is prepared for trial.
   If baseball can't block the July 6 hearing, Giamatti will appear
before Nadel to try to convince the judge he is wrong, baseball
lawyer Louis L. Hoynes Jr. said.
   ``The commissioner will certainly be a witness for us,'' Hoynes
said. ``It's important for us, for him, to be here, and he will be
here.''
   In an unpredecented ruling, Nadel decided last Sunday that
Giamatti has prejudged Rose as guilty, and concluded a hearing
before the commissioner would be pointless. Giamatti can suspend
Rose for life if he determines the manager bet on his own team.
   Giamatti said Wednesday that the appeals court didn't decide
whether Nadel was correct in his assessment, but had concluded it
had no authority to act. Giamatti has said he hasn't yet decided
Rose's fate.
   ``They didn't affirm Judge Nadel's finding about me. They just
decided they couldn't decide,'' Giamatti said.
   Hoynes gave no indication of baseball's next legal move, which
could turn to the Ohio Supreme Court.
   Although Rose is unbeaten in the state courts, evidence supplied
by his accusers to baseball could give him trouble with federal
authorities.
   Rose also is being investigated by a federal grand jury in
Cincinnati looking into whether he listed all his income on his tax
returns.
   Testimony in baseball's report on Rose alleges he purposely hid
income from the Internal Revenue Service from race track wagers,
memorabilia sales and public appearances _ offenses that carry the
threat of jail and fines.
</TEXT>
