<FIRST>u w AM-MrsBush-GirlScouts 1stLd-Writethru a0703 06-28 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mrs Bush-Girl Scouts, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Becomes First Girl Scout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 9, bgng, ``She said,'' to insert dropped ``it''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush called it a ``red-letter day,''
but the emphasis was on green Wednesday as she became the 14th
consecutive first lady to serve as honorary president of Girl Scouts
of the U.S.A.
   A hundred Girl Scouts of all ages filled the East Room of the
White House for the investiture ceremony, which began with Mrs. Bush
summoning forth two aides to ``be my props.''
   Down the aisle came chief of staff Susan Porter Rose and staff
member Julia Cooke, both wearing the familiar green sash from their
own scouting days.
   ``You might think I use scout involvement as a criterion for
hiring if you look at the members of my staff,'' said Mrs. Bush.
   ``I'm realy sort of kidding ... but it wouldn't be such a bad
idea, would it?'' she said.
   Mrs. Bush was following a tradition started by Mrs. Woodrow
Wilson in 1917, five years after the Girl Scouts were founded. Today
it counts 2.3 million American girls and 706,000 adults among its
members.
   Mrs. Bush extolled ``the enormous benefits of growing up in this
outstanding organization,'' which includes one in every nine
American girls.
   ``Scouting builds confidence, compassion and self-esteem as no
other experience can. The girl Scout promise _ `Service to God,
Country and Other People' _ prepares millions of women to build
productive lives and contribute so richly to our national
well-being,'' said Mrs. Bush.
   She called it a historic day and ``surely a red-letter day for
me.''
   After getting a membership pin and gold bar from Betty F.
Pilsbury, the scouts' national president, Mrs. Bush joined her
troops in reciting the Girl Scout promise, then repaired down the
hall to the State Room for refreshments.
</TEXT>
