<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     06-28 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Deny They Ordered Honduran President Assassinated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILLA CARLOS FONSECA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega
denied Wednesday that his government ordered President Jose Azcona
Hoyo and three other leaders killed in neighboring Honduras, as a
Nicaraguan deserter claims.
   ``This man is crazy. I wouldn't even want to think that he is
being manipulated by the Honduran government or the gringos
(Americans). This is madness,'' Ortega told The Associated Press.
   Orlando Solorzano Martinez said in Tegucigalpa that the leftist
Sandinista government sent him to Honduras nine months ago to
assassinate Azcona, Roman Catholic Archbishop Hector Enrique Santos
of Tegucigalpa, and presidential candidates Rafael Leonardo Callejas
of the opposition National Party and Carlos Flores Facusse of the
governing Liberal Party.
   Ortega briefly answered questions on a visit he made to this town
near Managua, where he gave 200 peasant families title deeds to
plots of farmland.
   Solorzano spoke at a news conference Tuesday in San Pedro Sula, a
port city 125 miles north of Tegucigalpa, where he is staying.
   He said he and two other military officers entered Honduras in
1988 on a ``secret mission ordered by the Nicaraguan high command .
.. to assassinate political and military leaders in this country.''
   Solorzano said that instead he deserted because he was ``tired of
the corruption and degeneration by the communists in power in my
country.''
   Nicaragua's foreign Minister, Miguel d'Escoto, meanwhile told a
news conference in The Hague, Netherlands, on Wednesday that the
outlook for an early peace settlement in Central America was ``not
... promising.'' He said U.S.-sponsored military in the region were
blocking such an agreement.
   D'Escoto said the civilian presidents of some Central American
nations ``are hostages of the military ... and limited in what they
can do and how far they can go.''
   But he said Nicaragua was going ahead with general elections
scheduled for next year, and that the Sandinistas were ready to
yield power if defeated.
   He said his government ``definitely'' wanted better relations
with the Bush administration, adding: ``We told them that we were
waiting at the (negotiating) table ... but so far, I see no
indications for improvement yet.''
   D'Escoto said Washington still supported Honduras-based rebels
fighting the Managua government despite a 1986 World Court ruling
banning such support.
   D'Escoto was in The Hague to attend a foreign ministers'
conference of the movement of non-aligned countries.
</TEXT>
