<FIRST>r a AM-JailReunion     06-28 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jail Reunion,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>19 Years Later, Father And Son Reunite In Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father and son separated since birth
were reunited after 19 years, but the circumstances of their
surprise meeting were less than ideal _ both men were behind bars.
   Robert Arthur Magoon was in custody for allegedly violating his
parole and his father, Michael Arthur Magoon, was being held on
robbery charges at the Santa Clara County jail.
   He also has warrants pending out of Oakland for investigation of
felony child stealing.
   ``When I first came here, they said, `Do you have a relative
here?''' said Robert, 19. ``I said, `Not that I know of.' ... At
first, I thought it couldn't be possible. For all I knew, he could
have been on the other side of the world.''
   Robert was separated from his father when his parents split up
shortly after he was born. He spent most of his youth in foster
homes. He ran away from the last one at age 14.
   ``I tried to look for him,'' said Robert. ``I tried going to the
(Department of Motor Vehicles) and other places. They just didn't
have any information.''
   Michael also said he tried looking for his long-lost son and had
no idea he was in a foster home.
   Robert, of Modesto, was arrested by police in Santa Clara early
this month and put in jail for allegedly violating his parole from
the California Youth Authority, where he said he served time as a
juvenile for a burglary.
   Michael, meanwhile, lives in Texas but had been arrested by
police in Santa Clara about two months earlier and booked into the
same jail.
   A few jail guards helped the two learn they were in the same
jail, and Michael approached Sgt. Virgil King last week to ask if he
could see his son.
   ``It was a request that was not impossible to accomplish,''said
King. ``I have a motto: It's that you treat people, even though
they're in custody, the way you'd like to be treated.''
   King, who investigated the accounts and found them to be
accurate, set up a meeting for the father and son.
   The two men said they were nervous and excited before their
reunion. They shook hands, hugged and then sat down for their first
talk.
   ``He really surprises me,'' said Michael after the meeting.
``He's so handsome. Tears come to my eyes when I see my boy.''
   Robert said his father told him he wants him to come live with
him in Texas, where he is an auto painter. His father wants to teach
him the trade. Robert also got some advice from his father.
   ``He told me to keep my nose clean,'' recalled Robert.
   Robert also has an older brother neither he nor his father have
seen in years. They both hope to reunite with him, too.
   In the meantime, the father and son are making plans to spend
time together when they are both free.
   ``If we could just get together some day, everything would turn
out right,'' Michael said.
   It could be a while before the two get together.
   Robert is serving a sentence for attempted extortion and will not
be released from jail until July 20. He will then be turned over to
the California Youth Authority.
   Michael has a July 10 trial date in connection with charges of
robbery, petty theft and a weapons violation.
</TEXT>
