<FIRST>u w AM-Guns-Study 1stLd-Writethru a0686 06-28 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guns-Study, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Opposes Gun ID Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to RECAST to show that task force was making
suggestions, sted proposals. Picks up 5th graf pvs `An applicant ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh opposes the
idea of requiring gun buyers to obtain a national identification
card, one of several options outlined by a Justice Department task
force, a spokesman said Wednesday.
   The requirement would be ``an infringement on rights of
Americans,'' said David Runkel, adding that the attorney general
won't recommend that option to President Bush.
   Under the task force suggestion, published this week as part of a
gun-control study, each person who buys a gun would be required to
first obtain a firearms owner's identification card valid for three
years. The study estimated that as many as 5 million cards would be
issued annually.
   An applicant would wait four weeks to six weeks after being
photographed and fingerprinted while police determine if the
individual has been convicted of a felony.
   Thornburgh opposed a similar idea in the 1970s when he headed the
Justice Department's criminal division, Runkel said.
   The identification-card option was one of several ways the task
force offered to prevent felons from obtaining weapons. The task
force didn't recommend any one of the options it suggested.
   The study also noted that criminals would be able to obtain
weapons on the black market even if an effective screening system
could be devised.
   Thornburgh is required by Congress to propose a screening system
by Nov. 18, but won't review the options until a public comment
period ends in September, Runkel said.
   Another option in the 40-page report, published Monday in the
Federal Register, would require the nation's 270,000 gun dealers to
call local police before selling a weapon to determine if the
purchaser has a criminal record.
   There are an estimated 7.5 million gun sales each year.
   Requiring identity cards would force the FBI to hire 1,700
additional clerks to check fingerprints. The system would cost
federal, state and local governments $136 million to $161 million a
year, which could be financed by a user fee of $27 to $32, the study
said.
   Federal law doesn't require checks of those who want to buy guns.
Twenty states, as well as the District of Columbia, require checks
of the buyer's criminal history.
   The task-force study was mandated by Congress last year. Rep.
Bill McCollum, R-Fla., proposed the measure to head off a bill
requiring a seven-day waiting period for gun buyers.
   McCollum's measure was seen by many as an effort by the National
Rifle Association to stall gun control by requiring further study.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
