<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-28 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Weather In The Lower Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms associated with the remains of Tropical Storm
Allison spread heavy rain across the lower Mississippi Valley on
Wednesday, and a band of rain weather extended from that region to
New England.
   Baton Rouge, La., had received more than 11 inches of rain in two
days. The Houston area got over a foot of rain from the storm.
   Numerous roads were closed in the Baton Rouge area and
surrounding parishes and at least 100 homes were flooded.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
2.53 inches at Cape Girardeau, Mo., and 2.51 inches at Baton Rouge.
Paducah, Ky., got 3.57 inches of rain in 3 hours during the morning.
   Showers and thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold front
extended from the lower Mississippi Valley through the middle
Atlantic Coast region to southern New England.
   During the afternoon, a thunderstorm in northern Georgia produced
high wind which blew down at least one large tree in northern Floyd
County, the National Weather Service said.
   Numerous showers and thunderstorms also developed over the
Florida Peninsula during the afternoon.
   Thunderstorms extended from southwestern to northeastern Nebraska
during the afternoon. Morning thunderstorms in north-central
Nebraska produced one inch-diameter hail near Stuart, Amelia and
Burwell. During the afternoon, a thunderstorm produced hail 2 inches
in diameter at Comstock.
   Elsewhere, an approaching storm system brought showers to western
Oregon.
   Highs reached only the 60s and upper 50s in northeastern
Minnesota, northern Wisconsin, Upper Michigan and northern Lower
Michigan, and frost and freeze advisories were posted into Thursday
morning for Upper Michigan.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 102 at Phoenix. Wednesday's low in
the Lower 48 states was 36 at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the eastern half of Texas through Louisiana and Arkansas to
Florida and Georgia. Showers and thunderstorms also were forecast
from eastern Montana to the western Great Lakes region. A cold front
nearing the northern Pacific Coast was expected to produce scattered
showers and thunderstorms over Oregon and Washington.
   Highs in the 60s were predicted over northern Maine and western
sections of the Great Lakes region; in the 60s and 70s from New
England to the Great Lakes region and the northern Ohio Valley; in
the 70s along the California coast and across the Pacific Northwest;
in the lower 90s across Florida, Georgia and South Carolina; in the
90s across much of the high Plains region, the Rockies and the
Southwest; and above 100 from southwestern Texas to the deserts of
southern California.
</TEXT>
