<FIRST>u a AM-ChurchClosings Bjt   06-28 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Closings, Bjt,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Court Shouldn't Settle Religious Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KOLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge refused to grant an injunction
Wednesday for parishioners hoping to keep open 14 Roman Catholic
churches set to be closed in an effort to consolidate waning
membership and finances.
   The request for the injunction was the latest move in a long
fight against the closings by bitter parishioners and clergy in the
1.5 million-member Archdiocese of Detroit.
   Wayne County Circuit Judge James A. Hathaway made the decision
Wednesday, saying courts shouldn't settle religious disputes and,
``It was Jesus' idea that we love one another, and with a little
effort we can do that.''
   Outside the Wayne County Courthouse, more than 150 demonstrators
marched and sang ``We Shall Overcome'' to protest the closings.
   ``This idea of walking around with posters and haranguing each
other _ I don't want to see that. We need to approach the matter
from the point of trying to heal differences rather than exacerbate
them,'' the judge said.
   Hathaway agreed to consider issuing a temporary stay of Cardinal
Edmund Szoka's order to close the churches to give opponents a
chance to go to the Michigan Court of Appeals. A hearing was
scheduled for 2 p.m. Thursday.
   Since January, 16 of 30 parishes targeted to be closed have been
shut down by the Archdiocese of Detroit, including five last
weekend. The closings come under a plan Cardinal Edmund Szoka said
will strengthen the church by creating fewer parishes.
   Szoka said the closings became necessary as hundreds of thousands
of Catholics joined the migration to the suburbs of Detroit in
recent decades. It left fewer than 50,000 Catholics in the nation's
sixth-largest city.
   Detroit's population is approximately 1.1 million; about 4
million people live in the metropolitan area.
   Five parishes have permission to remain open until July 16, four
others have longer extensions tied to priests' retirements or church
anniversaries and the rest are to close by Friday, archdiocese
spokesman Jay Berman said Tuesday.
   Robert Van Cleef, an attorney for the 18 churches that are suing
to stay open, argued Wednesday that Szoka reneged on a promise to
conduct open grievance hearings before closing parishes.
   Szoka's attorney, Joseph Sullivan, said church members wouldn't
suffer by having their parishes closed until all appeals to the
Vatican are exhausted.
   ``It's a little bit difficult for me to understand that
worshiping at a church a few blocks away or a half-mile or a mile
from where one used to worship is a serious problem,'' he said.
   Church members said Wednesday they haven't lost all hopes of
saving their parishes.
   ``All I can say is we're in good company,'' said Leonard Gross, a
member of Our Lady of the Rosary. ``David had a lot of opposition
when he went up against Goliath.''
   Berman said the often-emotional struggle over the closings was a
painful period that is about to end. He expressed hope that Detroit
Catholics would begin working to strengthen the church.
   ``It's fortunate that this is now being brought to a close
because we can now focus on the mission, which is to revitalize and
re-energize the church in the city,'' Berman said.
   Last September, Szoka unveiled a proposal to close or merge 48 of
112 parishes within the city. Initially, members of most targeted
parishes opposed the move, filing internal appeals with the
archbishop.
   On Jan. 8, Szoka said 30 churches would close this year and 25
more would have until 1990 to increase membership and improve their
finances.
   Last week, priests, nuns and parishioners from nine parishes said
they would defy the closing order. In several cases, they have held
services outside locked buildings.
   But determination to resist the closings began to crumble when
Szoka announced last week that the Vatican had rejected appeals
filed in March by 14 parishes.
   Opponents of the closings said they may consider filing an appeal
with the Vatican supreme court, a move Berman said the cardinal
believes would be a waste of time.
   ``This week is pivotal, and the people here will hold a town hall
meeting next Sunday to decide what we will do,'' said the Rev. A.J.
Conti of St. Ignatius of Antioch parish.
</TEXT>
