<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-OwlCompromise     06-28 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Owl Compromise,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Blame Environmentalists For Scuttling Ancient Forest Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last-minute efforts to revive a compromise
aimed at ending the bitter owls-vs.-trees fight over the ancient
forests of the Northwest collapsed Wednesday with most lawmakers
blaming environmentalists for scuttling the proposal.
   After a 45-minute joint meeting of the Oregon and Washington
state delegations, congressmen said they would drop their effort to
attach the compromise to the House interior appropriations bill
Thursday.
   Lawmakers added, however, they would still try to negotiate a
settlement between environmentalists and the timber industry.
   Environmentalists, who on Tuesday rejected the compromise
proposed at a weekend ``timber summit,'' said they, too, were
willing to continue negotiations and thought the proposal offered
the framework for a possible solution, possibly to attach to the
bill when the counterpart Senate committee takes it up.
   Oregon Democratic Rep. Les AuCoin called the decision not to seek
a legislative solution now a ``lost opportunity'' to ensure a
short-term supply of logs for Northwest mills while protecting the
old-growth forests where the rare northern spotted owl lives.
   ``Environmentalists have decided to pursue a strategy that is
shortsighted, politically risky, if not plain dumb,'' said AuCoin.
``I don't think they understand how damned mad the people of the
Northwest will be over the torpedoing of what was a fair, equitable
and balanced proposal.''
   Rep. Al Swift, D-Wash., said that environmentalists have been
able to put a virtual ``stranglehold'' on the supply of timber for
Northwest mills by securing court injunctions barring timber sales
in spotted owl habitat.
   The compromise called for harvesting of 8 billion board feet of
timber from the national forests of the Northwest and 1 billion
board feet from Bureau of Land Management forests in Oregon over the
next 15 months _ roughly the quantity loggers said they needed to
keep area mills running, though not necessarily in the same places.
   The deal also would have ended all court appeals of timber sales
during the period and would have protected large blocks of old
growth from fragmentation by logging roads and scattered clearcuts.
   Environmentalists said they thought the plan was vague and they
did not have adequate time to consider it. They, too, said they were
optimistic about an eventual agreement, despite the criticism from
lawmakers.
   ``There is not a level playing field here,'' said Swift. ``We
must appeal to them (environmentalists) for more flexibility.''
   ``Fingerpointing isn't going to get anything done,'' said Lee
Keller Reis, a spokeswoman for the National Wildlife Federation.
``We have been willing to talk all along and we are still willing to
talk.''
   George Frampton Jr., president of The Wilderness Society, said
negotiations were ``far from over'' and it was just ``unrealistic''
to expect that a compromise proposed on Saturday could be nailed
down so quickly.
   Environmentalists have sought to have the spotted owl, which
nests only in the old-growth forest of Oregon, Washington and
northern California, protected as a threatened or endangered species
as part of their campaign to halt logging in the ancient forests.
Such a designation for any species requires that its habitat be
preserved.
   The industry has claimed such protection would lock up vast
sections of the federal forests to logging, creating economic
catastrophe in dozens of one-mill towns.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has proposed the owl for
listing as a threatened species, but a decision might still be two
years away.
   Timber industry representatives, who had reluctantly accepted the
compromise, said they were not surprised the lawmakers had decided
not to pursue legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
