<FIRST>r a AM-ChinaSpy     06-28 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China Spy,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Declares Himself Chinese Spy, Wants to Sever Ties to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegate to a convention of a
dissident Chinese group declared himself a spy sent to infiltrate
the group and said he wanted to sever his ties with China, a group
spokesman said.
   Shou Huaqing told members of the Chinese Alliance for Democracy
he wanted to come forward because he was shaken by the bloody
crackdown of pro-democracy activists in China, alliance chairman Hu
Ping said Tuesday.
   Shou was taken to the FBI's West Covina office after his
surprising declaration Friday and his whereabouts were unknown, said
Hu.
   FBI officials declined to comment. ``We just don't address that
sort of question for the media,'' said FBI spokesman Fred Reagan in
Los Angeles.
   Shou's remarks created a stir at the fourth worldwide convention
of the alliance, formed seven years ago by overseas Chinese scholars
who favor democratic reforms in China, said Hu.
   The group, which lists 3,000 members worldwide, publishes China
Spring, a Chinese-language magazine critical of the Communist
government.
   Shou told the delegates that the Chinese government assigned him
to infiltrate the alliance, disrupt the group's work and find
evidence of a financial link between it and the Taiwan government,
Hu said.
   Shou, believed to be in his 30s, moved from Shanghai to Missouri
about two years ago to attend Washington University in St. Louis. He
wrote for China Spring under various pen names, said Hu.
   Last October, Hu sponsored Shou to become an alliance member.
   Chris Wu, a Monterey Park engineer, said Shou told him he decided
to reveal his activities because of the June 4 massacre of
pro-democracy demonstrators by government troops in Beijing's
Tiananmen Square.
   ``He said he cried for several days. He was determined to change
his life,'' Wu said.
</TEXT>
