<FIRST>r a AM-CrashReport     06-28 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash Report,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Load, Engine Problems Tied To Air Force Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE ST. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heavy load, wind gusts and engine
problems caused an Air Force jet to crash and burn on takeoff from a
Texas base, killing 19 people, said a military report released
Wednesday.
   The KC-135A tanker crashed Jan. 31 at Dyess Air Force Base near
Abilene, Texas. The refueling plane was carrying a crew from
Michigan's Sawyer Air Force Base to participate in exercises over
Guam.
   The death toll included eight military retirees and family
members taking advantage of a policy that lets them hop overseas
flights as space permits. Two of those killed had just boarded at
Dyess.
   The Air Force isn't limiting the numbers of civilians catching
such flights because of the crash, said Maj. Ken St. John, a
spokesman for the 8th Air Force in Barksdale, La.
   The Air Force report released Wednesday fails to say outright why
the 26-year-old tanker swerved suddenly into the ground as it took
off from Dyess.
   The report notes the possible failure of a water-injection system
designed to give the jet extra liftoff power, and mentions that the
heavily loaded plane was struggling to take off under gusting winds.
   ``There wasn't anything black and white,'' St. John said. ``The
team believes a combination of factors was involved.''
   St. John said the investigating team blamed the crash on the
combined effect of the gusting wind, the plane's full weight and its
failing water-injection system. He said witnesses also told
investigators the craft took off at too steep an angle, which also
would have cut its liftoff power.
   Repair records showed the craft's water-injection system had
failed eight times from October to December. Maintenance crews
replaced one engine and believed they had the problem fixed, St.
John said.
   ``Those kinds of malfunctions are not unusual,'' he said. ``It is
a recurrent problem with the KC-135A.''
   The crash was the second at Dyess in less than three months, and
third in three months involving a plane from Sawyer, a nuclear base
by Lake Superior.
   Six people died Oct. 11 when another plane from Sawyer crashed
during landing at Wurtsmith Air Force Base in eastern Lower
Michigan. Pilot inexperience was cited as a factor.
   A broken fuel pump overheated and sparked the Dec. 6 explosion of
a B-52 bomber during touc-and-go landings at Sawyer. All eight crew
members survived in what base personnel called a miracle.
   Sawyer, part of the nation's Strategic Air Command, maintains
nuclear bombers on 24-hour alert.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DefenseBudget 3rdLd-Writethru a0759 06-28 1018</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Budget, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0759,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aspin Loses, Osprey and F-14D Restored to Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout starting with 11th graf: ``But members,'' with B-2
amendment and other measures failing; comments from lawmakers; INSERTS
6th graf: ``Individual amendments,'' to sum up those developments. Edits
to tighten. Will stand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Against the advice of its chairman, the House
Armed Services Committee voted Wednesday to restore funds to the
$295 billion defense budget to save a Marine aircraft and F-14D
fighter jet the Bush administration wants to cancel.
   In a vote marked by high drama, the Democratic-controlled panel
tied 26-all on an amendment to accept the $64 billion procurement
budget without any add-ons or deletion.
   Reps. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., and Ron Dellums, D-Calif.,
initially passed during the roll call but then cast ``no'' votes
that resulted in a tie and the amendment's failure.
   By virtue of the measure's defeat, two other amendments saving
the Marine Corps V-22 Osprey and the Navy's F-14D Tomcat fighter,
and providing about $1 billion for the National Guard and reserves
by reducing funds for the B-2 stealth bomber, were adopted as part
of the procurement budget.
   In a final vote, the committee sent the bill to the full House,
44-5.
   Individual amendments to cancel the B-2 program outright, cut all
funds to move 50 MX missiles from silos to railroad cars and reduce
B-2 spending by $379 million to buy Army ammunition were defeated.
   Approved and made part of the procurement budget was an amendment
introduced by Reps. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., and Thomas Foglietta, D-Pa.,
that would provide $157 million in the 1990 fiscal year beginning
Oct. 1 for the Bell-Boeing V-22, to be built in Fort Worth, Texas,
and which Defense Secretary Dick Cheney wants to cancel.
   The F-14D fighter, which is manufactured by Grumman Corp., on
Long Island, would receive $230 million.
   The amendment backed by Rep. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss., would
take $500 million from the B-2 bomber and about $520 million from
spare parts for the National Guard and reserves.
   The committee chairman, Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., had urged his
colleagues to accept the procurement budget as presented. Last week,
in a 10-9 vote, the procurement subcommittee had responded
positively to Aspin's call.
   But members expressed dismay with Aspin's schedule for voting on
the amendments which even if approved would be negated if the panel,
in its last decision, accepted Cheney's $64 billion procurement
budget.
   ``It's like going to a dance by yourself. You get to dance with
all the girls but at the end you get to pick only one to take
home,'' said Rep. Arthur Ravenel Jr., R-S.C.
   Nevertheless, the panel voted on five individual amendments
before deciding against Cheney's budget.
   By a vote of 36-16, the panel rejected an amendment introduced by
Dellums to cancel the B-2 bomber, which at between $500 million and
$650 million a copy is considered the most expensive plane in
history.
   ``It's time to cut ... loose from the monument to misallocated
money,'' Dellums argued. ``We've obligated ourselves to $22 billion
without knowing whether this plane can fly.''
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who backed the amendment, noted that
every week the Air Force changes the mission for the radar-evading
plane.
   Another B-2 opponent, Rep. John Rowland, R-Conn., reminded his
colleagues that based on the newly declassified cost figures
released by the Pentagon, it was likely that Congress would use the
proposed $5 billion in fiscal 1991 for the B-2 as a ``cash cow.''
   But Aspin argued that a vote on the B-2 will take place on the
House floor and ``total termination at this point is wrong.''
   The panel also rejected Dellums' amendment to stop $164 million
requested by the Pentagon to move 50 MX missiles from silos to
railroad cars. The vote was 42-10.
   The panel did approve a report's language that transferred money
from B-2 procurement to research and development on the stealth
bomber. A day earlier, the panel rejected an amendment to restore
$351 million for the bomber that the research and development
subcommittee voted to spend on the Osprey.
   That vote left $2.7 billion in procurement funds for the B-2 and
cut the proposed $1.8 billion for research and development to about
$1.5 billion.
   In its first work of the day, the committee beat back efforts to
provide money, at the expense of the stealth bomber, for buying the
V-22, a revolutionary aircraft that would take off like a helicopter
but fly like an airplane.
   In the two votes, the committee:
   _Rejected by voice vote an amendment by Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C.,
that would have cut funds for the B-2 by $850 million and allocated
$157 million for the Osprey, contingent on Cheney's reevaluation of
the aircraft.
   _Rejected 31-21 an amendment by Rep. Marvin Leath, D-Texas, to
reduce B-2 money by $900 million and restore $157 million for the
Osprey without any restrictions.
   Aspin said Wednesday of the procurement budget, ``I support Dick
Cheney's budget not because it's Dick Cheney's. ... I played with
the amendments and I didn't come up with anything better than what
Cheney had.''
   The committee also approved an additional $300 million for the
Department of Energy to clean up toxic and radioactive wastes at
nuclear weapons sites.
   And the panel accepted an amendment requiring the Bush
administration to certify that safety standards for the withdrawal
of chemical stockpiles in Europe be met before certain money could
be spent.
   Both measures were approved by voice vote.
   Late Tuesday, the panel agreed to reduce the number of troops
stationed in Europe in connection with the U.S.-Soviet
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty by 15,000.
   Star Wars, formally known as the Strategic Defense Initiative,
took a $1.1 billion cut as the committee, by voice vote, approved a
$3.5 billion budget, considerably less than the $4.6 billion Bush
proposed for the program to develop lasers and other weapons to stop
enemy nuclear missiles.
   That reduction came on top of a $1 billion cut in proposed Star
Wars spending made by Cheney two months ago as he slashed $10
billion from the budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ForeignAid     06-28 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Aid,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>El Salvador Aid Restrictions Rejected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Wednesday rejected an effort to
attach strings to U.S. aid to El Salvador as it worked toward
completion of a $23 billion two-year foreign aid bill.
   Lawmakers voted 233-185 to kill an amendment by Rep. Matthew
McHugh, D-N.Y., that would have held back $34 million in military
aid to El Salvador next year until Congress had a chance to review
how the right-wing ruling ARENA party is handling human rights.
   McHugh argued that the amendment, backed primarily by Democrats,
would keep pressure on newly elected ARENA president Alfredo
Cristiani to curb right-wing death squads and work toward a peaceful
settlement of a civil war with leftist rebels.
   Without some chance to review the aid _ totaling $170 million
over the life of the bill _ Congress would be giving Cristiani ``a
blank check for two years,'' he said.
   But opponents noted that the bill already gives Congress a chance
to vote down further aid next April if it finds serious human rights
abuses and accused Democrats of harboring grudges left over from
tensions over Central America with the Reagan administration.
   Rep. Henry Hyde, arguing against the proposal, noted that the
FMLN guerillas have been accused of numerous recent murders of
civilians, including Cristiani's chief of staff. ``The FMLN has
never been more brutal in its tactics,'' Hyde said. ``Why in the
world would you want to coddle these people?''
   Consideration of the measure was expected to extend into
Thursday, when the House was to take up an amendment imposing a
series of new sanctions against China for its deadly crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., said the list would include
suspending trade and development programs, banning the sale of
police-related weapons and limiting transfer of high-technology
items.
   ``I think it sends a very strong signal to the leaders and people
of China that the United States will not continue business as usual
in the absence of fundamental human rights improvement,'' Solarz
said.
   The bill authorizes the spending of up to $11.5 billion each in
fiscal 1990 and 1991 for the entire range of U.S. foreign aid
programs, including military support, economic subsidies and
development aid for friendly countries around the world.
   The measure, perenially one of the most politically unpopular to
come before Congress, still faces an uphill fight. No separate
foreign aid bill has been enacted since 1985; each year's aid since
then has been taken care of in annual spending bills.
   This year, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee has had a
particularly hard time grappling with its version, prompting
chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., to observe that there is ``a
profound lack of interest'' in the measure. In addition, the Bush
administration has threatened a veto over provisions it says
unfairly limit the president's foreign policy latitude.
   As they worked through a deep pile of amendments to the bill, the
lawmakers also:
   _Rejected, 212-204, a proposal to force random drug testing for
State Department employees and others involved in administering
foreign aid programs.
   _Earmarked $7.5 million in each of the two years of the bill for
``humanitarian aid'' for the people of Lebanon, to be administered
through international aid agencies.
   _Approved a non-binding amendment stating that election law
reforms undertaken by the left-wing Sandinista government in
Nicaragua do not meet the requirement of a regional peace accord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
