<FIRST>r a AM-Helmsley     06-28 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Queen Cries In Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leona Helmsley cried in court Wednesday when her
lawyer argued she could not get a fair trial unless he was allowed
to show that one of her co-defendants had stolen money from Helmsley
businesses.
   ``This isn't going to be a trial, it's going to be a farce,''
said her lawyer, Gerald Feffer.
   Mrs. Helmsley, who sat facing U.S. District Judge John Walker
Jr., used her hands to wipe away tears that fell down her face. A
judge's clerk later brought her a handful of tissues.
   The arguments came late in the afternoon after Walker completed
three days of screening potential jurors for the tax evasion trial
of Mrs. Helmsley and two former aides.
   Feffer asked the judge for broad latitude in presenting evidence,
cross-examining witnesses and arguing in his opening and closing
statements that co-defendant Frank J. Turco, an ex-senior officer
with Helmsley Hotels, had engaged in ``wholesale theft'' from the
Helmsleys.
   ``It's an essential part of our defense,'' he said.
   Turco's attorney, William Brodsky, argued a separate motion
asking that his client be severed from the trial because Mrs.
Helmsley's defense would be prejudicial and deny him a fair trial.
   ``I think it would be devastating for Mr. Turco to have two sides
attacking him with artillery,'' Brodsky said, referring to Assistant
U.S. Attorney James DaVita and Feffer.
   Walker reserved decision on both motions.
   Feffer claimed he had evidence that showed Turco had siphoned
large amounts of money and deposited it into his personal bank
accounts.
   One charge in the indictment alleged that Mrs. Helmsley had
instructed employees, through Turco, to submit phony travel vouchers
and then give her the cash, Feffer said. He alleged that Turco had
kept the money and that it was not passed on to Mrs. Helmsley.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 68, who with her husband heads a $5 billion real
estate and hotel empire, is charged with conspiracy, tax and fraud
charges in connection with the billing of more than $4 million in
personal expenses to Helmsley-controlled companies.
   Among the expenses prosecutors allege were wrongfully reported
were renovations, including the installation of a marble dance
floor, at the couple's mansion in Greenwich, Conn.
   Two former aides, Turco and Joseph Licari, are charged with
assisting in the scheme. Mrs. Helmsley's 80-year-old husband, Harry,
was indicted but removed from the trial for health reasons.
   Mrs. Helmsley and Turco also are charged with extortion for
allegedly shaking down employees and contractors doing business with
the Helmsley companies.
   Walker completed choosing a pool of 60 potential jurors. On
Wednesday, before opening arguments, lawyers and prosecutors will
select the 12 jurors and six alternates who will serve.
</TEXT>
