<FIRST>r a AM-NorthropIndictment     06-28 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrop Indictment,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>22 Counts Added in Federal Defense Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fraud case against Northrop Corp. now
includes allegations the defense contractor sold the government
about 200 improperly tested guidance systems for missiles and
planes, rather than 17.
   The amended indictment, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court by
the U.S. Attorney's Office, adds 22 counts to a 167-count indictment
filed April 11.
   The company was charged with conspiracy and lying to the
government in the testing and sale of stabilization devices used in
nuclear-tipped cruise missiles and the Marines' AV-8B Harrier jets.
   Northrop spokesman Tony Cantafio repeated the company's position
that there had been no wrongdoing.
   The government alleges the company sold devices, called flight
data transmitters and costing $4,000 to $6,000 apiece, that had
failed tests to show they would work at temperatures as low as 65
degrees below zero.
   Contracts required that test because the gyroscopic devices must
work in the cold encountered at high altitudes.
   The original indictment alleged 17 of more than 1,000 of the
units sold from 1984 through 1989 had been improperly tested. The
amended indictment says 200 weren't properly tested.
   Northrop, which makes the flight data transmitters at its Pomona
plant, could be fined up to $30 million if convicted.
</TEXT>
