<FIRST>r a AM-RogerRabbit 1stLd-Writethru a0782 06-28 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Roger Rabbit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0782,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roger Rabbit Animation Cells Sold at Auction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, final graf to CORRECT film title by deleting question
mark; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 animation cells from the 1988
box-office hit ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' were sold at auction
Wednesday, with the top-selling frame bringing more than $50,000.
   The standing-room-only sale at Sotheby's auction house, called
``The Art of Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' brought $1.66 million, or
about twice the $600,000 to $900,000 pre-sale estimate, said Matthew
Weigman, a Sotheby's spokesman.
   Four cells of the so-called Toons _ cartoon characters _
assembled at the end of the movie brought the highest prices.
   A cell featuring about two dozen cartoon characters, from Roger
Rabbit and Jessica to Mickey Mouse, Donald Duck, Betty Boop and Bugs
Bunny, sold for $50,600 to the Philip Samuels Fine Art Gallery in
St. Louis, Mo..
   Private collectors bought the other three, which went for
$33,000, $31,900 and $27,500.
   The cells are painted on acetate and mounted against the color
photograph background used in the movie. They ranged in size from 10
inches by 39 inches to 7 inches by 13 inches.
   David Redden, Sotheby's senior vice president and auctioneer at
the six-hour sale, said prices were much higher than expected
primarily because ``it's hard for us to put values on these since
it's the first time Roger Rabbit cells have ever been offered at
auction.''
   Bidders included first-time buyers who loved the movie as well as
collectors who have a tradition of buying animation cells, he said.
   ``I think there a lot of collectors out there who really view
this sort of Disney animation art as real American art,'' he added.
``It's not just fun stuff, it's taken seriously.''
   Redden said an auction of animation cells is unusual, especially
so soon after the movie was released. And he acknowledged that
Sotheby's, better known for its multimillion dollar auctions of
famous paintings, was an atypical setting for a sale like this.
   ``I said to the audience after I finished that it was time to go
home and eat carrot cake,'' he said.
   The cells were sold by Walt Disney Studio and Amblin
Entertainment.
   ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' won four Academy Awards for its
technical feats in which cartoon characters interacted with live
actors.
</TEXT>
