<SECOND>AM-Shoreham Agreement, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0773,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders OK Settlement to Dismantle Shoreham Nuclear Power Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `In exchange ..., to CORRECT that LILCO is not
granted rate hikes in exchange for agreement. Longer version moved on business
wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTBURY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement to abandon the beleaguered
Shoreham nuclear power plant cleared its final hurdle Wednesday when
Long Island Lighting Co. shareholders overwhelmingly approved the
deal.
   ``We must now come together and end the controversy,'' Chairman
William Catacosinos told about 600 shareholders at the utility's
annual meeting. ``It's hurt all of us too much.''
   Gov. Mario Cuomo, who helped negotiate the deal, said the
shareholders' approval ``allows LILCO to devote itself exclusively
in the future to providing safe and reliable energy for Long Island
at the lowest possible cost.''
   The shareholders also approved the terms of a settlement of a
class-action lawsuit filed against the utility under the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act. It calls for Long Island
Lighting to refund $390 million to ratepayers as adjustments in
monthly bills over a 10-year period.
   The shareholders' approval was the final step necessary before
the settlement between the company and the state to close the $5.5
billion Shoreham plant can take effect.
   The utility is expected to seek permission from the federal
Nuclear Regulatory Commission to sell Shoreham for $1 to the Long
Island Power Authority, a state agency. The agency will then seek
approval from the NRC to dismantle the plant.
   The company was not guaranteed any rate increases in exchange for
agreeing to sell the plant. Cuomo predicted when the deal was
announced that any hikes would be probably less than 4.5 percent a
year. The utility's customers already pay among the highest electric
rates in the nation.
   State and local officials contend the area around the plant,
about 50 miles east of New York City, could not be safely evacuated
in the event of an accident.
   It would be the first time a completed nuclear power plant will
be closed without ever going on line.
   A preliminary tally of about 85 percent of shareholders indicated
that shareholders voted approximately 82 million to 3 million to
accept the deal, company spokesman James Lois said.
   Still, the deal could lead to a new round of battles since
federal Energy Department officials have stated they intend to block
the sale and transfer of Shoreham for dismantling.
   They contend the reactor should be mothballed so that it could be
activated if necessary to meet energy needs in the future.
</TEXT>
