<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Namibia     06-28 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Namibia,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>SWAPO Accuses South Africa of Trying To Sabotage Namibia Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Namibia's main guerrilla organization
Wednesday accused South Africa of using murder and terror to
sabotage the Namibian peace process and November independence
elections.
   Sam Nujoma, president of the South West Africa People's
Organization, said Pretoria was waging a campaign against the
Namibian people despite the move towards free elections overseen by
the United Nations.
   Nujoma said special South African police units known as Koevoets
_ meaning Crowbar in Afrikaans _ were murdering and terrorizing the
black population and destroying crops.
   U.N. secretary-general Javier Perez de Cuellar is reported to
have told a closed meeting of the Security Council on Tuesday that
actions by Koevoet members raised grave doubts about the possibility
of free and fair elections in Namibia.
   In Windhoek on Wednesday, Louis Pienaar, the South African
administrator of the territory, said he would be happy to discuss
the presence of the Koevoet units in the Namibian security forces
with Perez de Cuellar.
   Nujoma, who intends to end his exile from Namibia soon, also
criticized South African moves to raise the age for voters from 18
to 21. He said that might reduce SWAPO's support by 30 percent.
   Though SWAPO is expected to win a majority in the elections, it
is not certain they will receive the two-thirds majority needed to
control the government.
   SWAPO has been engaged in a bush war against South African rule
of Namibia since 1966.
   Nujoma also hinted that an independent Namibia could join the
Commonwealth, the 48-nation association of Britain and its former
colonies. He said the matter was raised at the meeting.
   Asked whether Swapo would want the country to join, Nujoma
replied: ``Perhaps it would be a good idea for us to be in the
Commonwealth. We will look into that.''
   Namibia gained independence from South Africa under a
U.N.-sponsored peace plan that included the withdrawal of 50,000
Cuban troops from Angola. But the peace process almost foundered the
day it began on April 1, when more than 1,000 SWAPO guerrillas
crossed over the boarder from Angola into Namibia in violation of
the regional peace agreement.
   More than 300 guerrillas and 27 security-force members were
killed in subsequent fighting, but clashes have stopped and the
election campaign begins in July. Independence is expected to come
early next year.
   The U.N. has sponsored an airlift to repatriate 41,000 registered
Namibian refugees in time for the opening of the campaign but so
far, only 10,200 have been returned.
</TEXT>
