<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2342EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LastTemptation     06-28 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Last Temptation,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Last Temptation Of Christ' Video Set to Arrive in Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' is
being introduced to video stores with as little fanfare as possible
Thursday to avoid tempting the virulent protests that met its
theatrical debut, producers said.
   MCA Home Video, fearful that the movie's video release might
encourage further demonstrations and boycotts, is distributing ``The
Last Temptation'' without store displays, promotional posters or
advertising.
   So far there have been no organized demonstrations against the
video. Even so, ``The Last Temptation,'' at a suggested retail price
of $89.95, will not be sold by Blockbuster Video, the nation's
largest video-store chain.
   ``It's certainly unusual, but it was a corporate decision
considering all that went on with the film,'' said Wally Knief, a
spokesman for the Fort Lauderdale-based video chain with 343
company-owned outlets nationwide.
   It is Blockbuster's first such action against a major studio
release, Knief said, and nearly 80 percent of Blockbuster's 387
franchise locations also have indicated they won't carry the video.
   Robert Blattner, president of MCA Home Video, which is affiliated
with ``Last Temptation'' producer Universal Pictures, said his
company was taking a low-key marketing approach because it was
``conscious of provoking a new controversy, which was clearly not in
anybody's interest.''
   ``On the other hand, we're not willing to keep it on the shelf,''
Blattner said. ``We think it's important that this title be made
available in the marketplace.''
   Starring Willem Dafoe and directed by Martin Scorsese, ``The Last
Temptation'' was attacked before it appeared in theaters last August
by many fundamentalist Christian organizations. Most objected to the
depiction of Christ as a doubting messiah with human frailties and
sexual fantasies.
   A secretary for the Rev. Donald Wildmon, a conservative Christian
activist who led those attacks, said Wednesday that Wildmon was not
planning any protests against the videocassette debut, as he had
threatened to do last year.
   A number of independent stores also will not carry the cassette.
John Clark, owner of The Video Center in Gilroy, Calif., said
although he carries X-rated videos that could be considered
controversial, he would not bring in ``The Last Temptation'' for
that very reason.
   ``I just don't need the potential of the community being upset,''
Clark said. Clark said he has a separate room for the sexually
explicit movies and that he was not willing to build another room
just for ``The Last Temptation.''
   Employees of national video retailer Music Plus, which will carry
``The Last Temptation,'' have been told to tell patrons that the
chain does not have the right to censor its product line because it
would not serve customer needs.
   Although the film's opening was greeted with pickets and
vandalism, ``The Last Temptation'' was a modest hit. It has grossed
$8.2 million to date, according to Exhibitor Relations Co., and won
an Academy Award nomination for director Scorsese.
   MCA Home Video declined to say how many cassettes of ``The Last
Temptation'' it was producing, but the trade magazine Video Week
estimated that 47,000 units will be shipped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
