<FIRST>r a AM-HazelwoodTrial     06-28 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazelwood Trial,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sets October Date for Hazelwood Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Wednesday set an Oct. 30 trial
date for Joseph Hazelwood, who was in charge of the tanker Exxon
Valdez when it spilled 10.9 million gallons of oil off the Alaska
coast three months ago.
   The trial, initially set for June 20 and then moved to Monday,
was rescheduled again after state and defense attorneys asked Palmer
Superior Court Judge Beverly Cutler for more preparation time.
   The skipper, fired by Exxon after his ship hit a Prince William
Sound reef March 24, faces three felony counts of second-degree
criminal mischief in addition to misdemeanor charges of operating a
vessel while intoxicated, reckless endangerment and negligent
discharge of pollutants.
   Cutler said all charges will be considered in one trial.
   Hazelwood, who participated in the Anchorage hearing by telephone
from New York City, waived his right to a speedy trial. The
42-year-old Huntington, N.Y., man is free on $50,000 bail.
   Defense attorney Dick Madson told Cutler he expects to seek
dismissal of Hazelwood's felony indictment. He said there are at
least four reasons for dismissal, but he did not disclose them.
</TEXT>
