<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     06-28 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roh Opposes Demands to Cut U.S. Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo said Wednesday he
firmly opposes demands by U.S. lawmakers and some of his countrymen
to reduce the number of U.S. troops in South Korea.
   He said American troops contribute to the stability of the
divided Korean peninsula, the rest of Asia and the entire Pacific
region.
   Roh, holding his first news conference for the foreign press
since becoming president, expressed concern about events in China
while also expressing hope for early restoration of ``tranquility
and stability.''
   He said the ``moderating influence'' of neighboring China on
Korea has been affected by the recent turmoil, but he did specify.
South Korea regards China, an ally of the communist north, as having
moderating influence on militant North Korea.
   Roh said South Korea's democratization has not always been easy.
``There is still unrest in this country. Our society has many issues
to solve as it moves from authoritarianism to democracy.''
   He said the economy is experiencing difficulties due to labor
demands, excessive consumption and the appreciation of the currency,
but said he was confident the economic and labor problems would be
resolved.
   Acknowledging that demands for reduction or withdrawal of 43,000
American troops come from both South Korea and Washington, he said
he is against making any change in America's commitment to keep
forces in Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   He said North Korea continues to introduce modern weapons from
the Soviet Union and deploys massive troops along the demilitarized
zone separating the two nations, which technically remain at war. A
peace treaty was never signed after the bloody 1950-53 Korean War.
   The global trend of relaxation of military tensions seen in
Europe does not apply to Korea, he said.
   Democratic lawmakers in Washington have urged a reduction in U.S.
troops in Korea, saying that the $2.6 billion spent on them could be
better used elsewhere. They say South Korea, with seven times the
gross national product of the north and twice as many people, could
afford its own defense.
   Roh said keeping troops in Korea was ``the wisest and most
economical investment'' Americans could make.
   He said dissidents and radical students demand withdrawal of U.S.
troops but that ``most Koreans share my view that America is our
best and oldest friend and ally.''
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' he said.
   Roh said North Korea has made only ``cosmetic changes'' in its
rigid isolationist policy. He repeated a call for a summit
conference with North Korean leader Kim Il Sung.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
