<DOCNO> AP890628-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Children-ReportCard     06-28 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children-Report Card,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocacy Group Gives State Bad Grade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new advocacy group of prominent Californians
gave their state a ``D'' grade Wednesday for the way it cares for
children.
   Children Now based its ``Children's Report Card'' on 27 factors,
including infant mortality, teen-age pregnancy and high school
graduation rates and drug use among teens, according to a press
release.
   The card, issued to coincide with the end of the school year,
graded the state in five categories. It gave a ``C'' for the status
of children's health and education, a ``D-minus'' for the teen
years, a ``D-plus'' for investing in families and a ``U'' or
unsatisfactory grade for children's safety.
   The graders were California Supreme Court Justice Allen
Broussard; Stanford University President Dr. Donald Kennedy; former
U.S. Secretary of Education Shirley Hufstedler; Garfield High School
teacher Jaime Escalante, whose life was depicted in the film ``Stand
and Deliver,'' and former baseball commissioner Peter Ueberroth.
   The report found that California ranked worse than the national
average in more than three-quarters of the areas it researched,
including graduation rates, children in poverty and student-teacher
ratios.
   In a few cases, the state ranked among the 10 worst states.
   ``We like to think of ourselves as the Golden State and we should
be able to do more for our kids,'' said Wendy Lazarus, vice
president for policy for the non-profit, foundation-funded group
founded in 1988.
   ``The good news in this report card is that there are some areas
that we can be proud of,'' she said. ``We really think it's a call
to action with a message that together we can do it.''
   The statistics, mostly for 1987 and 1988, were gathered from a
variety of state and federal agencies.
   ``Unfortunately, on some of the measures, there just wasn't any
information available. Nobody can tell us how many homeless children
there are in California. So we just gave an incomplete in that
category,'' Ms. Lazarus said.
   State schools chief William Honig agreed with the report's
conclusion.
   ``There is a major problem on comprehensive children's
programs,'' he said. ``There's been an explosive growth in poverty
... and we're all going to pay the price.''
</TEXT>
