<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpillsRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0811 06-28 1043</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0811,1068</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearings Open on Two Spills; Hot Weather Threatens Delaware Cleanup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Yost said...,' to CORRECT press secretary's
name to Welsh, sted Walsh.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising temperatures melted globs of congealed oil in the Delaware
River on Tuesday, complicating efforts to remove the oil spilled
from a tanker, and hearings opened into two other oil spills in
Texas and Rhode Island.
   A harbor pilot testified he radioed three warnings to the tanker
World Prodigy before it hit a reef and spilled 420,000 gallons of
oil off the Rhode Island coast. A Coast Guard officer said the
tanker's captain apparently used the wrong chart to plot his course.
   In Texas, the pilot of a tanker that collided with a barge in the
Houston Ship Channel testified Tuesday that his vessel didn't react
as expected just before the accident that ruptured the barge and
spilled 250,000 gallons of oil. He said sediment buildup in a
channel may have kept him from making a turn.
   In Delaware, Coast Guard Commandant Adm. Paul A. Yost called
Tuesday to promise more action, said a spokesman for Gov. Michael
Castle, who has complained that the cleanup has been far too slow.
   Yost said he would put more resources into the cleanup
immediately, said Castle's press secretary, Jeff Welsh. Yost also
promised to put a command post on location, wherever it will do the
most good.
   ``The message from the admiral is this: If the governor isn't
happy, the admiral isn't happy,'' Welsh said.
   Delaware officials, including Castle, filed suit in federal court
seeking unspecified damages against the country of Uruguay, the
owner of the tanker.
   Coast Guard officials had said they hoped more than 500 people
would be involved in the Delaware cleanup Tuesday. But Roger A.
Lucio of the Delaware Department of Natural Resources and
Environmental Control said 207 National Guard and private contractor
employees were working along with 100 federal government workers. In
Philadelphia, Coast Guard spokesman David Oney said Delaware was
sending 150 more Guardsmen.
   The Coast Guard reduced its estimate of the spill Tuesday, saying
about 306,000 gallons of heavy oil, down from 800,000 gallons,
spilled into the river Saturday when the Uruguayan tanker Presidente
Rivera ran aground.
   Unlike the lighter oil spilled in Rhode Island and Texas, and the
crude oil that leaked March 24 in Alaska, the oil coagulated in the
cool water into chunks ranging in size from a basketball to two or
three feet.
   Cleanup workers had been using pitchforks and even their hands to
snare the globs from the water because skimmers were jammed by the
larger chunks. About 64,000 gallons had been recovered as of Tuesday.
   But on Tuesday, the temperature headed out of the 80s and into
the 90s, the melting range for the No. 6 industrial heating oil.
   ``When we've got it in chunks, we can pick it up,'' said Coast
Guard Capt. Larry Murdock.
   Liquefied oil poses a much greater hazard to shoreline and to
wildlife, Murdock said.
   During an inspection tour, officials pointed to patches where the
rainbow hue of petroleum on water showed up and said it was coming
from oil blobs close enough to the surface to heat and melt.
   Until Tuesday, only a short stretch of shoreline had been tainted
in Delaware. Injuries to wildlife were limited to 25 Canada geese,
which were being cleaned at the Tri State Bird Rescue Center in
Wilmington, Del. A 26th goose died. An additional 50 geese spattered
with oil were trapped in a lagoon near Wilmington.
   In Providence, R.I., pilot David G. Leonard, 55, told a Coast
Guard-National Transportation Safety Board hearing that pleasure
boat radio traffic may have kept his warnings to the tanker World
Prodigy from being understood. He said vital radio channels should
be freed because pleasure boat interference is common during summer.
   Virtually all the No. 2 heating oil spilled in Friday's accident
had dissipated by Tuesday and state officials began reopening
beaches.
   Coast Guard Lt. Paul Cormier said the World Prodigy's captain,
Iakavos Georgudis, acknowledged seeing a buoy that warns traffic
away from Brenton Reef but said: ``I turned the ship too late.''
   Cormier said Georgudis was not using a chart with enough detail
to show the buoy or water depth and said the captain turned the
ship, with a 36-foot draft, into 30 feet of water.
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete, who met the captain on a Coast Guard
vessel hours after the accident, asked him why there was no pilot
aboard. ``He said, `That was my mistake.' He made no bones about
it,'' DiPrete said.
   Authorities are investigating whether the ship was past the point
where state law required a pilot on board.
   The investigating panel, however, was blocked from hearing
testimony from the ship's helmsman, Konstadinos A. Paraskevopulos,
when his attorney, Lise J. Gescheidt, advised him to invoke his
right against self-incrimination.
   Capt. David H. Whitten, who is leading the investigation for the
Coast Guard, said he was working with the U.S. attorney's office to
grant Paraskevopulos immunity. The helmsman, who speaks no English,
appeared with a Greek translator.
   U.S. Attorney Lincon Almond indicated the request would be
granted.
   ``He could be important to the inquiry and he could be important
to any criminal prosecutions,'' the prosecutor said.
   Almond said the captain would not be granted immunity, however,
because he was the target of a criminal investigation.
   In Texas, about a dozen huge vacuum machines and regular vacuum
machines were at work pumping oil from the Bayport Channel, where
much of the 250,000 gallons of oil spilled into the Houston Ship
Channel was funneled to help in the cleanup, Coast Guard spokesman
Bob Morehead said. Cleanup crews by Tuesday had collected 4,300
barrels of oil from the water, Morehead said.
   Tanker pilot Michael Gale said he was trying to make a right turn
from the Bayport Channel into the Ship Channel, but the tanker
continued straight ahead and collided with the barge Friday.
   ``My only opinion is, she didn't have enough water underneath her
keel,'' Gale said. ``It could have been caused by too much sediment
in the channel.''
   Gale, a pilot for 12 years, said he has made 2,700 trips in the
channel.
</TEXT>
