<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     06-28 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Lawmaker Arrested for Unauthorized Trip to North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security agents Wednesday arrested an
opposition lawmaker for making an unauthorized, secret visit to
Pyongyang for an interview with North Korea's leader.
   Officials of the Agency for National Security Planning said Suh
Kyung-won, of South Korea's largest opposition Party, Peace and
Democracy, was charged with violating South Korea's National
Security Law.
   The law provides for a maximum of the death penalty and a minimum
of five years imprisonment for such an illegal trip to the north.
   The announcement said Suh visited the communist north Aug. 19-21
last year via Prague, Czechoslovakia after contacting North Korean
agents in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   While in the north, Suh met with Kim Il Sung and Ho Dam, chairman
of North Korea's Committee for the Peaceful Unification of the
Fatherland, on national unification and other issues.
   Newspapers said that Suh had kept his clandestine visit to the
north secret but began considering surrendering to authorities after
dissident leader Rev. Moon Ik-hwan was arrested in April for his
unauthorized visit to the north. Moon is now on trial for violating
the security law.
   Meanwhile, a national student group said Tuesday it will defy a
government ban and march to communist North Korea for a youth
festival.
   The chairman of the radical National Council of Student
Representatives, Im Chong-suk said he expects 15,000 students to
congregate at Seoul's Hanyang University for a march Friday, the eve
of the festival. The World Youth Festival will be held in North
Korea's capital, Pyongyang, July 1-8.
   Prosecutors said they issued warrants for the arrest of Im and
two other leaders of the radical student group, charging them with
violating the security law by talking on the telephone with North
Korean students.
   Seoul accuses Pyongyang of using the festival to stir up
dissident movements in South Korea _ a charge the North Korean
government denies. The festival is a political and sports event
attended mostly by youths from the Third World and communist bloc.
   In Tokyo, officials said representatives of Japan's governing
Liberal Democratic Party and its largest opposition party left
Tuesday for North Korea via Beijing to attend the youth festival in
North Korea. They were also to hold talks with the Pyongyang
government toward improving relations.
   South and North Korea have been bitter rivals since their land
was divided at the end of World War II. North Korea invaded the
south in 1950 and the three-year Korean War left more than l million
dead on both sides. A truce was never signed.
</TEXT>
