<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpills-Governors     06-28 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills-Governors,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska's Governor Offers Help to Other Oil-Spill States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Oil Spill Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Steve Cowper on Tuesday offered to
share the lessons Alaska has learned from the nation's worst oil
spill with five states affected by a recent rash of spills.
   ``I stand ready to offer you Alaska's expertise learned the hard
way from three months on the front lines of North America's largest
oil spill,'' Cowper said in letters sent to the states' governors.
   He referred to the March 24 Exxon Valdez spill, which polluted
Alaska's Prince William Sound with nearly 11 million gallons of
crude oil. The cleanup of that spill ``is in no way over,'' he said.
   Copwer also asked the governors of Delaware, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Rhode Island and Texas to help him push for federal
legislation to prevent spills and improve the nation's ability to
respond to them.
   He outlined his proposals for improving tanker safety and
spill-response capabilities.
   ``It is clear that the industry, from producers to shippers, does
not have the equipment, expertise or technology to mount an
effective response in a critically short period of time,'' Cowper
said.
   The United States should adopt the advanced technology of other
oil-producing nations, especially Norway and the Soviet Union, which
provided Alaska with expert help after the Exxon Valdez spill, he
said.
   Alaska's governor noted that federal law allows the party
responsible for the spill to direct the cleanup until it is either
unwilling or unable to do so.
   ``The public shouldn't have to wait for a spiller to quit or
fail. We should have the ability to act quickly without worrying
about emptying federal or state treasuries,'' Cowper wrote.
</TEXT>
