<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     06-28 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fresh Scandal Over Prime Minister's Affairs With Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new scandal ignited Wednesday as Prime Minister
Sousuke Uno, already suffering from allegations of an affair with a
former geisha, was hit with reports of two other liaisons.
   The reports, which appeared in a popular women's magazine, Josei
Jishin, alleged that Uno had affairs with a hostess in the Ginza
entertainment district from 1962 to 1972 and with a geisha from 1975
to 1984.
   Before the magazine hit the stands Wednesday, rumors that Uno was
considering resigning, less than a month after taking office on June
2, reflected in overseas financial markets and surfaced in the
Japanese press.
   Top stories in major national newspapers said leaders of the
governing Liberal Democratic Party held an emergency meeting Tuesday
night and persuaded Uno to stay in office.
   According to reports in Asahi Shimbun, Mainichi Shimbun and
Yomiuri Shimbun, among other newspapers, Uno told advisers the
reports of womanizing insulted his dignity. He said they made it
difficult for him to meet other world leaders at such forums as the
Paris summit in July.
   On Wednesday, Uno denied reports that he expressed desire to
resign over the scandals.
   ``I did't say such a thing,'' Uno told reporters, referring to
the reports.
   The Yomiuri Shimbun and Mainichi Shimbun quoted sources close to
the prime minister as saying: ``If I am troubling you further, I
must resign.
   ``I cannot manage my job, receiving such an insult. ... I didn't
become prime minister because I wanted to,'' Yomiuri quoted Uno as
saying.
   But Mainichi said Uno also said: ``I will not resign for awhile
whatever happens.''
   Uno told a group of legislators and businessmen attending a trade
meeting Wednesday that he would attend the Paris summit of major
industrial powers.
   ``As Japan's representative, I must discuss important issues with
leaders from other countries,'' an official of the Prime Minister's
Office quoted Uno as saying.
   The scandals come as the Liberal Democrats, who have ruled Japan
for 34 years, struggle to regroup after the resignation of Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, who left office after being linked to the
Recruit influence-peddling scandal, which tainted many of the
party's elite.
   The scandal is widely expected to hurt the party in an election
this weekend for the Tokyo Metropolitan Assembly and in voting next
month for half the seats in Parliament's upper house.
   Uno, when questioned in Parliament, refused to comment on earlier
reports he paid a geisha to be his mistress in 1985, saying it was a
private matter.
   After a setback for the ruling party in a by-election Sunday,
however, he acknowledged rumors of womanizing had added to damage
done to the party by the Recruit scandal.
   Uno was foreign minister until he was drafted on June 2 to be
prime minister, ending the party's search for a politician with a
clean image to help it overcome the widespread Recruit scandal.
   The report in Josei Jishin claimed that Uno began his affair with
the Ginza hostess, identified in the article only as Ms. Y, 50,
several years after he was first elected to Parliament in 1960.
   It said the other geisha, who also was not named, met Uno once a
week from 1975 to 1984 and was paid the equivalent of about $700 a
month.
   On Sunday, a former geisha appeared on television to say she was
paid by Uno to be his mistress in 1985. Mitsuko Nakanishi, 40,
claimed that under a contract with her geisha house, Uno paid the
equivalent of $14,280 to the house and $7,140 to her, in addition to
monthly payments of $2,100 over four months.
   Contrary to their reputation overseas, real geisha are not
prostitutes, but are highly trained entertainers well versed in the
arts and in conversation. Most work in traditional Japanese
restaurants, often frequented by politicians and businessmen. Some
become mistresses of favored patrons.
</TEXT>
