<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Bullitt     06-28 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bullitt,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dorothy Bullitt, TV Pioneer, Dead at 97</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorothy Stimson Bullitt, grande dame of Pacific
Northwest television and founder of the KING Broadcasting Co., died
of heart failure Tuesday at her home at age 97.
   Mrs. Bullitt, heiress to a real-estate fortune, was a leading
figure in the city's business and cultural life for more than 50
years.
   Widowed in 1932, she raised three children alone and took over
the Bullitt family's real estate business.
   In 1947, she founded King Broadcasting, purchased a local AM and
FM radio station, KEVR, and changed the call letters to KING, after
King County.
   Mrs. Bullitt ran the outfit with fierce independence, vowing
never to sell air time to religious organizations. That ban remains
in place at KING Television, which she purchased for $375,000 from a
Merrill Lynch employee who had built Channel 5 himself and put it on
the air on Thanksgiving Day, 1948.
   The Federal Communications Commission placed a temporary ban on
the establishment of new stations while resolving problems with
transmission, giving KING a five-year monopoly as the only
television station west of the Mississippi and north of San
Francisco. It showed programming from all three networks.
   ``That was what made us,'' Mrs. Bullitt once said in a published
interview. The station is now an NBC affiliate.
   KING Broadcasting today owns four television and six radio
stations, including KGW-TV in Portland, Ore. and KREM TV and radio
in Spokane.
   Mrs. Bullitt retired as company president in 1962 but remained
honorary chairman of the board. She was replaced as president by her
son, Stimson Bullitt, an attorney who was succeeded at the station
by Ancil Payne in 1971.
   Mrs. Bullitt, born in Seattle, was the second of two children of
a mill owner and real estate tycoon, C.D. Stimson, who moved to
Seattle early in the year of the Great Fire of 1889.
   At 18 , she married Alexander Scott Bullitt, a Democrat who later
ran for the U.S. Senate and the governor of Washington, but lost
both races in what was then a strongly Republican state.
   He died in 1932 of cancer of the liver, leaving Mrs. Bullitt and
three children: Charles Stimson; Priscilla, known as Patsy, and
Harriet, owner of Pacific Northwest magazine.
   Mrs. Bullitt, then 40, took charge as the sole person responsible
for managing her share of a large estate.
   She served on the boards of the Seattle Art Museum, the
University of Washington, Children's Hospital, Pacific University,
Seattle Public Library and Seattle Symphony. She was also one of
five founding members of the Code Board of the National Association
of Broadcasters in the 1950s.
   Survivors include her son and two daughters, 10 grandhildren and
10 great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     06-28 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0793</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House will not rush to nullify a Supreme
Court decision on flag-burning, says House Speaker Thomas Foley, who
contends the issue should not be used for ``crass political
purposes.''
   Moving Tuesday to slow down a possible stampede for
constitutional change, Foley announced that hearings will be held in
July on setting aside the court ruling that threw out flag
desecration laws in 48 states.
   He acted only hours after President Bush joined a chorus of
lawmakers in proclaiming that a constitutional amendment _ a process
used only 26 times in the nation's history _ is the only solution to
change the 5-4 ruling.
   Foley, D-Wash., said the House Judiciary Committee hearings ``are
not going to be rushed but they will not be obstructive.'' They will
``be conducted calmly in the spirit of deliberation and care ... we
are not seeking to inflame this issue,'' he told reporters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush seems more interested in defending
the flag than defending the ideas the flag represents, say civil
rights leaders who heard a speech by Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh.
   In his address Tuesday to Operation PUSH, Thornburgh said the
Bush administration wouldn't immediately pursue legislation to
overturn controversial U.S. Supreme Court rulings on job
discrimination.
   Thornburgh said the administration wanted to first assess the
impact of the high court rulings on anti-discrimination laws.
   Jesse Jackson, founder of the Chicago-based Operation PUSH,
expressed disappointment with Thornburgh's ``wait-and-see'' message.
He and others contrasted it with Bush's immediate call for a
constitutional amendment to set aside last week's Supreme Court
ruling nullifying flag desecration laws in 48 states.
   ``We cannot help but notice the haste with which Bush has rushed
to defend the flag, and his lack of haste in defending the substance
that flag stands for, which is equality under the law and
fairness,'' Jackson said after Thornburgh's speech.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is weighing proposals to curb
special-interest influence in political campaigns, and an aide says
he also may act to keep track of Congress members' efforts to
influence executive branch policy.
   Bush is to announce on Thursday his proposals to revise the
campaign funding laws. He is expected to call for abolition of
special-interest political action committees that pour millions of
dollars into the war chests of federal candidates.
   In addition to the election law reform, the president is
considering a proposal to log calls from Congress members trying to
sway officials' decisions, said one official who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The president indicated in a news conference Tuesday that he has
not made his final decisions. He is to announce his proposals in a
speech to a group of congressional interns at the Library of
Congress.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new state law that allows police to
withhold the names of crime victims went into effect quietly earlier
this month but is creating an uproar.
   The law, which amends the Texas Open Records Act, allows
government agencies to keep confidential the identities of victims
of felonies, including homicide.
   Police also can withhold information that could lead to victims'
identification, such as addresses. The bill went into effect June 14.
   Generally, the news media voluntarily withholds the names only of
victims of sex crimes.
   ``I think the law is outrageous and I hope law enforcement
agencies will choose to ignore it until this serious challenge to
freedom of information can be corrected,'' Jack Loftis, editor and
vice president of the Houston Chronicle, said in a telephone
interview Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carrie Bray was looking for real-life
cowboys when she came to Cheyenne but the closest the 14-year-old
Texan got was a peek inside the ``Howdy Wagon'' parked in front of
the chamber of commerce.
   ``There's got to be some cowboys around here somewhere,'' the
Dallas teen-ager said during a recent visit with her mother.
   Sorry. Tourists lured to Cheyenne to ``Live the Legend'' are
finding there's little legend to live in the southeastern Wyoming
city of 47,000 residents.
   City officials know they're letting tourists down and admit they
might be deceiving them with the advertising slogan.
   ``Can they `Live the Legend?' No,'' said Mayor Gary Schaeffer.
``As soon as people start making up slogans, there's a perception of
problems or they wouldn't need a slogan. We have to give them what
they need to live it.''
   Realizing the western deficiency of the Cowboy State's capital,
civic leaders are beefing up frontier activities and sinking
thousands of dollars into marketing surveys and tourist promotions.
</TEXT>
