<FIRST>s a BC-Apollo-MoonJunk Adv16   06-28 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Apollo-Moon Junk, Adv 16,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Astronauts Left Cars, Golf Balls, Trash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Part of an eight-story package for use at will or on successful
Sundays in July.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 12 Apollo astronauts who explored
the moon brought back 842 pounds of lunar rocks and left behind $517
million worth of discarded equipment, from moon buggies to family
photographs.
   Among the items left are the bottom halves of six lunar landing
vehicles, used as launching pads, worth a total of $270 million;
five science laboratories, $125 million; three battery-powered moon
cars, $6 million; television and still camera gear, about $4
million; 12 life support backpacks, $3.6 million, and hammers,
tongs, scoops, drills and other tools, $600,000.
   The cars and other equipment would not be suitable for use on
future missions, NASA says, ``because of structural deterioration
brought on by extreme changes in temperature.''
   Also left were batteries; garbage and human waste disposal bags;
one pullcart; six scales for weighing lunar samples; 12 pairs of
lunar boots; surface maps; compasses, and conveyor belts for
hoisting samples into the Lunar Module.
   There are six American flags, a plaque and figurine commemorating
14 dead American and Russian spacemen; a falcon feather from the Air
Force Academy, the thumbprints of moonwalker Jim Irwin's family on
silver medallions, a photograph of moonwalker Charles Duke's family,
including Booster the dog, and two golf balls that Alan Shepard hit
on the moon with a makeshift golf club.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
