<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0886</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said nearly 43,000 coal
miners on wildcat strikes in nine states are violating U.S. labor
law and ordered them not to engage in any strike-related activities.
   U.S. District Judge Dennis Knapp said Tuesday the walkout by
United Mine Workers members violated National Labor Relations Act
guidelines against secondary boycotts. The walkout began June 12 in
support of 1,900 UMW members who have been on strike against The
Pittston Coal Group since April 5.
   Knapp issued a temporary injunction at the request of the
National Labor Relations Board.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Line Pilots Association has asked
federal mediators to intervene in talks with strikebound Eastern
Airlines, a request that could complicate the troubled carrier's
plans to reorganize.
   The union made the request Tuesday of the National Mediation
Board even as it continued negotiations with Eastern in talks
ordered by the bankruptcy judge overseeing the airline, which filed
for court protection from its creditors after its Machinists union
struck in March.
   Mediation Board spokesman David Bushnell said he believed a
mediation request involving a company in bankruptcy proceedings was
unprecedented and could not say what it would mean for Eastern's bid
to abrogate the pilots' contract.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banking regulators have threatened to raise
reserve requirements for major U.S. banks with loans to developing
countries unless there is progress soon on Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady's plan for reducing Third World debt.
   The plan calls for commercial banks to forgive large amounts of
their loans to developing nations, but it has run into stiff
opposition from the banks in an early test over loans to Mexico.
   William Taylor, director of banking supervision and regulation
for the Federal Reserve, issued the warning Tuesday at a House
Banking subcommittee hearing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission denied a
request to delay a new pricing scheme scheduled to go into effect
July 1 for the nation's largest long-distance company, AT&amp;T.
   Competitors had requested a delay in June, saying a price-cap
regulatory scheme for American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. would hurt
them and the public.
   But the FCC, in a decision reached Friday and made public
Tuesday, said the companies failed to provide adequate reasons for a
stay and that the public would benefit from the new pricing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision is near on whether to extend steel
import curbs with 29 countries, according to government and industry
officials.
   The five-year curbs expire Sept. 30.
   Lawmakers on both sides of the issue expected President Bush to
issue a decision, possibly by the end of the week, that seeks to
appease both sides in the steel import barrier dispute.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has ignored a veto threat and passed
legislation to pay more than $900 million to farmers suffering
losses from drought and other weather disasters.
   The assistance legislation, approved Tuesday on a voice vote and
sent to the Senate, is aimed primarily at winter wheat growers in
Kansas, Oklahoma, Texas, Nebraska and other states. It also would
provide payments to some livestock producers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The junk bond market, already troubled by the
prospect of an economic slowdown, could suffer a heavy blow if
Congress adopts legislation forcing savings and loans to sell their
holdings of the high-risk, high-yield securities, economists say.
   Nevertheless, members of Congress upset about the wave of
corporate takeovers and leveraged buyouts are determined to push
thrifts out of the lucrative, but speculative, investment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European leaders have made a deal to take
the first steps toward economic and monetary union, but Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain fended off moves for a single
currency and one central bank.
   Leaders of the 12-nation European Economic Community on Tuesday
fell far short of embracing sweeping proposals that would lead to
tight economic integration of the trading bloc.
   Mrs. Thatcher was pitted against French President Francois
Mitterrand and West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who wanted a
quick monetary marriage.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s stock jumped in response to a report
that a group led by Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass had acquired up
to 3 percent of the company, which owns United Airlines.
   Bass spokeswoman Susan Hawkins declined Tuesday to comment on the
report in USA Today, and UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins said the company
would not comment on the stock activity.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading Tuesday, UAL rose $6.75 to
$146 a share.
</TEXT>
