<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Books-Bankruptcy Bjt   06-28 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Books-Bankruptcy, Bjt,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishers Say Bankruptcy Case Threatens Their Livelihood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-five book publishers nationwide
say they are being squeezed financially and half may be forced out
of business because millions of dollars worth of their books have
been tied up in a bankruptcy dispute.
   The complicated case in federal bankruptcy court here involves
the small publishing houses, a Bridgeport distributor that has
failed to repay $3 million in bank loans, the Hartford bank that
loaned the money and a New York book sales organization.
   In order to collect on the loans, the Connecticut Bank and Trust
Co. has threatened to sell all the publishers' inventory held at the
distributor's warehouse.
   The bank and distributor believe receipts generated by the sale
of the books belong to the distributor. The publishers disagree.
   ``CBT may or may not win their argument that it has some right to
the publishers' books, but knows that it can bring the publishers to
their knees in the meantime because we have to have our inventory to
survive,'' said Rollin Riggs, president of one of the affected
companies, Mustang Publishing of New Haven.
   Riggs and representatives of the other publishers, the owner of
the distributorship and a host of attorneys were at U.S. Bankruptcy
Court in Bridgeport on Tuesday. They had hoped to make some progress
in settling the issue, but couldn't even agree on when to return to
court for their next pre-trial hearing.
   As it now stands, a trial might not begin until December, meaning
the books could be held until at least that time.
   The case began March 9 when Key Book Service, the Bridgeport
distributor, filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the Federal
Bankruptcy Act.
   Three weeks later, the publishers' sales group filed for Chapter
11 protection.
   The sales organization, Kampmann &amp; Co. of New York, had been
hired by the publishers to warehouse and ship their books, as well
as collect money for the publishers. It was Kampmann &amp; Co. that
contracted with Key Book in 1987 to distribute the books.
   As part of its reorganization plan, Kampmann &amp; Co. reached an
agreement with a new distributor in Maryland. But when it sought to
move the books from Key Book in May, CBT won a court order putting a
hold on the merchandise. The order prevents the distribution or sale
of about 850,000 volumes worth about $7 each.
   In addition, all proceeds from earlier book sales were put in an
escrow account and book stores stopped payment on their orders, the
book publishers said.
   On Tuesday, CBT offered a settlement that would have required the
publishers to be responsible for repaying about $1.7 million owed by
Key Book, the publishers said. The publishers rejected the offer.
   Tracy A. Saxe, the publishers' attorney, declined to provide
details on the settlement offer. ``Their solutions are
unsatisfactory,'' he said.
   Robert M. Dombroff, CBT's attorney, refused to comment on the
case.
   Riggs, of Mustang Books, said he has about 70,000 books at the
Bridgeport warehouse. He estimated that he has books and other
assets worth more than $200,000 at risk in the case.
   ``This is my salary and profit for six years. This is everything
I've worked for,'' Riggs said.
   Bruce Shaw, the owner of Harvard Common Press in Boston, said he
has more than 75 different titles at the warehouse worth more than
$100,000. He said the books represent about half his assets.
   Unlike Riggs, Shaw said he could continue to publish if the bank
seizes all the books. ``But I will lose everything I have earned in
the past 10 years,'' he said.
   Eric M. Kampmann, president of the sales group, said about half
the 65 publishers would be put out of business if the books are
seized and sold at discount by the bank.
   Harold Levine, owner of Key Book for 40 years, said Tuesday that
he didn't want to harm the publishers and that it was CBT's decision
to obtain a court order blocking distribution of the books.
   Levine also said it was the publishers' fault that their books
were put on hold. He said that if the publishers hadn't attempted to
move the books, CBT wouldn't have acted.
   ``The independent publishers brought this to a head,'' he said.
``It didn't come out of left field. We didn't pick on those guys
because they're small and we want to beat on them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
