<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DrinkingAds     06-28 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drinking Ads,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brewery Will Boost Responsible Drinking Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anheuser-Busch Inc. will add millions of dollars
annually to its advertising programs aimed at promoting responsible
drinking, the chairman and president of the brewery's parent company
announced.
   August A. Busch III of Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc. told of the plan
at the annual meeting Tuesday of the Beer Institute in Washington.
The programs and projects, Busch said, will be coordinated and
administered by the parent company's new Department of Consumer
Awareness and Education.
   ``Whether it be through public education programs, through server
training efforts, through supporting scientific research or through
advocating the strict enforcement of the law, we can leave no doubt
where we stand,'' Busch said.
   Four years ago, Anheuser-Busch introduced the beer industry's
first prime time, paid advertising program to encourage responsible
drinking through its ``Know When to Say When'' commercials.
   Its programs since then have included TIPS, aimed at teaching
those serving alcohol to identify and prevent potential drinking
abuse, and an ``I'm Driving'' project involving designated drivers.
The company is also the major corporate sponsor of Students Against
Driving Drunk (SADD).
   A companion to the advertising, Busch said, will be a ``Good Part
of the Good Life'' campaign portraying beer's role in history, its
place in family life and its contributions to the economy.
</TEXT>
