<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bush-Steel     06-28 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Steel,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Panel Debates Fate Of Steel Trade Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bush administration economic panel has
debated whether to extend steel import barriers as signs pointed to
a compromise decision aimed at mollifying opponents of the
restraints.
   The five-year curbs expire Sept. 30.
   White House officials said that the cabinet-level Economic Policy
Council met privately Tuesday to discuss the controversial trade
program. Among those on the council are Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher, who would oversee the steel trade program, and U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills, whose office would negotiate the
restraints with other nations.
   Administration officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said it was a ``guessing game'' whether a decision by Bush would be
released before the end of the week. The officials said Bush was
anxious to keep a campaign pledge to renew the curbs, but that he
hoped to appease manufacturers and lawmakers who believe the program
has caused steel shortages.
   ``His (Bush's) tendency seems to be to compromise,'' William
Reinsch, a steel trade expert and aide to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa,
said Tuesday. Heinz, co-chairman of the Senate Steel Caucus, has
been pushing for an extension of the import barriers in their
current form.
   The American Iron and Steel Institute, an industry group, said in
a news release that the administration ``is expected to announce its
decision this week.''
   Pressured by Congress, the Reagan administration negotiated
five-year, product-by-product ``voluntary restraint agreements'' in
1984 with 29 nations, including Japan, South Korea, Brazil and the
European Community to limit the flow of steel into the United States.
   Three days before last November's election, Bush pledged to renew
the restraints in some form. But with the steel industry newly
profitable, opponents of the curbs _ led by a coalition of
steel-using U.S. manufacturers concerned about high steel prices _
say they can make a case for ending the program, or at least
narrowing its scope.
   If the program is continued, opponents are hoping it will be for
less than five years, and will allow new exemptions for
manufacturers who claim the program has left them with inadequate
steel supplies.
   ``I suppose I could live with a compromise,'' Sen. Bob Packwood,
R-Ore., a leading opponent of the restraint program, said last week.
   Bush's decision will cap months of lobbying that has included a
steel industry consultant gathering information on a rival group and
planting questions with pro-import quota lawmakers for use during
congressional hearings, according to an American Iron and Steel
Institute memorandum obtained by The Associated Press.
   The May 25 memorandum described the work of the public relations
firm Oglivy &amp; Mather, which has been lobbying on behalf of extending
the import restraints.
   The memorandum said the firm ``planted'' questions for House and
Senate committee members to ask administration trade officials, and
``gathered information on our opponents,'' namely a coalition of
U.S. manufacturers opposed to continuing the curbs.
   Reinsch, Heinz's aide, said he saw nothing wrong with the firm
offering questions to members. ``We take questions from all
sources,'' he said. ``We won't always use them, but it's the
quickest, simplest way to get the lobbyists' perspective.''
   The firm said it gathered information on the manufacturers group
simply to find out who its members were and how much steel the group
purchased.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
