<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-28 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drifts Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar drifted higher in quiet European
trading today, supported by a weak yen but lacking a clear sense of
direction.
   Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar had seemed to gain
momentum on the widening political crisis of Japanese Prime Minister
Sousuke Uno and the weakness of the yen.
   They said the currency may have lost some steam after unconfirmed
reports of intervention by the Bank of Japan early today. Statements
by the Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita indicating the Group of
Seven industrialized countries wanted a lower dollar also slowed the
U.S. unit, they said.
   ``The market hasn't really sorted its ideas out yet,'' one trader
said. ``The dollar is really drifting without turning into a clear
direction.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 143.55, up from Tuesday's closing 141.23 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 143.10 yen.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.5585 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5640 late Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.9677 West German marks, up from 1.9550; 1.6930
Swiss francs, up from 1.6845; 6.6755 French francs, up from 6.6335;
2.2034 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2010; 1,422.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,408.50; and 1.1950 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19395.
   Gold opened in London at $373.90 a troy ounce, lower than
Tuesday's closing of $376.75. At midmorning, the city's bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $373.75.
   In Zurich, gold was trading at $373.50 a troy ounce, lower than
late Tuesday's $375.75.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.02 to close at $374.09.
   Silver bullion was selling on the London market at $5.30 a troy
ounce, down from late Tuesday's $5.33.
</TEXT>
