<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-28 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo, Dollar Up Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
today and the U.S. dollar climbed sharply against the Japanese yen
in trading affected by new worries over Japan's political stability,
traders said.
   The dollar closed at 143.55 yen, up 2.32 yen from Tuesday's close
of 141.23 yen. It opened at 141.80 yen and fluctuated between 141.80
yen and 143.75 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues fell 223.61
points, or 0.67 percent, closing at 33,245.60. The market's main
barometer lost 156.61 points Tuesday.
   ``During the morning, there was strong yen selling because of the
Uno scandal. The selling really took hold in the afternoon,'' said a
dealer at Daiwa Bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Rumors spread through the market this morning that new Prime
Minister Sousuke Uno might resign following allegations he had paid
three women for sexual liaisons in past years. Uno denied any
intention to resign.
   Uno's ruling Liberal Democratic Party also was shaken Sunday by a
defeat in an upper house by-election in Niigata prefecture. The
recent developments have raised concern about the conservative
party's prospects in elections next month for half the seats in the
upper house.
   The Daiwa dealer said the Bank of Japan sold $500 million to $600
million during the day in efforts to check the U.S. currency's rise.
But the intervention was absorbed as the dollar was rising, so there
was little impact, he added.
   On the stock exchange, Daiwa Bank's Kenji Ishizuka said the
plunge resulted from political concerns and the yen's fall.
   ``Seventy percent (of the fall) stems from politicians' inability
to resolve their problems,'' he said.
   Ishizuka said shares such as high-speed linear-motor car related
issues that are not affected by the exchange rate and interest rates
received particular attention from investors.
   Volume traded in the first section totaled 600 million shares, up
from Monday's 500 million shares.
</TEXT>
