<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed Following Strong Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade following a strong
rally in the previous session fueled by talk of Soviet purchases of
U.S. grain.
   The corn market advanced this morning on follow-through buying
but wheat and soybean prices were narrowly mixed in subdued trading.
   The Agriculture Department announced after Tuesday's close that
the Soviet Union had bought 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
market prices, partially confirming market rumors.
   And exporters reported this morning that Mexico had bought nearly
140,000 metric tons of U.S. corn overnight.
   But most of the excitement about export business seemed to have
faded today and traders were again focusing on crop weather,
including the rain that continues to delay winter wheat harvesting
in the Southeast and forecasts for drier conditions in the thirsty
western Corn Belt.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1} cents higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $4.12 a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 2} cents higher with July at $2.65 a bushel; oats were \
cent to 1 cent higher with July at $1.53} a bushel; soybeans were 1{
cents lower to 1} cents higher with July at $7.37 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower to .10 cent higher with August at
70.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .07 cent lower
with August at 81.20 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .47 cent
lower with July at 48.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
unchanged to .20 cent lower with July at 34.55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Tuesday.
