<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru f0021 06-28 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders End to Miners' Strike; More Violence Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with picket line violence. No pickup; Also
moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal trucks were ambushed in Virginia
and West Virginia and striking miners clogged roads used by coal
haulers today, one day after a judge ordered an end to wildcat
strikes by 43,000 miners in nine states.
   The United Mine Workers said it would encourage the strikers to
comply with the federal judge's order, but miners have ignored
similar orders in the past.
   There were no immediate reports of strikers heeding the order.
But most began their traditional, two-week summer vacations this
week.
   Four coal trucks were peppered with gunfire this morning in West
Virginia and Virginia, and another was shot Tuesday, police said. No
injuries were reported and no arrests were made. Some shots were
fired from the hills.
   A truck was hit with steel balls fired from a slingshot this
morning, State Police said. Rocks were thrown at coal trucks
Tuesday, breaking windshields and injuring a mining superintendent
in the eye near Boomer, authorities said.
   Shots were fired at coal trucks and on picket lines Thursday and
Friday for the first time since the wildcat strikes began June 12.
No one was seriously injured.
   In Virginia, UMW members from six states continued to create
traffic jams on coal hauling roads today despite a federal judge's
threat of daily fines of $120,000.
   Hundreds of cars and trucks paraded slowly on a narrow road
linking Pittston Coal Group's main processing plant with supply
mines, said State Police spokesman Charlie Vaughan.
   U.S. District Judge Dennis Knapp ruled Tuesday the wildcat
strikes in nine states violate U.S. law against secondary strikes.
The strikes are in support of 1,900 UMW members who have been on
strike against Pittston Coal Group since April 5.
   Knapp issued the temporary injunction at the request of the
National Labor Relations Board. He said union officials must report
to the NLRB within 10 days on what steps they have taken to meet the
court order.
   Union President Richard Trumka said union officials did not
believe an injunction was warranted.
   ``These work stoppages are not sanctioned by the union and the
international has requested the affected members to return to
work,'' he said in a statement.
   ``We will take the necessary steps to comply with the court's
order as we review the next legal steps.''
   As many as 46,000 miners in Missouri, West Virginia, Alabama,
Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Tennessee and
Virginia have been off the job. Missouri's miners went back to work
on Monday.
   Back-to-work orders have been issued in at least four states but
largely have been ignored.
   Knapp ordered the union to stop any activities that might cause
miners to continue wildcat strikes.
   In Ohio, union officials representing 850 coal miners at two
Southern Ohio Coal mines said the miners would ignore the judge's
order.
   ``These men ain't going back,'' said George Thacker, president of
UMW Local 1890 in Langsville. ``We got to take a stand sometime. It
might as well be now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890628-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Japan-FaxBoom Adv02   06-28 0956</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Fax Boom, Adv 02,0987</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Faxes Duplicating Japanese Electronics Success Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During protests in Beijing for democracy, Chinese
students in California demonstrated the growing power of the humble
fax machine by using it to bypass censorship and send information
into China.
   The machines were made, naturally, in Japan.
   Faxes, once pricey, snail-paced curiosities, have become a basic
necessity in offices around the world _ and a source of profits for
Japanese electronics companies.
   Although fax machines were invented in the West, it was Japanese
companies that perfected and popularized them in a repeat of their
success with a host of other products originally developed overseas.
   More than 20 Japanese companies now produce almost all the
world's facsimile machines, a market estimated at $3.5 billion a
year. U.S. firms that once made them have become mere middlemen,
putting their name on equipment manufactured in Japan.
   ``American companies don't seem interested in making faxes
themselves,'' said Toshikasu Hori of Matsushita Graphic
Communications, maker of Panasonic faxes. ``They're more interested
in buying Japanese-made machines to sell under their own brand
names.''
   Japan's domination of the market reportedly spared faxes from
inclusion this spring in a list of Japanese products being
considered by Washington for punitive tariffs in response to alleged
restrictive trading practices in Japan. The reason: tariffs would
hurt American consumers without benefiting any American producers.
   With the world's market open to them, Japanese fax makers are
waging a fierce battle among themselves for rapidly increasing sales.
   The battle illustrates the way Japanese companies have come to
dominate markets in the past for such products as transistor radios
and videotape recorders.
   It may look like an orchestrated push by Japan Inc. when Japanese
companies enter an overseas market with price-slashing, heavy
advertising and a flurry of product introductions. But underneath
there is cutthroat competition among Japanese firms for market share
and razor-thin initial profits.
   The competition has brought down prices and speeded the
introduction of sophisticated features into lower-priced models,
says Satoshi Aoki of Ricoh Co., which shares the market lead with
Matsushita.
   Ten years ago, fax machines made in the United States took up to
six minutes to transmit a page. Now technological advances,
particularly in semiconductor image sensors, digitization and
microprocessors _ the ``brains'' of the machines _ have reduced
transmission time to as little as three seconds and the price for
slower basic models to as low as $500.
   At those prices, a fax message often costs less than a letter,
even to another country, and much less than overnight delivery
service.
   ``We've virtually stopped sending letters, and use the fax
instead,'' says Nobue Hoshi, a secretary at a radio production
company. ``It's cheaper and much faster than a letter.''
   Hori says Japan's lead in image sensor technology so far has kept
out competition from Asia's newly industrialized economies, South
Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong and Singapore.
   ``But we've had many Korean and Taiwanese visiting Matsushita in
the past year studying our production process,'' he said.
   Analysts expect one and possibly both countries to enter the
market later this year with low-priced models, in a repeat of
patterns followed in other industries once dominated by Japan.
   That would intensify competition in the fastest-growing market
segment, moderate-priced machines for smaller businesses.
   About 22 percent of Japan's 5.7 million small businesses and
stores with less than 10 employees now have faxes, and the rate is
expected to rocket to about 60 percent in three years, Hori says.
   Japan is expected to produce 4.2 million fax machines this year,
up 23 percent from last year. Of that, about 1.2 million will be
sold in Japan, and a similar amount in both North America and
Europe, according to government forecasts.
   The fax caught on quickly in this country partly because the
complexity of the Japanese writing system makes it difficult to use
Japanese in sending a message by telex or computer.
   Already, Japanese can use coin-operated fax machines at the
neighborhood convenience store to order home-delivery noodles or
pizza, send a comment to a TV panel discussion show, request prayers
from a shrine for success in school entrance exams, or obtain a
detailed map of any part of Japan.
   In Osaka, the Sakura Taxi Co. offers fax-equipped taxis for those
who don't want to be out of touch with their offices. Coin faxes
also are available in some train stations, tour buses, boats and
Japan Airlines flights.
   Few Japanese homes are fax-equipped, Hori said. ``There are still
too few uses for a home fax,'' he said. ``Not enough other people
have them yet to make them worthwhile. It's still easier just to use
the telephone.''
   But that will change over the next five years, the Matsushita
executive said.
   New models aimed at household use include a combination fax and
answering machine that can recognize whether a human voice or
another fax is on the other end of the phone line and respond
accordingly.
   Some foreign businesses are using the Japanese product to
increase their sales in Japan, bypassing traditional distributors.
   ``I couldn't live without it,'' says Paul MacLardy, owner of
Arise Imports, a Washington, D.C.-based fashion and antique exporter.
   ``It's amazing how many small businesses have faxes in Japan. We
get a new piece of merchandise in and fax out a letter to about 20
shops. Then the next day we generally get a fax back saying whether
they want it,'' he says.
   While fax owners in the United States complain about a stream of
``junk faxes,'' or unsolicited advertising messages, Japanese
secretaries are reporting ``obscene faxes,'' often dirty drawings,
arriving on their office fax machines.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, July 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
