<HEAD>Dollar Stronger in Europe, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar strengthened against major European
currencies Wednesday, largely due to an overnight fall in the
Japanese yen. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the yen was driven down on
speculation that Japanese Prime Minister Sousuke Uno might be forced
to resign because of a sex scandal, renewing political uncertainty.
   In April, Uno's predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, anounced his
resignation in the wake of a financial scandal involving cabinet
ministers, officials and businessmen.
   London financial markets were quiet because of a one-day rail and
subway strike that kept some dealers and investors away from their
offices.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 143.55 yen, up from 141.23. In
London late Wednesday the dollar traded lower at 142.65.
   One British pound cost $1.5613 dollars in London late Wednesday,
cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.5640.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday: 1.9630
West German marks, up from 1.9550; 1.6870 Swiss francs, up from
1.6845; 6.6645 French francs, up from 6.6335; 2.2125 Dutch guilders,
up from 2.2010; 1,421.50 Italian lire, up from 1,408.50; and 1.1950
Canadian dollars, up from 1.19395.
   Gold bullion prices dropped by as much as $2 an ounce as the
dollar strengthened.
   The late gold price in London was a bid at $375.25 a troy ounce,
down from $376.75 late Tuesday. The late Zurich bid price was
$373.75 an ounce, down from $375.75.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $373.55 an ounce, down from
$373.85.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.30 a troy ounce,
down from $5.33.
</TEXT>
