<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-TWAAppeal     06-28 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-TWA Appeal,0346</SECOND>
<UNK>Appeals Court Upholds Ruling For TWA</UNK>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court panel ruled Wednesday
that Trans World Airlines Inc. had not bargained in bad faith to
precipitate and prolong a strike by flight attendants in 1986.
   Members of the Independent Federation of Flight Attendants went
on strike March 17, 1986 after Carl Icahn, who had taken control of
TWA, bargained unsuccessfully for cost-saving concessions from the
union. After a federal mediator could not resolve differences, Icahn
cut flight attendants' wages by 22 percent, increased working hours
and changed rules.
   TWA hired 2,700 new flight attendants to replace strikers. About
1,300 attendants resigned from the union and continued to work. On
May 17, 1986, the union offered unconditionally to return to work
without a contract.
   The union later went to court, accusing TWA of bargaining in bad
faith and seeking reinstatement to jobs lost in the strike and back
pay at pre-strike rates.
   U.S. District Court Judge Howard Sachs granted TWA's motion to
dismiss the union's claim and his decision was upheld by a
three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. In his
ruling, Sachs chastised both sides for sometimes angry and abrasive
negotiations, but said TWA's actions were legal responses to
economic conditions.
   ``I cannot conclude from the evidence presented that TWA's
bargaining was in bad faith,'' Sachs said in a 78-page ruling.
   Sachs said the law permits an aggressive union to bargain for
benefits that will increase an employer's costs, and that an
aggressive employer can lawfully bargain for reduction in total
expenses of a group thought to be considerably overpaid and much
less productive than is feasible.
   Sachs made reference to allegedly sexist remarks made by Icahn,
saying they were made when he ``was engaged in debating and
apparently became angry or lacked the sophistication to realize he
was likely to antagonize rather than convince.''
   ``There has been no persuasive showing that sex stereotyping
governed or influenced Icahn's economic demands _ only his
rationalizations,'' Sachs said.
</TEXT>
