<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-28 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Boosts Corn, Wheat Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most corn and wheat futures prices closed
moderately higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in
reaction to detrimental crop-weather forecasts.
   Oat futures retreated and soybeans were mixed.
   The outlook is for hot, dry weather this weekend in the Midwest,
especially in the western section, where corn and soybean crops are
still badly in need of rain.
   The same forecasts gave some support to the soybean market but
the weather-related buying was offset by technically inspired
selling, analysts said.
   News that protesting Brazilian soybean producers may temporarily
resume sales to processors as part of a government-requsted 10-day
``cooling-off period'' prompted further selling of soybeans,
especially for near-term delivery.
   But rain is expected to continue in the southern Mississippi
Valley, where soggy field conditions have brought harvesting of soft
red winter wheat to a standstill.
   ``The wheat is not coming to market, it's not going out for
export, it's not going to mills and they are starting to have some
loss-of-quality problems,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain-market
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   At the close of trading, wheat was { cent lower to 4} cents
higher with the contract for delivery in July at $4.12 a bushel;
corn was 1} cents to 3{ cents higher with July at $2.64{ a bushel;
oats were 2 cents to 3 cents lower with July at $1.50{ a bushel;
soybeans were 11 cents lower to 1{ cents higher with July at $7.27{
a bushel.
</TEXT>
