<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GeneralMills     06-28 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-General Mills,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Mills Profit Cut by Loss from Discontinued Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Inc. on Wednesday reported a 35
percent drop in fourth quarter profit due to a loss from
discontinued operations.
   The maker of cereals and other packaged foods also said its
after-tax earnings in the year ended May 28 rose 46 percent.
   For the final quarter of the company's 1989 financial year,
income came to $35.6 million, or 45 cents a share, down from $54.9
million, or 65 cents a share, in the corresponding 1988 quarter.
   The profit deterioration reflected a $22.1 million loss from
discontinued operations.
   Sales came to $1.44 billion in the fourth quarter, up from $1.25
billion a year year earlier.
   Earnings for all of 1989 amounted to $414.3 million, or $5.06 a
share, compared to 1988's $283.1 million, or $3.25 a share. Sales
totaled $5.62 billion in 1989 vs. $4.98 billion in 1988.
   The 1989 earnings included a net gain of $169 million from the
divestiture of operations, including Eddie Bauer, Talbots, York's,
Vroman's, which was partially offset by a loss of $70 million
related to an accounting change.
   Chairman Bruce Atwater said the annual sales and earnings gains
reflected aggressive internal growth programs throughout the company.
   General Mills' cereals, Red Lobster seafood restaurants and The
Olive Garden Italian restaurants reported strong growth, with an 11
percent unit volume gain in cereals, excellent sales gains in
established restaurants, and the addition of 100 new restaurants, he
said.
   Restaurants led the company's operating performance with gains in
sales and operating profits of 24 percent and 23 percent,
respectively.
   Atwater said the fiscal 1990 outlook in each of the company's key
businesses is promising, with expected strong food volume gains, the
addition of 90 new restaurants planned and expected benefits from
increased operating efficiency.
   General Mills, based in Minneapolis, makes cereals including
Cheerios, Wheaties and Lucky Charms. Among its other packaged foods
are Hamburger Helper, Betty Crocker and Bisquick baking mixes.
</TEXT>
