<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Drop from Highs to Close Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended mixed Wednesday on the London
Stock Exchange, after tumbling sharply from strong early gains.
   The market got off to a brisk start as enthusiasm spilled over
from Tuesday's news of a narrower-than-expected British trade
deficit in May.
   But trading volume dried up in the afternoon, as many traders and
fund managers tried to make their way home amid a strike by public
transportation workers. The stock exchange closed at 4 p.m. local
time, one hour earlier than normal, because of the strike.
   At the close of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 3.0 points, or 0.1 percent, at 2,209.4. The
index surged as much as 19.2 points in early trading but then
slumped to show a loss of 0.2 point in early afternoon.
   Of the top 100 shares, there were 49 declining issues and 44
gainers. Seven of the top stocks were unchanged on the day.
   Volume declined to 446.2 million shares from Tuesday's 498.2
million.
   Despite the day's sluggish performance, traders said many
participants remained optimistic about the market following the
British trade report and the subsequent recovery in the pound.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 2.7 points at 1,832.4
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 2.06 points
to close at 1,251.62.
</TEXT>
