<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-28 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Tumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices tumbled in moderate trading
Wednesday as investors took profits from what analysts said was an
overpriced market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 45
cents to finish at $20.03 cents per barrel. The August contract had
risen 77 cents over the previous two sessions.
   Contracts for later delivery of West Texas Intermediate posted
smaller decreases.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the July
contract for unleaded gasoline plunged 2.53 cents to 61.15 cents a
gallon. Heating oil for July skidded 1.22 cents to 49.31 cents a
gallon. Product prices for delivery after July also eased.
   Analysts attributed Wednesday's declines to a temporary
correction after recent steep gains.
   ``People...have been skeptical of the recent rise so they sold it
out today taking profits,'' said John Hill, energy broker with
Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Paving the way for Wednesday's declines was an industry report
showing crude oil supplies rose last week, some traders said.
   The American Petroleum Institute reported that crude oil supplies
rose 2.2 million barrels from the previous week to 342.4 million
barrels. Heating oil stocks also rose by more than 1 million barrels
to 98.8 million.
   Although the API report showed a 1.3 million-barrel decline in
gasoline stocks to 219.3 million, analysts said prices were
continuing a correction from May's sharp rise following the Alaska
oil spill and reports of tight supplies due to new octane
requirements.
   Crude oil prices for August had risen $1.17 a barrel since last
Wednesday, the day after the July contract expired, surprising many
analysts. Several factors contributed to the rise, including a
report that Kuwait was lowering its oil production closer to the
level desired by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   Kuwait previously had rejected its OPEC-imposed production
ceiling and set its own quota.
   Also driving prices higher this week were reports that put OPEC
output last month at below 20 million barrels a day, down from
previous estimates in excess of 20.5 million barrels. OPEC's
self-imposed quota is 19.5 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
