<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-28 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Rise On Hopes For Price-Support Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices posted solid gains Wednesday on slim hopes
for an international compromise to avert a collapse of the market's
26-year-old price-support machinery.
   ``The market feels that producers and consumers are working to
pull the proverbial rabbit out of the hat,'' said Arthur Stevenson,
a coffee-market analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New
York.
   On other markets, gasoline futures plunged; platinum futures fell
sharply; corn and wheat futures advanced; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Green, unroasted coffee settled .35 cent to 3.2 cents higher on
New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange with the contract for
delivery in July at $1.1438 a pound.
   The rally represented a significant rebound from the 11-month-low
of $1.11 a pound reached Monday, when it appeared the International
Coffee Organization was headed for the junk heap.
   The ICO, formed in 1963, is composed of 74 major coffee producing
and consuming countries. It tries to stabilize coffee prices by
limiting sales of green coffee beans by the producers to the
consumers.
   The group's current 6-year agreement expires on Sept. 30 and
members have been unable to agree on a new pact.
   The catalyst for Monday's collapse was Colombia's stated
intention to move for the abolition of all export quotas unless the
organization's members approve one of two proposals for a new
agreement at their scheduled meeting in London on Monday. Analysts
said neither proposal appeared to have enough support to succeed.
   But on Wednesday, the eve of a scheduled meeting of the ICO's
executive board, rumors flew that Colombia was seeking to postpone
the crucial vote while seeking a compromise with Brazil, the world's
largest coffee producer. Colombia is the second-largest producer.
   The key issues in the debate include demands by consumer nations
for more shipments of mild arabica coffees, the type most in demand
in North America and Europe, and for tighter controls on discount
sales of coffee to non-ICO members.
   Some unleaded gasoline futures plunged the permitted
2-cents-a-gallon limit on the New York Mercantile Exchange following
the latest weekly American Petroleum Institute report, which showed
a 1.3 percent increase in refinery activity.
   But the API report also showed a 1.3-million barrel drop in U.S.
gasoline supplies last week, and many analysts said the market's
collapse was less a reaction to the report than a technical
correction following substantial gains in six of the previous seven
sessions.
   Crude oil and heating oil futures also ended lower.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 27 cents to 45 cents lower
with August at $20.03 a barrel; heating oil was 1.22 cents to 1.57
cents lower with July at 49.31 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
1.56 cents to 2.53 cents lower with July, which has no daily price
limit, at 61.15 cents a gallon.
   Platinum futures plummeted in a selloff sparked by early Japanese
selling in the wake of the dollar's sharp rise against the Japanese
yen. Gold and silver posted only slight losses.
   Platinum settled $10.80 to $11 lower on the New York Merc with
July at $503.60 a troy ounce. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold
settled 10 cents to 60 cents lower with August at $379.20 an ounce;
silver was 2.4 cents to 2.5 cents lower with July at $5.285 an ounce.
   Most corn and wheat futures posted moderate gains on the Chicago
Board of Trade, partly in reaction to forecasts for weather
detrimental to those crops.
   Wheat settled \ cent lower to 4} cents higher with July at $4.12\
a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 3{ cents higher with July at $2.64} a
bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3 cents lower with July at $1.50{ a
bushel; soybeans were 10} cents lower to 1{ cents higher with July
at $7.27} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures ended mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in light trading ahead of Friday's quarterly hogs-and-pigs
inventory from the Agriculture Department.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .20 cent higher with August at
70.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .18 cent lower
with August at 81.07 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to
.20 cent higher with July at 49.10 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent to 1.30 cents higher with July at 35.35 cents
a pound.

</TEXT>
