<FIRST>r f BC-AtlantisBid     06-28 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Atlantis Bid,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clothing Company Owners Bid on Bankrupt Casino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A last-minute $70 million bid for Elsinore's
Atlantis Casino Hotel in Atlantic City was filed Tuesday in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court here by an Israeli industrialist family, topping by
$7 million a bid by New York developer Donald Trump.
   Joseph, Ralph and Avi Nakash, best known as owners of Jordache
Enterprises, a New York-based jeans and clothing manufacturer, filed
the bid with U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rosemary Gambardella. The judge
set a hearing Wednesday to consider the offer.
   The new bid comes about a week after Ms. Gambardella issued a
10-day restraining order to temporarily block Trump's $63 million
purchase agreement with hotel officials.
   Creditors hold a $6.5 million mortgage on three Atlantis parking
lots. They requested the judge's order to prevent the state Casino
Control Commission, a state-appointed conservator and Elsinor Shore
Associates, owners of the property, from transferring the property
to Trump.
   The judge had scheduled a hearing for Thursday to consider
whether to extend the restraining order.
   The Nakash brothers' bid could be attractive to state gaming
regulators, and not only because it is higher. Many casino
regulators, including the Atlantis' state-appointed conservators,
have expressed concern about allowing more of Atlantic City's casino
and hotel industry to be owned by Trump.
   Trump has said he would close the casino and convert it into a
luxury hotel.
   Trump owns two Atlantic City casinos and has a third under
construction. If he buys the Atlantis, it would give him control of
34 percent of Atlantic City's casino hotel rooms, 31 percent of
casino floor space and revenue, and 48 percent of casino meeting and
exhibition space, according to state statistics.
   New Jersey gaming regulators have approved Trump's bid, and his
lawyer has said the closing on the sale is set for July 7, pending
the outcome of court action.
   In April, the Atlantis became the first New Jersey casino to fail
to win approval of its regular license renewal since legal casino
gambling began in Atlantic City in 1978. The state ordered the
casino to shut last month, ruling that the gaming hall's financial
situation was too marginal to allow it to continue operations.
   Nakash, who lives in Manhattan, said he and his brothers own
several hotels, including the Guest Quarters in Houston and two
hotels in Israel. The family also owns an American shipping line
that operates tankers and bulk carriers under the Liberian and
Panamanian flags.
</TEXT>
