<FIRST>r f AM-CatastrophicIllness 1stLd-Writethru f0271 06-28 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Illness, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0271,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Seek Delay of Catastrophic Illness Protections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after penultimate graf pvs `House Ways ...'
with White House comment. Picks up last graf pvs `Proponents argue ...'.
Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of House Republicans introduced
legislation Wednesday to delay implementation of major provisions of
Medicare's new catastrophic illness protections, including a
controversial income tax surcharge.
   Rep. Harris Fawell, R-Ill., who instigated the legislation,
acknowledged an uphill fight in getting the measure considered by
the full House. However, the Ways and Means Committee must send the
measure to the floor if a majority of House members _ 218 _ sign a
petition demanding such action.
   The Fawell bill, which has 25 sponsors, is identical to a measure
by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., that failed to pass the Senate by one
vote.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates that a little under 40
percent of the 33 million Americans eligible for Medicare have
enough income to subject them to the surtax, and that only 5.6
percent are financially well off to be liable for the maximum tax.
   For about 60 percent of those eligible for Medicare, the only
additional charge for the expanded catastrophic protection is $4 a
month.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, has
scheduled hearings to consider reducing the surtax, which could be
as much as $800 this year for upper-income people over 65.
   The hearings also will consider whether to make participation in
the catastrophic illness program, and thus payment of the surtax,
voluntary rather than mandatory.
   House Ways and Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., opposes
any changes in the new program, which took effect Jan. 1. President
Bush also opposes any changes.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday that Bush
doesn't want the surtax rolled back, despite estimates that it may
collect $4 billion more than needed.
   ``The program is just starting,'' Fitzwater said. ``We don't know
whether that excess will hold up or not. ... The first year is
probably not the time to tamper with a program of this magnitude
when you don't really have real-world experience.''
   Proponents argue that much of the criticism stems from the fact
that the surtax is being collected in advance to build up a trust
fund from which benefits are to be paid.
</TEXT>
