<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-KansasCitySouthern     06-28 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kansas City Southern,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Reverses $800 Million Award in Antitrust Case Against Railroad
Co.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Wednesday reversed a
lower court ruling that had granted more than $800 million to the
state of South Dakota in a federal antitrust claim against Kansas
City Southern Industries Inc.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said South Dakota had no
standing to assert the federal antitrust action.
   About $600 million of the $844.2 million represented a trebled
jury verdict of $200 million on the antitrust claim. The rest was an
award to South Dakota on claims that Kansas City Southern and its
chief subsidiary, the Kansas City Southern Railway Co., interfered
with a contractual relationship.
   A U.S. District Court jury made the award in Sioux Falls, S.D.,
in April 1988. The jury agreed with the state's claim that the
Kansas City Southern railway had conspired with other railroads to
block a coal slurry pipeline proposed by Energy Transportation
Systems Inc. The railroad company, based in Kansas City, appealed
the award.
   ETSI was created during the early 1970s by a number of
corporations to build a slurry pipeline through which coal could be
transported from mining sites in north-central states to utility
companies in south-central states. The project was begun in response
to the energy crisis at the time.
   Coal slurry is a mixture of roughly half coal and half water.
Consequently, large quantities of water were required to operate the
pipeline.
   South Dakota's contract with ETSI to supply the pipeline with
water would have brought the state $9 million a year in revenue.
   The state's lawsuit claimed that Kansas City Southern and others
violated federal antitrust laws in delaying the 1,400-mile, $3.8
billion pipeline, which would have crossed railroad tracks.
Attorneys for the state produced a document that said Kansas City
Southern was designated to be the lead railroad to fight the project
and the water sale.
   The railroad argued that it opposed the pipeline but that there
was no conspiracy. The company also contended the project was
financially doomed with or without South Dakota water contracts.
   In its opinion, the appeals court said: ``The judgment of the
District Court should be vacated on the grounds that 1. the state of
South Dakota had no standing to bring the antitrust claim and 2. the
evidence fails to show that KCS improperly interfered with the South
Dakota ... district contract through the petitioning activities
occurring after December 1981.''
   Kansas City Southern, in a statement, hailed the decision.
   ``This removes a cloud that has hung over the company and its
business operations since the return of the jury verdict in April
1988,'' said Landon H. Rowland, president and chief executive
officer.
   South Dakota Gov. George Mickelson said he would have to read the
ruling before deciding which of three options the state will pursue.
The state could do nothing, ask the full court of appeals to review
the panel's ruling or apply directly for a hearing before the U.S.
Supreme Court, he said.
   Mickelson said he was extremely disappointed with the ruling. He
said South Dakota intended to use the money from the ETSI water sale
to support water development projects.
   ``We pursued the ETSI damages in an attempt to right a wrong done
to South Dakotans in our development of one of our most valuable
resources, water,'' the governor said in a statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
