<DOCNO> AP890628-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 2151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilSpillsRdp 2ndLd-Writethru f0306 06-28 0995</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0306,1018</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captain of Rhode Island Tanker Spill Charged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Each of ..., to CORRECT maximum fine to $100,000,
sted $200,000; SUBS 6th graf, `Painstaking cleanup ..., to reflect that
most of cleanup of Rhode Island spill is complete; SUBS 11th graf, `In
interviews ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Rhode Island governor meeting
with Bush, saying most shellfish beds would reopen Thursday. Picks up 12th
graf pvs: `At the ...'. Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Greek tanker that
spilled 420,000 gallons of heating oil into Narragansett Bay was
arrested and charged Wednesday with violating the federal Clean
Water Act and Refuse Act.
   The captain, Iakovas Georgudis, 43, surrendered and was charged
promptly in federal court in Providence to ensure that he would
remain in this country, said U.S. Attorney Lincoln Almond.
   Each of the two misdemeanor counts carries up to a year in prison
and $100,000 fine or double the actual damages, which the Coast
Guard has estimated at $1.6 million.
   The Clean Water Act prohibits the negligent discharge of
pollutants; the Refuse Act prohibits unlawfully discharging refuse
into navigable water without a permit.
   In a hearing on a second spill on the Delaware River, the pilot
and captain of an Uruguayan tanker testified that the ship's anchor
was dropped too soon, causing the vessel to run aground and leak
more than 310,000 gallons of oil.
   Painstaking cleanup continued on that spill, while workers using
hand-held skimmers were close to finishing the cleanup of 250,000
gallons of crude spilled when a third tanker collided with a barge
in Texas, soiling a mile-long stretch of Galveston Bay shoreline.
   All three spills occurred within hours of each other over the
weekend.
   In Rhode Island, U.S. Magistrate Jacob Hagopian set bail for
Georgudis at $50,000 and ordered the captain to surrender his
passport and remain on the ship until bail is paid.
   Georgudis also was subpoenaed to appear at a statewide grand jury
Wednesday that is investigating possible violations of state
pollution laws and a statute that requires ships within Narragansett
Bay to have harbor pilots on board, but he did not testify, said
State Attorney General James O'Neil.
   ``His attorney indicated he was going to exercise his privilege''
against self-incrimination, O'Neil said. Georgudis declined to
answer questions as he ran into the courthouse followed by his
attorney, Peter DiBiase.
   In interviews with Coast Guard officials and Rhode Island Gov.
Edward D. DiPrete after the spill, Georgudis admitted he made a
mistake in not taking on a pilot to escort the vessel into the
harbor.
   DiPrete said after meeting with President Bush in Washington late
Tuesday that Bush pledged the federal government would pay all state
cleanup expenses. Officials reported earlier this week, however,
that most of the oil has evaporated.
   The governor said Wednesday most shellfish beds closed in upper
Narragansett Bay after the accident would reopen Thursday. Federal
Food and Drug Administration tests showed no contamination, he said.
   The reopening comes just before the July Fourth weekend,
traditionally the most profitable time of year for shellfishermen.
Further tests would be needed before the southernmost beds could be
reopened, DiPrete said.
   At the Philadelphia hearing into the Delaware River spill, pilot
Robert Anderson said the transit of the 749-foot-long Presidente
Rivera was normal and he started slowing down more than 10 miles
below his destination, the Sun Marketing and Refining Co. refinery
in Marcus Hook, Pa. He said he told the captain to prepare for
anchoring.
   ``As we approached the intersection of Marcus Hook, I suddenly
saw sparks fly, and I said, `Jesus Christ, he didn't drop the
anchor?' I saw that's what had happened,'' Anderson said at the
Coast Guard inquiry.
   ``I was waiting for the jerk (of the anchor) that would yank the
ship. They finally got it stopped and I felt we had hit something on
the bottom. We went through various maneuvers and got the help of
two tugboats. We were able to get off and heave the anchor up.
   ``All of a sudden the ship hit bottom again, and I heard it, and
I knew we were hard and fast. One tugboat captain said he could see
oil coming out. At that point I said to the captain that we had to
notify the Coast Guard,'' he said.
   Speaking through an interpreter, Capt. Raul DiBarrart said he
told a lieutenant to prepare to drop the port anchor about 1:30 a.m.
Saturday, but before he knew it, the anchor had begun to fall.
   Lt. Ricardo Schunk, the second officer on the tanker, said the
ship's windlass, a huge winch used to raise and lower the anchor,
was not engaged as it usually is when dropping anchor. The botswain
responsible for the windlass was not present, he said.
   The hearing was recessed until next Wednesday.
   Hundreds of people have been working since the weekend to clean
up the spilled oil, which took the shape of greasy, sticky blobs,
some as large as beach balls.
   A Coast Guard spokesman said Wednesday that cleanup crews were
making headway sweeping the Delaware River. Cooler weather kept oil
blobs from melting into puddles that would soak into shorelines, but
wind shifts began to move oil to New Jersey riverbanks for the first
time.
   In Texas, only about 40 of the 6,000 barrels of oil that leaked
from the barge in the Houston Ship Channel remained on the water
Wednesday afternoon, U.S. Coast Guard spokesman William Nash said.
   ``It's a slower process now because the larger machines can't be
utilized with the smaller levels (of oil),'' Nash said. ``It's more
of a hands-on operation now.''
   Testimony continued Wednesday in a hearing being held to
determine what caused the spill, which occurred Friday evening when
the Panamanian tanker turned into the barge near the intersection of
the Houston Ship Channel and the Bayport Ship Channel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
