<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Pickens 1stLd-Writethru f0139 06-28 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Pickens, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0139,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koito President Fears Pickens May Be Greeted by Gangsters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UDPATE with start of meeting, hecklers.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Pickens' purchase ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American investor T. Boone Pickens prepared Thursday
to assert his rights as the largest shareholder in Koito
Manufacturing Co. at the Japanese auto lighting manufacturer's
annual shareholders meeting.
   The stockholders meeting began at 10 a.m. with Pickens in
attendance. On several occasions, hecklers disrupted Koito President
Takao Matsuura's opening remarks and his presentation of the
company's annual report.
   In a controversial deal that is challenging the insularity of the
Japanese corporate world, Pickens announced in March that he had
bought 20.2 percent of Koito's stock, making him the company's
largest shareholder, which has close ties to Toyota Motor Corp.
   Koito has refused Pickens' request for a seat on its board of
directors, saying it doubts his assertions that he is long-term
investor with a genuine interest in helping manage the company.
   Pickens planned to present his case at the meeting, held in Tokyo.
   Meanwhile, Matsuura said Wednesday he was worried gangsters might
disrupt the gathering.
   The National Police Agency said 5,358 police are being sent to
shareholders' meetings scheduled Thursday across Japan to deal with
``sokaiya,'' racketeers who regularly disrupt such meetings, trying
to extract payoffs from management to keep silent.
   Koito, like more than 1,300 other firms, is expected to receive
police protection for its meeting, where Japanese media plan heavy
coverage in case of a management showdown with Pickens.
   Pickens _ who has a reputation as a corporate raider in the
United States _ planned a showdown at the meeting at least over the
number if representatives he can bring into the gathering.
   Pickens' purchase of Koito stock sent shock waves through the
Japanese business community, whose tradition is to consult with a
firm before taking a major stake in its stock.
   The Texas oilman has argued that Japanese shareholders should
stand up for their rights, which Japanese critics agree are limited.
Japanese businessmen agree that the interests of shareholders are
often ignored in favor of those of management and employees.
   Although Pickens' arguments for shareholders' rights have gained
some support in leading newspaper editorials, Japanese _ with an eye
to his string of unsuccessful hostile takeover attempts in the
United States _ remain suspicious of his motives.
   He has strongly denied, however, that his intention is greenmail
_ the practice of buying a company's shares to force their
repurchase at a higher price to maintain the company's management
independence.
   Pickens has raised his problems with Koito as a trade issue in
Washington, saying Americans are denied the right to invest freely
in Japan while Japanese can easily purchase American companies.
   It was not known whether sokaiya actually would show up at
Koito's meeting Thursday, but ``it's a big worry,'' said company
president Takao Matsuura in a meeting with reporters Wednesday.
   Japanese companies regularly pay off sokaiya so they won't
disrupt shareholders' meetings, and sometimes hire them to silence
complaints from other shareholders. Although the practice has been
illegal since 1982, securities industry sources say it is still
common, and over the past several years a number of executives of
major companies have been arrested for paying sokaiya.
   Koito officials say they have no ties with sokaiya. Koito is
known as a company that has avoided contact with sokaiya, said a
former securities house executive in charge of dealing with the
racketeers. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Sources close to Koito and securities industry sources say they
don't think Pickens himself has any ties to sokaiya, either.
   Many industry sources are unwilling to comment on the record
about sokaiya because they fear them or their associates. However,
information on sokaiya is well-organized, with newsletters on their
activities circulating among securities houses and businessmen who
have to deal with them.
   Detailed directories and histories of sokaiyas' activities
charting their ties with yakuza _ Japan's organized crime gangs _
are bought by managers to determine how much attention to pay to
pressure from a particular person claiming to be a sokaiya.
   Koito was informed that a number of people registered to attend
its meeting were on a police list of known sokaiya, said a source
close to the company who refused to be further identified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
