<FIRST>r f BC-Electrolux-Regina     06-28 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Electrolux-Regina,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electrolux Bid to Purchase Regina Approved By Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge on Wednesday
approved the Electrolux Corp.'s $70 million bid to purchase one of
its ailing competitors, the Regina Co. Inc.
   After a daylong hearing, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge William Tuohey
agreed to allow the sale of all of the Rahway-based vacuum maker's
assets to CRC Acquisitions, a subsidiary of Marietta, Ga.-based
Electrolux.
   ``It was a day for the court to consider any higher or better
offers, and essentially there were none,'' said Howard S. Greenberg,
an attorney for Regina.
   The decision clears the way for sale of all Regina assets to
Electrolux, including inventory, the company name, land, trademarks
and production plants in Rahway and Long Beach, Miss.
   Electrolux, a privately-held company, lists its annual sales at
about $400 million in 1988. Regina's last fiscal year yielded about
$160 million in sales.
   Attorneys for both companies said a final closing has been
scheduled for Friday.
   Regina, a public corporation, filed for reorganization under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code on April 26. The company's
hopes to survive as an independent competitor were all but dashed
May 4, when Tuohey turned down a $5 million refinancing package
worked out between the company and its two largest creditors, Chase
Manhattan Bank and Philadelphia National Bank.
   The package was contingent upon the banks' ability to combine a
new loan with the company's existing debt, amounting to about $25
million.
   Tuohey turned the plan down, voicing concern for the roughly $36
million in unsecured debt owed to other creditors.
</TEXT>
